iara Bertola, Sylvia Kouvali, Ruth Keshisian, Maroulla Zivanari, Giorgos Orfanos, Pavlos Fotsios, Stelios Lenas, Savvas Siakas, Pierre Dechavanne, Maria Saranti, Michalis Kyriakides, Presviteros Asinou, Presviteros Kalopanayioti, Cyprus Theater Organisation, Department of Antiquities, Kalavasos Municipality, A.B Seahorse Film Productions Ltd, Lumiere Services, ARRI Berlin, Kodak Berlin, Petopia Petshop, Camel Park Mazotos, Paphos Zoo\r\n\r\nSPONSORS\r\nPHC Franchised Restaurants Ltd',NULL),(170,1,'2016-04-04 09:56:53','2017-10-18 11:41:57',75,'RE APHRODITE',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'re-aphrodite',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\nInfo\r\n\r\nRe Aphrodite (est. in 2010 by Chrystalleni Loizidou and Evanthia Tselika) is an independent, not-for-profit, Cyprus-based group of practitioners and researchers focusing on issues of gender, social difference and Cypriot political and social paradoxes through research and educational, curatorial and creative practice. \r\n\r\nWork from the Re Aphrodite Project has appeared at the House of Hadjigeorgakis Kornesios in Nicosia, Cyprus (2013), and at the Nicosia Municipal Arts Centre.\r\n\r\n',NULL),(171,1,'2016-04-04 10:10:22','2017-05-25 16:17:54',76,'ON COLLABORATION',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'on-collaboration',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\n12.03.2013\r\n\r\nPress Release:\r\n\r\nRe Aphrodite would like to invite you to an open conversation on the arts in Cyprus and art in general. The conversation itself will culminate in a contribution to the [fifth issue of the Cyprus Dossier](https://issuu.com/cyprusdossier/docs/cyprusdossier05) on the theme of collaboration, to be launched at the 2013 Venice Biennale as part of the Cypriot-Lithuanian pavilion. An initial idea is that the conversation itself will be transcribed and part of it written up in the journal, with the names of the participants included.\r\n\r\nIssues of collectivity, authorship, participation, consensus, community behaviour, group activity, labour organization and team work are only some of the elements that are used to describe the functions of contemporary, collaborative, project-driven practices. Within such  a framework, working well with other people becomes an important asset. Likewise, breaking through the limitations of the self can assist in strengthening the process, production and development of a project or a concept. This conversation aims to critically reflect on issues of collaboration through open exchange and dialogue while addressing the concerns and ideas of the participants.\r\n\r\nWe would like to propose the following starting points:\r\n\r\nCan we identify present trends within the arts in contrast to the auteur model and can we try out models developed and tested in other fields? If different places can be said to reflect their own forms of collaborative patterns within the arts, then what has been the prevailing pattern in Cyprus?\r\n\r\nHow can local interpretations of what artistic collaboration is highlight, demonstrate and challenge a trend that has prevailed in the art world since the beginning of the 20th century and that exploded as a methodology in the 1960s?\r\n\r\nHow do different forms of collaboration act in creating community and how do they in turn challenge dominant political and social narratives and patterns?  Where does collaboration fit in within the context of ‘the social function’ of the arts (an important question in the last twenty years)?\r\n\r\nCan we speak of an ethics of collaboration beyond managerial prescriptions of good practice and models of team structure? Can we work towards developing a culture of openness in the arts that reflects on broader questions about productivity, social organisation and good governance?\r\n\r\nHow can collaboration challenge notions of nationalism?\r\n\r\nHave new technologies and social media changed the nature of collaboration?\r\n\r\nWhat is the role of open conversation and dialogue within collaborative practices?\r\n\r\nHow far can a participatory, collaborative event such as this go towards reflexively dealing with its own subject matter?',NULL),(172,1,'2016-04-04 10:10:36','2017-05-26 20:17:18',240,'ANDREA BRUNO',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'andrea-bruno',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\nBio\r\n\r\nAndrea Bruno (b. 1931, Italy) graduated from Turin Polytechnic University with a degree in Architecture in 1956.\r\n\r\nHe teaches architectural restoration in the schools of architecture at Milan and Turin Polytechnic Universities. He is also honorary president of the Centre d’Etudes pour la Conservation du Patrimoine Architectural et Urbain at Katholieke Universiteit in Leuven, Belgium and a member of the Royal Academy of Belgium. He has been a UNESCO consultant for the restoration and conservation of artistic and cultural heritage since 1974 with a particular focus on the Middle East. In 2002, he was named advisor for UNESCO’s Cultural Division for Afghanistan. Bruno designed a model site museum at Maa-Palaiokastro in Cyprus, sponsored by the A.G. Leventis Foundation, which was completed in 1989.\r\n\r\n(2013)',NULL),(173,0,'2016-04-04 10:12:27','2016-04-06 15:46:09',77,'ON COLLABORATION - CYD',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'on-collaboration---cyd',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(174,0,'2016-04-04 10:26:57','2016-04-04 10:27:37',96,'BIO',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'bio',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Bio\r\n\r\nAndrea Bruno was born in Torino, Italy in 1931. He graduated from the Polytechnic with a degree in Architecture in 1956. He teaches architectonic restoration at the schools of Architecture at the Milano Polytechnic and the Torino Polytechnic. He is also honorary president of the Centre d’Etudes pour la Conservation du Patrimoine Architectural et Urbain at Katholieke Universiteit in Leuven, Belgium, and is a member of the Académie Royale de Belgique. A UNESCO consultant for the restoration and conservation of artistic and cultural heritage since 1974, he has coordinated various projects in the Middle East. He has focused special attention on early studies on the Bamyan Valley, the Museum of Islamic Art in Ghaznì, and the restoration of the Herat historical sites and the minaret of Jam, also in Afghanistan. In 2002 he was named advisor for UNESCO’s Cultural Division for Afghanistan. Bruno designed a model Site Museum, at Maa-Palaiocastro in Cyprus, sponsored by the A.G. Leventis Foundation, which was completed in 1989.\r\n',NULL),(175,1,'2016-04-04 10:33:59','2017-05-25 16:19:11',77,'BANK OF COMMONS: ALTERNATIVE SOLUTIONS FOR CYPRUS',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'bank-of-commons',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\n13.04.2013\r\n\r\nPress Release:\r\n\r\nRealising the financial gap that currently exists in our country, we are creating a window of opportunity for action, independence and self-organisation. Our aim is to secure basic human needs. The project is open source and open to anyone who would like to take part in its development.\r\n\r\nOver the recent weeks, the concern we all share under the threat of a collapsing economy is indisputable. Our trust in types of authority and decision-making is being challenged. Everywhere people are discussing one thing only: What do we do now?\r\n\r\nWhat tools do we have as a society to find communal and collective solutions to the social, economic and political problems that put us under siege? How do we come to a consensus on all these different ideas? We are looking for practical solutions to practical problems through conversations on many issues: alternative economies, the creation of jobs, new areas of entrepreneurship, local food production and sustainability. We are also looking for answers to questions of democratic representation, consensus building, and decision making, among other things.\r\n\r\nThe aim of this open, casual event on Saturday, April 13 is to bring together existing networks and build new ones so that we can learn from each other and work together for the common good. We can start by finding ways to create jobs through cooperative networks and specialised entrepreneurship.\r\n\r\nWe will use Open Space Technology as a method of self-organisation.\r\nLook it up in advance and get in touch with questions on our Facebook group, the mailing list, or the Facebook event page.\r\n\r\nBank of Commons is open source and open to anyone who would like to take part in its development.\r\n\r\nInstitutional Partners so far: Artos Foundation, Re Aphrodite, Point Centre for Contemporary Art, Politeia, University of Cyprus, University of Nicosia, Utopia Collective.',NULL),(176,1,'2016-04-04 10:45:27','2017-05-25 16:25:57',79,'CYPRUS FILM DAYS',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'cyprus-film-days',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\n19 – 28.04.2013\r\n\r\nPress Release:\r\n\r\n[Cyprus Film Days](https://www.facebook.com/events/432747746811438/) is co-organised by the Ministry of Education and Culture of the Republic of Cyprus and the Rialto Theatre. The 11th edition of the Festival will take place from 19–28 April 2013, with parallel screenings both in Limassol (RIALTO Theatre) and in Nicosia (Zena Palace Cinema, Point Centre for Contemporary Art).\r\n\r\nPoint Centre for Contemporary Art will screen four films from the section *Bang, Bang, Bang! Vendetta Cinema from Around the World*. The four movies are:\r\n\r\n*A Gun for Jennifer* (1997)<br/>\r\ndir. Todd Morris, 85\'<br/>\r\nSaturday 20 April | 00:00 (midnight)\r\n\r\n*The Warrior* (1981)<br/>\r\ndir. Sisworo Gautama Putra, 92\'<br/>\r\nSunday 21 April | 00:00 (midnight)<br/>\r\n\r\n*Fair Game* (1986)<br/>\r\ndir. Mario Andreacchio, 90\'<br/>\r\nFriday 26 April | 00:00 (midnight)<br/>\r\n\r\n*Death Weekend* (1976)<br/>\r\ndir. William Fruet, 87\'<br/>\r\nSaturday 27 April | 00:00 (midnight)<br/>\r\n\r\nCyprus Film Days Festival 2013 will also host an international competition section entitled *Global Images*, showcasing films from Cyprus and across the globe. All films in the competitive section will be selected by the festival’s artistic committee: Adonis Florides (film director/writer), Dr Costas Constandinides (Assistant Professor of Film Studies) and Constantinos Sarkas (Film Journalist). \r\n\r\nShowcasing cinematic excellence has been the mission of Cyprus Film Days since its first screenings in 2003. The festival has now been established as a much anticipated event, aiming at promoting international and Cypriot cinema, supporting and featuring the work of independent filmmakers, showcasing emerging talent and serving as a meeting point for filmmakers from the three continents surrounding the island of Cyprus. Cyprus Film Days encompasses a ten-day programme featuring some of this year’s most talked about films, screened for the first time in Cyprus.',NULL),(177,1,'2016-04-04 10:52:34','2017-05-25 16:27:19',80,'DISPLAYS: AN EXHIBITION AND RESEARCH PROJECT',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'displays',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\n21.05 – 20.08.2013\r\n\r\nPress Release:\r\n\r\nIn collaboration with the Cyprus State Gallery of Contemporary Art and the Cultural Services of the Ministry of Education and Culture, Point proposed and organized the participatory exhibition and research project *Displays*. To investigate the very concept and uses of the traditional archive, Point invited 27 experts to choose an artwork from the State Collection. The chosen artworks were displayed at Point as a non-curated group exhibition and used as springboards for presentations, discussions and creative happenings.\r\n\r\n*Displays* was a participatory project about research and archival access that delved into the [archives](http://dev.o-r-g.com/point/annual-reports/2013/archive) of the Cyprus State Gallery of Contemporary Art. The project\'s main objective was to encourage access, new research and creative engagement with the Cypriot State Collection of Contemporary Art and its archive. To do that, it displaced works from the collection, either from exhibition or storage, and brought them to Point. In so doing, it raised new questions about, and proposed new textual and event-based revisions of, Cypriot art and the ways in which it is contextualised and historicised. \r\n\r\nFurther research into the gallery\'s archives produced a [map](http://point-centre.tumblr.com/) that traces the works of art hanging in public institutions in Cyprus, including the Presidential Palace, Parliament, the Supreme Court, the Ministry of the Exterior, and the Ministry of Education and Culture. A four-volume [catalogue](http://dev.o-r-g.com/point/annual-reports/2013/displays-book) documenting all the works in the State Gallery’s collection was produced by Point. Only one hard copy of the book was printed. It was donated to the State Gallery to be used as a reference work.\r\n\r\nParticipants:\r\n\r\nAndreas Vrahimis<br />\r\nMarina Yerali<br />\r\nTheodoulos Gregoriou<br />\r\nZelia Gregoriou<br />\r\nKonstantina Zanou<br />\r\nGloria Kassianidou<br />\r\nChristina Lambrou<br />\r\nEleni Loizidou<br />\r\nJoanna Louka<br />\r\nCostas Mantzalos<br />\r\nEleni Nikita<br />\r\nAnna Nicolaou<br />\r\nChristodoulos Panayiotou<br />\r\nGeorge Papageorgiou<br />\r\nElena Parpa<br />\r\nDespo Pashia<br />\r\nPolys Peslikas<br />\r\nUrsula Savvopoulou<br />\r\nRita Severi<br />\r\nChara Stephanou<br />\r\nTheopisti Stylianou-Lambert<br />\r\nMarina Schiza<br />\r\nYiannis Toumazis<br />\r\nEvi Tselika<br />\r\nAlkis Hadjiandreou<br />\r\nChristos Hadjichristos<br />\r\nNatalie Heller<br />',NULL),(178,1,'2016-04-04 11:05:20','2017-05-25 15:55:39',63,'BABAK RADBOY ',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'babak-radboy',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\nBio\r\n\r\n[Babak Radboy](http://www.babakradboy.com/) (b. Tehran) has produced fifteen issues of *Bidoun Magazine* and continues to be creative director and chief curator of the Bidoun Library. Besides Bidoun and his personal work, he is a freelance art director, produces music and attends to an eccentric archive of printed matter. He lives in New York City.\r\n\r\n(2013)',NULL),(179,1,'2016-04-04 11:11:57','2017-05-26 20:20:06',248,'PAVEL PYS',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'pavel-pys',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\nBio\r\n\r\nPavel S. Pys holds an MFA in Curating from Goldsmiths College and an MSc in Culture & Society from the London School of Economics & Political Science. \r\nHe is the Exhibitions & Displays Curator at the Henry Moore Institute, Leeds. At the Institute, Pavel has overseen *Robert Filliou: The Institute of Endless Possibilities* (March 2013); *Indifferent Matter: From Object to Sculpture* (July 2013), and solo presentations of Alberto Giacommetti, Sturtevant and Jean Tinguely. He is currently working on *Carol Bove / Carlo Scarpa* (an exhibition produced in collaboration with Museion Bolzano and Museum Dhondt-Dhaenens, Deurle) and a focused display of work by Christine Kozlov. Pavel also frequently contributes to *Frieze*, *Mousse* and *ArtReview*.\r\n\r\nIn 2011, Pavel was the winner of the inaugural [Zabludowicz Collection Curatorial Open](http://www.zabludowiczcollection.com/exhibitions/view/zabludowicz-collection-curatorial-open-we-will-live-we-will-see), and was also one of the three curators in residence at the Fondazione Sandretto Re Rebaudengo, Turin.\r\n\r\n(2013)',NULL),(180,1,'2016-04-04 11:17:57','2016-04-07 15:41:24',250,'FRIEZE REVIEW',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'frieze-review',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(181,1,'2016-04-04 12:07:45','2017-05-25 16:31:07',95,'DISPLAYS: EXHIBITION',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'displays-exhibition',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\nInstallation Views ',NULL),(182,1,'2016-04-04 12:15:23','2017-10-18 12:09:58',90,'DISPLAYS: DISCUSSION',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'displays-discussions',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br/>\r\n21.5 – 20.7.2013\r\n\r\nPress Release:\r\n\r\n[Display 1](https://vimeo.com/163973482): 21 June 2013\r\n\r\nThree researchers (C. Lambrou, C. Zanou and E. Parpa) from the fields of Cypriot Art History and History of Ideas address the ideological, historical and aesthetic dimensions of Cypriot painter Adamantios Diamantis’s painting *Fyteftries* (1932–33). \r\n\r\nThe discussion (in Greek) is the first of a series of scheduled weekly happenings at Point in conjunction with the *Displays* Project.\r\n\r\nDisplay 2: 24 May 2013\r\n\r\nAs part of the exhibition and research project *Displays* Point presents the discussion *Museum purchases: Experiences from current and former members of the Purchase Committee of the State Collection of Contemporary Art* with [Artemis Eleftheriadou](http://dev.o-r-g.com/point/annual-reports/2013/artemis-eleftheriadou), Andre Zivanari, Costas  Mantzalos, [Margarita Paraskevaidou](http://dev.o-r-g.com/point/annual-reports/2013/margarita-paraskevaidou), and [Mikella Psara](http://dev.o-r-g.com/point/annual-reports/2013/mikella-psara).\r\n\r\n[Display 3](https://vimeo.com/170739362): 31 May 2013\r\n\r\n*Ceramic art in Cyprus*, artist talk (in Greek) with [Valentinos Charalambous](http://dev.o-r-g.com/point/annual-reports/2013/valentinos-haralambous) and Marina Schiza\r\n\r\nDisplay 4: 7 June 2013\r\n\r\n*Art and Power* with Theodoulos Gregoriou (visual artist), Despo Pasia (educator, museologist), Chara Stephanou (art theorist/political scientist), Demetris Taliotis (cultural entrepreneur/curator). Moderation: Alkis Hadjiandreou. The discussion will be in Greek.\r\n\r\n[Display 5](https://vimeo.com/167894141): 14 July 2013\r\n\r\n*Dialogues with Antiquity*, discussion (in Greek) with Ursula Savvopoulou.\r\nPolys Peslikas invites Soso Hadjimanoli to talk about the work of Vera Hadjida.\r\n\r\n[Display 6](https://vimeo.com/171654841): 21 July 2013\r\n\r\nRita Severis on the work of Emin Çizenel (in English).\r\n\r\nOther *Displays* events:\r\n\r\n19 July 2013\r\n\r\n*Artists\' Book: Investigating the book as an artistic form*, presentation by Marina Yerali. The presentation will focus on the spectrum of book arts (books that are made or conceived by artists and that are works of art by themselves). Contemporary artists’ books are noteworthy for their many different forms, and perhaps because of this they have an equally large number of precursors and influences. The presentation will be in Greek.\r\n\r\n*Starting point: How does a dance artist respond creatively to a visual artwork?* by Natalie Heller, a response to Andros Kazamias’ painting *Drawing*. This live performance piece won\'t be a response to the physical movement of Kazamias’ painted dancer but an interpretation of the artist’s intent. Reflected in the live moving body is a sense of internal conflict and duality. Heller invites the spectator to consider a dance work as a piece of live visual art.\r\n\r\nWatch the [live performance](https://vimeo.com/167813880). ',NULL),(183,0,'2016-04-04 12:39:21','2016-04-06 20:33:20',150,'DISPLAYS LAPIDARIUM',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'displays-lapidarium',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'The aim of the project is to open up and encourage access to the Stage Collection, with attention to its artistic wealth and the scientific value of its records. The first part of the project is an open, collaborative, research-focused exploration of the Gallery, its library and its archives. Point will provide all possible support for this effort in constant exchange with the State Gallery and its staff. The information will be used to set-up interviews, to document the development of the Gallery and of the Cypriot arts, and invite dialogue around art history, archival issues, questions of arts policy and management, with the intention of giving rise to new scholarly and creative projects. \r\n\r\nThe process will give the project participants the chance to get acquainted with the Gallery and its material. Although we would like this part of the project to extend for a longer period and in collaboration with a greater number of individuals, for this initial round we are only able to provide support to a few. \r\n\r\nTwenty-two people (theorists, historians, practitioners),  invited for their research interests, will choose a work from the collection, will produce a written piece on the work which will become part of an edited volume, and will be encouraged to organise an event with Point (a presentation, a round-table, a participatory event, an educational workshop, or something different) expanding on related themes. \r\n\r\nPoint will open to the public by the beginning of April, while all the above is being organised, and as research material accumulates at the Centre.\r\n\r\nLapidarium \r\nAs art-works are chosen they will be transported to Point, with due security and insurance, where they will accumulate into an exhibition. The shape will be that of a collective, collectively curated, and somewhat irregular exhibition. The works will be selected gradually, at each participant\'s own time up until June, and so later additions will be in conversation with previous ones. The exhibition\'s curatorial direction will be that of a Lapidarium: a museum storage space.  The contributors\' texts will be made available along with their selections, with an expanded edited volume to follow,  while events developed with the contributors will be organised at an ad-hoc basis.\r\n\r\n\r\n',NULL),(184,1,'2016-04-04 13:19:54','2017-05-25 17:13:44',98,'LAPIDARIUM',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'lapidarium',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\nAs artworks are chosen they will be transported to Point, where they will accumulate into a collectively curated, somewhat irregular exhibition. The works will be selected gradually until June so that later additions will be in conversation with previous ones. The exhibition’s curatorial direction will be that of a Lapidarium: a museum storage space. The contributors’ texts will be made available along with their selections, with an expanded edited volume to follow, while events developed with the contributors will be organised on an ad-hoc basis.',NULL),(185,1,'2016-04-04 13:47:53','2017-05-25 17:15:13',100,'CHRIS BORS',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'chris-bors',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\nBio\r\n\r\n[Chris Bors](http://www.chrisbors.com/) (b. 1971, USA) received his MFA from the School of Visual Arts, New York. His work has been exhibited in Washington, New York, Luxembourg, Berlin, Esslingen, Athens and Nicosia, among others. Reviews of his work have appeared in *The New York Times*, *Time Out New York* and *Brooklyn Rail*, and featured in *Vogue Italia*, *K48* and *zingmagazine*. He has written for *Artforum.com*, *ArtReview* and *Art in America*, among many publications. He lives in New York City.\r\n\r\n(2013)',NULL),(186,0,'2016-04-04 14:54:17','2016-04-04 15:29:38',NULL,'WES HILL',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'wes-hill',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Bio\r\n\r\nDr. Wes Hill is an art writer, artist and curator who lectures in art theory and curatorial studies at Southern Cross University. He has a PhD in art history from the University of Queensland, and he is regularly published in visual art magazines and journals such as Artforum, Frieze, Broadsheet and Art and Australia. Speciality research areas include contemporary art, the ‘folkloric’ and the nature and representation of ‘criticality’ in cultural practice. Curated exhibitions include This is what I do (Metro Arts, Brisbane, and Contemporary Art Spaces Tasmania, Hobart), and Living Things (Lismore Regional Gallery, Lismore). As an artist specialising in the medium of installation, he has exhibited with Wendy Wilkins as ‘Wilkins Hill’ at numerous national art institutions such as the Museum of Contemporary Art, Sydney, Artspace, Sydney, and Queensland Art Gallery, Brisbane.\r\n\r\n',NULL),(187,1,'2016-04-04 14:56:07','2017-05-26 20:25:12',255,'WES HILL',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'we-hill',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\nBio\r\n\r\n[Dr Wes Hill](http://www.wilkinshill.com/weshill.html) (b. 1978, Australia) holds a PhD in Art History from the University of Queensland. He lectures in art theory and curatorial studies in Southern Cross University and is regularly published in visual art magazines and journals such as *Artforum*, *Frieze*, *Broadsheet* and *Art and Australia*. Curated exhibitions have been held, among others, in Metro Arts, Brisbane; Contemporary Art Spaces Tasmania, Hobart, and Lismore Regional Gallery, Lismore. He has exhibited with Wendy Wilkins as *Wilkins Hill* in numerous national art institutions, including the Museum of Contemporary Art, Sydney; Artspace, Sydney, and Queensland Art Gallery, Brisbane. He lives in Lismore.\r\n\r\n(2013)\r\n',NULL),(188,0,'2016-04-04 15:00:26','2016-04-06 19:48:32',86,'TEXTS',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'texts',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(189,1,'2016-04-04 15:11:42','2017-05-25 16:34:00',86,'DISPLAYS: WORKS',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'exhibition-and-events',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\nA catalogue of works in the exhibition',NULL),(190,1,'2016-04-04 16:14:19','2017-05-26 10:40:48',142,'TUNE IN',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'tune-in',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\nA solo performance by Lia Haraki \r\n\r\n24 – 25.06.2013\r\n\r\nPress Release:\r\n\r\n‘I still don\'t know whether the protagonists of Lia Haraki’s work are herself or an energy that makes the self happen – or an energy that depersonalises us in an intimate act that discards the notion of a protagonist itself. Practising electro-muscular vibration with her is where I would like to send the most anxious audience members (those who have a fear of missing out and who keep following The Next Thing’). They could experiment with new states of collective embodied identity at the pace of the pulse.’\r\n\r\n– Raimundas Malašauskas, Curator of *Oo* (Cyprus & Lithuania pavilions in the 55th Venice Biennale)\r\n\r\nMoving from side to side from now to now in a forever changing moment allowing consciousness to perform itself in a dance without the ego of a body or a mind and just tuning into whatever is without judgment.\r\n\r\nThe solo *Tune In* is the second in a series of works exploring how repetition can stimulate a kinesthetic response (The first in the series, *Again*, premiered at Old Music New Dance Project, Poland in 2011).\r\n\r\nIn *Tune In* the artist explored how motion brings emotion and how by witnessing this process one can reach a new state of being.<br />\r\n<br/>\r\n<br/>\r\nCredits:\r\n<br/>\r\n<br/>Concept/Creation/Performance: Lia Haraki\r\n<br/>Music/Sound Design: Pandelis Diamantides\r\n<br/>Mentoring: Evi Haraki Mahera\r\n<br/>Lighting Design: Alexander Jotovic\r\n<br/>Sound engineer: Yiannos Ionas',NULL),(191,1,'2016-04-04 16:24:25','2017-10-18 11:56:19',140,'LIA HARAKI',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'lia-xaraki',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\nBio\r\n\r\n[Lia Haraki](http://liaharaki.com) (b. 1978, Cyprus) studied Dance Theatre at the Laban Centre in London. In 2003, after returning to Cyprus, she founded *.pelma.*, which is the creative structure that supports, produces and presents her work locally and internationally. \r\n\r\nLia’s performances have been presented, among others, at the Kalamata International Festival; Julidans, Amsterdam; the Athens Festival; Royal Festival Hall, London; BOZAR, Brussels; UNESCO, Paris; Aerowaves Dance Festival; the Place, London; Tanec Praha; Kleines Haus, Dresden; Korzo, the Hague; euro-scene Leipzig, and the Venice Biennale for Visual Arts.\r\n\r\n(2013)',NULL),(192,0,'2016-04-04 16:27:08','2016-04-06 18:12:45',83,'RESEARCH - BOOK',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'research---book',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(193,1,'2016-04-04 16:41:30','2017-05-26 10:50:25',162,'THE WALL',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the-wall',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br/>\r\n27.09.2013\r\n\r\nPress release:\r\n\r\n*The Wall* is a long-term project launched by Point Café on 27 September 2013. Every season Point Café will invite an artist to curate one of the walls of the café, creating a visual intervention in the space. \r\n\r\n’Autumn Wall’ (wall 1) by Natalie Yiaxi: Written in capital letters and always mounted on a wall, [*ORCA*](http://www.natalieyiaxi.com/orka) is a list of Cypriot toponyms or a poem, depending on how one chooses to read it.',NULL),(194,1,'2016-04-04 16:41:31','2017-10-18 12:03:18',160,'NATALIE YIAXI',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'natalie-yiaxi',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\nBio\r\n\r\n[Natalie Yiaxi](http://www.natalieyiaxi.com/) (b. 1980, Cyprus) studied Communication, Culture and Media at Coventry University; Creative and Media Enterprises at the University of Warwick, and Visual Arts with a focus on book arts at University of the Arts, London.\r\n\r\nFrom 2010 onwards she has participated in various exhibitions in Cyprus and abroad, including *Oo* at the Cyprus and Lithuania Pavilion at the 55th Venice Biennale, 2013.',NULL),(195,1,'2016-04-04 16:50:50','2017-05-26 10:44:43',150,'ART AND CULTURE IN A PERIOD OF CRISIS: <br/>WHAT ABOUT CYPRUS',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'art-and-culture-in-a-period-of-crisis',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br/>\r\n[A round-table discussion](https://vimeo.com/168440469) (in Greek)\r\n\r\n05.07.2013\r\n\r\nPress Release:\r\n\r\nMembers and associates of the School of Fine and Applied Arts, Cyprus University of Technology\r\n\r\n’Crisis as a Creative Factor Towards aNew Cultural Awareness’ – led by [Niki Louizidou](http://dev.o-r-g.com/point/annual-reports/2013/niki-louizidou), Visiting Professor in the History of Art/ Chair of the International Advisory Committee for the Formation of the Department of Fine Arts, Cyprus University of Technology.\r\n\r\n’Cultural Sustainability and Crisis’ – led by [Theopisti Stylianou-Lambert](http://dev.o-r-g.com/point/annual-reports/2013/theopisti-stylianou-lambert), Assistant Professor, Department of Multimedia and Graphic Arts, Cyprus University of Technology / Museologist / Photographer.\r\n\r\n’(Talking About) Art in the Globalised Crisis’ – led by [Antonis Danos](http://dev.o-r-g.com/point/annual-reports/2013/antonis-danos), Assistant Professor in the History and Theory of Art, Department of Multimedia and Graphic Arts, Cyprus University of Technology.\r\n\r\n’Art is a Reminding Process’ – led by [Klitsa Antoniou](http://dev.o-r-g.com/point/annual-reports/2013/klitsa-antoniou), Artist / PhD candidate, Cyprus University of Technology, Associate Professor, Frederick University.\r\n\r\nThe talk will be followed by a two-minute film projection on Argentina’s artistic boom during the crisis.',NULL),(196,0,'2016-04-04 17:11:17','2016-10-19 13:26:08',172,'OVEN',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'oven',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(197,1,'2016-04-04 17:42:37','2017-05-25 15:36:42',15,'ANDREAS ANGELIDAKIS',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'andreas-angelidakis',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\nBio\r\n\r\n[Andreas Angelidakis](http://www.angelidakis.com/) (b. 1968, Greece) studied architecture at the Southern California Institute of Architecture (SCI-Arc) and continued his studies at Columbia University (MSAAD) in New York, where he graduated in 1995. His solo exhibitions include: *Domesticated Mountain*, Gloria Maria Gallery, Milan, 2012; *The Angelo Foundation Headquarters*, with Angelos Plessas, Jeu de Paume, Paris, 2009, and *Hotel Blue Wave*, Inmo Gallery, Los Angeles, 2006. \r\n\r\nHis group exhibitions include: *MADEINATHENS*, 13th Venice Biennial of Architecture, Greek Pavilion, 2012; *It’s a wonderful life*, Kunsthalle Athena, Athens, 2012; 1st Beijing International Design Triennial, Beijing, 2011; *Somewhere else*, Espace Louis Vuitton, Paris, 2011, and *The Politics of Art*, National Museum of Contemporary Art, Athens, 2010.\r\n\r\n(2013)\r\n',NULL),(198,1,'2016-04-05 09:28:09','2017-05-25 15:52:48',39,'SHOW OFF: POSTCARDS',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'olivia-plender-publication',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\n*Green Lines* by Olivia Plender\r\n\r\nOn a visit to Bethlehem I was given a tour of the Narrative Museum, in the basement of the Peace Centre on Manger Square. We entered from a back street into a series of dimly lit rooms, recently designed and filled with the latest museum display technology. The Palestinian curator led us through the empty vitrines, whilst describing the stories and objects that will be presented there in the future. The one historical artefact already in situ was a column of building rubble, which, as far as I remember, he said had been excavated when the site was refurbished. It clearly illustrated several periods of occupation in the history of Palestine; a vertical slice starting with Roman remains at the bottom, followed by the Ottoman period and topped by the British Mandate. After the tour, the curator apologized for being so brief and returned to yet another meeting with the project’s international partners, in order to argue over untold stories from the current occupation that might one day fill the empty vitrines.\r\n\r\n*Story written on 40 postcards, sent from a post office in occupied East Jerusalem to Nicosia, September 2012.*\r\n\r\n42 pp | English | full colour | 9 x 13 cm | soft cover | published by Pork Salad Press, 2013\r\n',NULL),(199,1,'2016-04-05 11:00:48','2017-05-25 15:42:40',19,'POINT CENTRE FOR CONTEMPORARY ART: MISSION STATEMENT ',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'mission-statement',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\nLocated at a nodal point between the old city of Nicosia and its declining modern commercial centre, Point Centre for Contemporary Art is a not-for-profit organisation dedicated to the creative support and promotion of contemporary cultural production. \r\nIt aims to foster a multi-disciplinary engagement with new tendencies in all aspects of the arts, architecture, film, music and sound, performance, discourse and thought. Its international commissions focus on its Eastern Mediterranean context, providing a vibrant creative platform for artists in the region. \r\n\r\nPoint also hosts a library. Its research department organises seminars, workshops, lectures, screenings, educational programmes, and other events and happenings. \r\n',NULL),(200,1,'2016-04-05 11:12:09','2017-05-25 15:54:42',58,'HARUN FAROCKI',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'harun-farocki',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\nBio\r\n\r\n[Harun Farocki](http://www.harunfarocki.de/home.html) (b. 1944, Czech Republic) entered the German Cinematic and Television Academy (DFFB) in Berlin in 1966. He was expelled in 1968 for political reasons.\r\n\r\nHis work has been exhibited at Documenta 12, Kassel, 2007, and the Centre for Contemporary Arts, Glasgow, 2011, among others. In 2011 a retrospective of his work *Images of War (at a Distance)* was held at MoMA. His long track of publications for cinema and video includes the provocative *Filmkritik* (Munich), which Farocki edited. His writings include *Speaking about Godard*, 1988–9, and *Serious Games: War–Media–Art*, 2011. He also pursued an academic career in the 90s and was a visiting professor at the University of California, Berkeley. From 2006 until his death in 2014 he was a full professor at the Academy of Fine Arts Vienna.\r\n\r\n(2013)',NULL),(201,0,'2016-04-05 14:19:06','2016-10-18 22:00:53',84,'STATE GALLERY OF CONTEMPORARY ART',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'state-gallery-of-contemporary-art',NU