ts/2013/text-by-ioanna-louka)\r\n\r\n[Gloria Kassianidou](http://dev.o-r-g.com/point/annual-reports/2013/357)<br />\r\nGallery Owner<br />\r\n[Text](http://dev.o-r-g.com/point/annual-reports/2013/text-by-gloria-kassianidou)\r\n',NULL),(203,1,'2016-04-05 18:09:22','2017-04-13 19:51:31',82,'ARCHIVES',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'archive',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\nThe aim of the project is to open up and encourage access to the State Collection, with a focus on its artistic wealth and the scientific value of its records. The first part of the project is an open, collaborative, research-focused exploration of the gallery, its library and its archives. Point will provide all possible support for this effort in a constant exchange with the State Gallery and its staff. The information will be used to set up interviews, to document the development of the gallery and the arts in Cyprus, and to invite dialogue on art history, archival issues, and questions of arts policy and management, with the intention of giving rise to new scholarly and creative projects.\r\n',NULL),(204,1,'2016-04-06 10:43:34','2017-05-25 15:36:27',11,'ANNE SZEFER KARLSEN',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'anne-szefer-karlsen',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\nBio\r\n\r\n[Anne Szefer Karlsen](http://www.szefer.net/) (b. 1976, Norway) is the Director of Hordaland Art Centre in Bergen, Norway. \r\n\r\nShe was the curator of Lofoten International Art Festival, 2013, (*Just what is it that makes today so familiar, so uneasy?*), and created the project *The Transmitter Show – Words At a Distance*. She has served as Associate Curator for Research and Encounters for Biennale Berlin 2012. She has contributed to journals such as *Afterall*, *A journal of Art, Context and Enquiry*, and *Billedkunst*. She is series editor for *Dublett* and a co-editor of *Self- Organised and Localisert/ Localised*.\r\n\r\n(2013)',NULL),(205,1,'2016-04-06 10:49:55','2017-04-13 22:41:55',17,'AN EMBLEM OF ITS PAST',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'point-neon',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,' <br />\r\nOriginal neon sign from the facade of one of Point’s previous incarnations as the eponymous arcade game parlour, as found in the basement.',NULL),(206,1,'2016-04-06 11:04:39','2016-10-17 17:12:38',26,'POSTCARDS ',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'postcards',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\nby Meriç Algün Ringborg<br />\r\nand Nevin Aladağ ',NULL),(207,1,'2016-04-06 11:05:18','2016-09-16 14:44:52',27,'POSTERS',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'untitled',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\nby Haris Epaminonda',NULL),(208,1,'2016-04-06 15:50:24','2017-10-18 11:50:11',78,'CHRYSTALLENI LOIZIDOU',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'chrystalleni-loizidou',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\nBio\r\n\r\n[Chrystalleni Loizidou](https://londonconsortium.academia.edu/ChrystalleniLoizidou) (b. 1983, Cyprus) studied Philosophy and Art History at University College London (BA) and Design Studies at Central Saint Martins (MA). She is a doctoral researcher at the London Consortium (University of London) and Research Associate at the Visual Sociology and Museum Studies Lab (Department of Multimedia and Graphic Arts, Cyprus University of Technology).\r\n\r\nChrystalleni has been employed as an archivist and curator (*Curating the Virtual: Cyprus on the Net*, Nicosia Municipal Arts Centre, 2008), and was co-editor of the online multimedia journal *STATIC*, 2008. Her research interests include considerations of politics and design, as well as developments within the digital humanities.\r\n\r\n(2013)',NULL),(209,1,'2016-04-06 20:38:56','2017-10-18 11:55:00',99,'OF CRYPTS AND OTHER SPACES FOR ART',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'text',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\nby Andreas Vrahimis\r\n\r\nIn David Lynch’s television series *Twin Peaks*, the following scene occurs: the small town’s business magnate Benjamin Horne undergoes a temporary stint of psychosis, under the effect of which he begins to assemble a number of objects found in his office, rearranging them in a peculiar manner. When asked what he is doing (by those around him whose personal interests prevent them from openly calling him mad), he replies that ‘if one could find the perfect arrangement of all objects in any particular space it could create a resonance’, of which ‘the benefits to the individual dwelling in that space could be extensive, far reaching’. According to Horne, there is something magical about specific assemblages of objects in space, which can produce certain effects.\r\n \r\nThe interrogation of the particular assemblage of works of art that is attempted by the *Displays* Project is bound to stumble into and face a series of questions, some of which are to be addressed by this text. There is a sense in which the questions are an effect caused by this particular assemblage of objects in space (though not exactly with Horne’s hypothetical benefits of a perfect gathering). Once things are put together in space in a particular way, then some of these questions arise.\r\n\r\nThe first of these questions relates directly to this quasi-magical effect of gathering: What is a collection? At least in name, what we are faced with here is thought to be a collection. It is not only private individuals, but also states that engage in this activity of selectively gathering objects. To talk of ‘a collector’, or private gatherer, and of the accompanying psycho-pathologies, is problematic. The boundary that separates the collector from the hoarder or the connoisseur is delicate enough when these are somehow characteristics of individuals. Is there connoisseurship involved in what here goes by the name of a ‘collection’, supposedly undertaken on behalf of more than just a private gatherer? And what about hoarding? There is, one suspects, a multiplication of derangements when we move from the problematic case of the individual collector to that of a state collection.\r\n\r\nIn other words, if it is already difficult enough to answer *why collect?* for an individual collector, then it is almost impossible even to pose such a question for those who collect in the name of others. *In the name of whom?* is another question we might ask. Are there particular ways in which collecting addresses such questions? Should there be? If so, can they be identified through an interrogation of that which is collected itself?\r\n\r\nThis question leads us to some more basic problems. I can’t touch on the question of the accessibility of the collection itself here. It’s enough to say that it is in the name of others that things are collected.\r\n\r\nThe question of authorship lingers close by. Is there a way of uncontroversially establishing that the works collected are what they are? It seems like one of the magic functions peculiar to this particular assemblage of objects in space (i.e. the state collection of the Republic of Cyprus) is that it causes the objects involved to lose the potential to be accurately identified. Some of the works seem to have done this themselves prior to being delegated to the space of oblivion that their collection implies.[1] But this collection appears, in a quasi-Benjaminian manner, radical in attempting to destabilise the notion that an artwork’s originality matters.[2] It threatens to turn future historians of art in Cyprus into archaeologists faced with an alien culture.\r\n\r\nNo wonder, then, that very little dialogue, and much less critical inquiry, revolves around the space that is forged by this assemblage. Should this be just a matter of complaint? Such complaints might come from instrumental concerns regarding the immediate devaluation of cultural capital, another magical effect of its entrance into the space of oblivion. Should this remain a matter of a small complaint that gets superficially addressed, only to say that there has been a response to it, only to be forgotten?\r\n\r\nNo. By relocating the works in order to display them, by re-collecting them from their delegated space (of oblivion), by writing about them, some of these questions come to the fore and begin to be addressed.\r\n\r\n--\r\n\r\n1. Kashiallos, for example, as a visitor to the National Gallery might notice upon entrance, seems to have made up ‘ancient’ Cypriot artefacts. But do we know that Kashiallos made these himself? There doesn’t seem to be adequate proof of authenticity for many of the works in the collection.\r\n\r\n2. The underlying cause for this might, nonetheless, be completely un-Benjaminian, in that the relevant information seems to presume a kind of verbal tradition. Rather than an attempted enactment of the ‘death of the author’ (which, in a radical manner, it is unavoidably heading towards), here one might diagnose a scheme based on the contingent imagined availability of a living author, who is always supposedly willing to testify to his work.',NULL),(210,1,'2016-04-07 12:58:30','2017-04-19 06:13:56',190,'HARIS EPAMINONDA',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'haris-e',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\nBio\r\n\r\n[Haris Epaminonda](http://www.harisepaminonda.com/) (b. 1980, Cyprus) was educated at the Royal College of Art, Kingston University, and Chelsea College of Art & Design. She has exhibited at major art centres such as the Tate Modern, UK; MoMA, USA; Malmö Konsthall, Sweden; Künsthaus Zürich, Switzerland, and Modern Art Oxford, UK. \r\n\r\nShe was a resident at the Künstlerhaus Bethanien in Berlin, with the support of the UNDO Foundation, Nicosia, and was recently nominated for the [Preis der Nationalgalerie für junge Kunst](http://www.smb.museum/en/museums-institutions/hamburger-bahnhof/about-us/whats-new/detail.html?tx_smb_pi1%5BnewUid%5D=42&cHash=a8b18d8feb5ec5495ad04c0c46043c10) in Germany. In 2007, Epaminonda represented Cyprus at the 52nd Venice Biennale. She lives in Berlin.\r\n',NULL),(211,1,'2016-04-07 13:07:48','2017-05-25 16:10:21',69,'POINT CAFÃ‰',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'point-cafe',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\nPoint Café is a project created by and in support of Point and organised by [Gabrielle Duval](http://dev.o-r-g.com/point/annual-reports/2013/gaby-duval).\r\n\r\nMaking healthy and ecological choices that will support the long-term sustainability of the environment is an extremely difficult challenge, especially when one cares about using local produce. These are the questions that concern us here. We have chosen to focus primarily on sustainability. All excellent things happen through trial and error and express a set of values. My values are as follows: respect for the ingredients and the process of cooking them (this means having fewer ingredients in the beginning and gradually building on them as we build the relationships with the growers, producers and suppliers). I also believe in allowing the time to experiment as we get to know our ingredients and our tools (oven, location, staff). Respect for the community surrounding us – the art centre, the environment, our country – and not trying to be everything for everyone is equally important. This is why our menu is not a piece of paper but a booklet explaining the story behind each item on the menu, detailing the use of the ingredients and their origins, including health tips and historical backgrounds. Our menu is always in development as we try to stay seasonal and continue experimenting while we try to cater for all dietary requirements. Organic when we can, seasonal almost always, everything we prepare is prepared fresh using the best local ingredients available. Ask questions, and keep coming back for new things.\r\n',NULL),(212,1,'2016-04-07 13:33:00','2017-05-26 16:34:02',210,'CHAPTERS: PRODUCTION CREDITS',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'behind-the-scenes',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\nDirector, 