AIOKASTRO',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'museum-of-nothing',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\nAndrea Bruno, Museum of Nothing, 1989.',NULL),(217,0,'2016-04-11 17:07:08','2016-04-11 17:12:40',NULL,'SOCIOPOLITICAL EVENTS',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'sociopolitical-events',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'\r\nShooting Star\r\npine, glass \r\nA shooting star is a trading signal used to predict price movements. It typically occurs during an uptrend in stock prices and results when the the stock price shoots up well above the opening price, but then falls to a lower level. Shooting stars represent a signal to traders that the uptrend could be over, marking the beginning of a reversal and indicating that shares in the stock should be sold.\r\n\r\n\r\n(Economic) Sentiment Indicator, Cyprus\r\nsandstone\r\nThe Economic Sentiment Indicator summarises people\'s perceptions about the economic and financial outlook in their country. The index is constructed every month by collecting consumers\' views on the general socio-economic situation and the financial condition of their households, as well as managers\' expectations on demand, turnover, production, employment, and prices. The index is an average of all these opinions. The Cyprus ESI is compiled by the Economic Research Centre at the University of Cyprus\r\n',NULL),(218,1,'2016-04-11 17:11:01','2017-05-30 21:39:33',6,'RELOAD THE CURRENT PAGE: WORK TITLES',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'titles',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br/>\r\n*Shooting Star*, pine, glass \r\n\r\nA shooting star is a trading signal used to predict price movements. It typically occurs during an uptrend in stock prices and results when the the stock price shoots up well above the opening price, but then falls to a lower level. Shooting stars represent a signal to traders that the uptrend could be over, marking the beginning of a reversal and indicating that shares in the stock should be sold.\r\n\r\n\r\n*(Economic) Sentiment Indicator, Cyprus*,  sandstone\r\n\r\nThe Economic Sentiment Indicator summarises people\'s perceptions about the economic and financial outlook in their country. The index is constructed every month by collecting consumers’ views on the general socio-economic situation and the financial condition of their households, as well as managers’ expectations on demand, turnover, production, employment, and prices. The index is an average of all these opinions. The Cyprus ESI is compiled by the Economic Research Centre at the University of Cyprus.\r\n',NULL),(219,0,'2016-04-12 10:37:02','2017-05-30 22:52:54',65,'7 WINDOW FRAMES',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'7-window-frames',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(220,1,'2016-04-12 10:44:28','2016-04-12 10:44:28',65,'A SECOND TRY',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'a-second-try',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(221,1,'2016-04-12 12:01:07','2017-04-19 11:45:38',152,'FIELD RECORDINGS',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'field-recordings',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\nMaterial recorded outside a recording studio for the purpose of capturing the audible illustration of an environment. Captured sound can be either natural (nature recordings, such as the sound of water, wind, animal calls, etc.) or anthropogenic (e.g. noises caused by moving trains, city traffic or numbers stations broadcasts). Field recordings are widely used in experimental music, musique concrète, ambient and other similar genres. \r\n\r\n',NULL),(222,1,'2016-04-12 12:32:24','2017-05-30 23:59:32',160,'ELECTRIC SOUNDSCAPES',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'electric-soundscapes',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />Program',NULL),(223,1,'2016-04-12 12:36:25','2017-10-13 13:14:33',158,'EN ROUTE ',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'en-route',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br/> \r\nA [concert](https://vimeo.com/185190888) of recent works\r\n<br/> by Yiannis Christofides\r\n\r\n08.09.2014, 19:30\r\n\r\nProgramme:\r\n\r\nI. *Atmospheres II* (digital audio)\r\n\r\nII. *En route (for James Klopfleisch)* \r\n<br/>(double bass, digital audio and improviser)\r\n\r\nIII. *Postcards/Nicosia* (digital audio)\r\n\r\nDouble Bass: [Aische Wirsig](http://dev.o-r-g.com/point/annual-reports/2014/aische-wirsig)',NULL),(224,1,'2016-04-12 12:40:24','2017-05-30 23:48:11',160,'AISCHE WIRSIG ',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'aische-wirsig',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\nBio\r\n\r\nAische Elise Wirsig (b. Germany) studied Double Bass Performance at the Hanns Eisler University of Music in Berlin, Germany, received an MA at the Music University of Mannheim and studied Instrumental and Vocal Pedagogics at the Graz University of Fine Arts (Kunstuni Graz). \r\n\r\nSince 2013 she has been living in Cyprus and teaching at the Workshop for Young String Soloists, part of the programme established by the Ministry of Education and Culture of Cyprus for the training and promotion of new talents in music.\r\n\r\n(2014)',NULL),(225,1,'2016-04-12 13:40:52','2017-05-31 00:02:16',165,'SOUND WALK',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'sound-walk',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\nA sound walk is [defined](http://www.sfu.ca/sonic-studio/handbook/Soundwalk.html) as ‘a form of active participation in the soundscape. Though the variations are many, the essence of the soundwalk is to encourage the participant to listen discriminatively, and moreover, to make critical judgments about the sounds heard and their contribution to the balance or imbalance of the sonic environment.’\r\n\r\n\r\n',NULL),(226,0,'2016-04-12 17:04:31','2017-05-30 22:49:54',24,'LIGHTS',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'lights',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(227,1,'2016-04-12 17:35:45','2017-05-30 22:14:03',31,'NIKI KATSAOUNI',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'niki-katsaouni',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\nBio\r\n\r\nDr Niki Katsaouni (b. 1945, Cyprus) studied Psychology at Bedford College, University of London, received an MA in Philosophy and Aesthetics from Sorbonne, Paris, and holds a PhD in Politics from the National and Kapodistrian University of Athens.\r\n\r\nShe moved to London in 1972 and was involved in the creation of a sustainable Cypriot community there. She has published 28 books, eight of which are poetry. She was honoured by the Ministry of Education in Cyprus and her work has appeared in anthologies in France, Germany, Greece, Romania and Cyprus. Her poem [*Ammochostos*](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rFlyP_eXh84), put to music by Michael Christodoulides, has been sung by George Dalaras all over the world.\r\n\r\n(2014)',NULL),(228,0,'2016-04-12 17:57:10','2016-04-12 18:26:59',NULL,'BOOK ',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'book',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Throughout centuries of European colonial domination, the bodies of Middle Eastern dancers, male and female, move sumptuously and seductively across the pages of Western travel journals, evoking desire and derision, admiration and disdain, allure and revulsion. This profound ambivalence forms the axis of an investigation into Middle Eastern dance―an investigation that extends to contemporary belly dance.\r\n\r\nStavros Stavrou Karayanni, through historical investigation, theoretical analysis, and personal reflection, explores how Middle Eastern dance actively engages race, sex, and national identity. Close readings of colonial travel narratives, an examination of Oscar Wilde’s Salome, and analyses of treatises about Greek dance, reveal the intricate ways in which this controversial dance has been shaped by Eurocentric models that define and control identity performance.',NULL),(229,0,'2016-04-12 18:24:36','2017-04-14 06:41:14',40,'DANCING FEAR',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'dancing-fear',NULL,NULL,'0000-00-00 00:00:00',NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\n\r\nThroughout centuries of European colonial domination, the bodies of Middle Eastern dancers, male and female, move sumptuously and seductively across the pages of Western travel journals, evoking desire and derision, admiration and disdain, allure and revulsion. This profound ambivalence forms the axis of an investigation into Middle Eastern dance―an investigation that extends to contemporary belly dance.\r\n\r\nStavros Stavrou Karayanni, through historical investigation, theoretical analysis and personal reflection, explores how Middle Eastern dance actively engages race, sex and national identity. Close readings of colonial travel narratives, an examination of Oscar Wilde’s Salome, and analyses of treatises about Greek dance, reveal the intricate ways in which this controversial dance has been shaped by Eurocentric models that define and control identity performance.\r\n\r\n[Book](https://www.wlupress.wlu.ca/Books/D/Dancing-Fear-and-Desire)',NULL),(230,0,'2016-04-14 11:54:41','2017-05-30 23:09:39',NULL,'YIANNIS TOUMAZIS',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'yiannis-toumazis',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\nBio\r\n\r\nYiannis Toumazis (b. , )  living in Nicosia, studied Civil Engineering at Metsovion National Polytechnic (Greece), Theatre Design at the Academy of Fine Arts in Utrecht (The Netherlands), and Theory of Art and Aesthetics at Université de Picardie Jules Verne (UPJV) in Amiens (France), where he received his PhD, presenting his thesis on Marcel Duchamp. \r\n\r\nSince 1994, he is the Director of the Nicosia Municipal Arts Centre and of the [Pierides Foundation](http://www.pieridesfoundation.com.cy/main/default.aspx). He is also currently serving as Director of the Tornarites-Pierides Marine Life Foundation. He has designed, organised, and curated a number of contemporary art exhibitions, including Picasso-Graveur, Hommage a Van Gogh, Joan Miro, Accidental Meetings, [1960-1974 Young Cypriot Artists at the Dawn of the Republic](http://dev.o-r-g.com/point/annual-reports/2014/book-launch/1960-1974-young-cypriot-artists) etc. In 2011, he was appointed the first Cypriot curator of [the Cyprus Pavilion at the 54th Venice Biennale](http://cyprusinvenice.org/2011/pdf/PRESS_RELEASE_CYPRUS_EN.pdf). ',NULL),(231,1,'2016-04-15 09:31:51','2017-04-15 05:28:36',145,'ELENEIO',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'eleneio',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\nThe Eleneio Public Elementary School is located near the centre of Nicosia, just outside the Venetian Walls, and has been in operation since 1925. It is a school with a long illustrious history for the rising urban middle class during the 20th century that now finds its neighbourhood and community undergoing a cycle of economic decline and rapid gentrification, while catering to students of multicultural backgrounds. \r\n\r\nThe school has seen diminishing enrolment numbers, and numerous requests by Greek-Cypriot parents for transfer to other schools. Despite the fact that the continued operation of the school is crucial for the local community, Eleneio has recently been threatened with closure due to its low enrolment numbers.\r\n',NULL),(232,0,'2016-04-15 09:39:47','2017-03-30 11:03:27',76,'PETROS MORIS',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'petros-moris',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Bio\r\n\r\nPetros Moris is a Greek artist who was born in 1986. Petros Moris has had several gallery and museum exhibitions, including at the Nicholas P. Goulandris Foundation, Museum of Cycladic Art and at the DESTE Foundation, Centre for Contemporary Art. There have been Several articles about Petros Moris, including \'On the grid: new Athens show unites the work of three Greek artists\' written by Ali Morris for Wallpaper in 2015.',NULL),(233,1,'2016-04-15 13:14:13','2016-04-15 15:51:52',111,'TEXT BY ELENA PARPA',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'text-by-elena-parpa',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(234,1,'2016-04-15 13:40:36','2016-04-15 13:40:36',110,'TE