,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'text-by-gloria-kassianisou',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(255,1,'2016-04-18 12:48:32','2016-04-18 12:48:32',132,'TEXT BY ELENI LOIZIDOU',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'text-by-eleni-loizidou',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(256,1,'2016-04-18 12:55:46','2017-03-14 12:53:48',133,'TEXT BY IOANNA LOUCA',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'text-by-ioanna-louka',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(257,1,'2016-04-18 13:07:38','2017-05-25 15:32:37',6,'THE IDEA OF POINT',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'history',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\nThe creation of the art space Point Centre for Contemporary Art was the result of prior engagement with contemporary cultural production both in Cyprus and internationally. \r\nPoint’s origins can be traced back to 2007 with the founding of [UNDO](http://dev.o-r-g.com/point/annual-reports/2013/321), a critical journal of the arts and humanities. The journal gradually grew into the [UNDO Foundation](http://dev.o-r-g.com/point/annual-reports/2013/undo), formed in collaboration with Künstlerhaus Bethanien. The collaboration involved offering grants and residencies to Cypriot artists. A need thus emerged for a space in which the work produced by these artists could be shared. Here the seeds of Point slowly began taking root.\r\n',NULL),(258,1,'2016-04-18 13:21:21','2016-04-18 13:21:21',134,'TEXT BY GIORGOS PAPAGEORGIOU',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'text-by-giorgos-papageorgiou',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(259,1,'2016-04-18 13:26:13','2016-04-18 13:26:13',136,'TEXT BY RITA SEVERIS',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'text-by-rita-severis',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(260,1,'2016-04-18 13:29:07','2016-10-21 12:04:00',138,'TEXT BY ANTREAS VRAHIMIS',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'text-by-antreas-vrahimis',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(261,1,'2016-04-18 23:09:35','2017-05-25 15:24:22',5,'ANDRE ZIVANARI ',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'andre-zivanari',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\nBio\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAndre Zivanari (b. 1962, Cyprus) is the director and founder of Point Centre for Contemporary Art. She holds an MA in Art Criticism (Theory of Criticism, History of Aesthetics, Critical and Curatorial History of Visual Arts) from City University UK, and a BA in Design from Central St Martins School of Art and Design.\r\nAndre published *Undo / Critical Journal* in 2007, and initiated the UNDO Residency Award in collaboration with Künstlerhaus Bethanien, 2007. She has also served as a member of various committees including the Advisory Committee for the Selection of Artworks for the State Gallery, 2006–09, and the Committee for the Selection of Artists and Artworks for the Ministry of Education and Culture, 2003–2006.\r\n\r\n(2013)',NULL),(262,1,'2016-04-19 00:09:38','2017-05-30 21:59:28',15,'RELOAD THE CURRENT PAGE: TEXTS',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'texts',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br/>\r\nBy Emily King and Eleni Xenou, 2014\r\n\r\nI:\r\n\r\n‘Some people lose their sense of proportion, I’ve lost my sense of scale.’ (Will Self, *Scale*, 1992)\r\n\r\nWhen an economist makes a model, she simplifies. She selects the variables that she believes to be most pertinent to the issue at hand and maps their correspondence with one another according to the available evidence. These relationships are then used to predict a spectrum of potential future outcomes. Economists ignore complexity. They have to. It would be impossible to include all possible factors in their paradigms. They abstract, smooth away and scale down the real world in order to present it as, to some extent, predictable. \r\n\r\nEvery economic model is riddled with bias. There is no neutral method for selecting the relevant factors. The other-things-being-equal assumption on which all such schemes are founded requires an act of self-deception. These models are made to determine policy, but perhaps there is also psychological motivation behind their reductions. In ignoring messy reality in favour of making neat mock-ups economists find ways of managing our and their anxieties.\r\n\r\nAn economist’s model has something in common with a dollhouse or a miniature railway. It is an approximation of the real world that allows its creator to have a sense of control. Children test their ideas about the world by playing God with dolls and latterly with digital characters. Likewise, adults who find the world difficult to comprehend can find refuge in elaborate train sets. In his book *The Savage Mind*, published in 1962, the French anthropologist Claude Levi-Strauss argued ‘the intrinsic value of a small-scale model is that it compensates for the renunciation of sensible dimensions by the acquisition of intelligible dimensions.’\r\n\r\nA Japanese *suiseki* rock could find a place within a model railway or near a dollhouse, but the impulse behind its school of miniaturisation is different. *Suiseki* rocks are selected for their resemblance to other, usually larger scale, natural features such as mountain ranges or islands, but the relationships are suggestive, not exact. There is a huge range of different categories of suiseki, including not only rocks that look like mountains close up – *kinzan-seki* – and mountains in the distance – *enzan-seki* – but also those that bring to mind waterfalls – *yamagata-taki-ishi* – caves – *dokutsu-ish* – and even fish – *uogata-ishi* – or birds – *torigata-ishi*. Suiseki are not made or modelled, rather they are recognised. A *suiseki* is not a simplification, it is a kind of analogy. It prompts meditation on what one form might reveal about another. \r\n\r\nThe central piece in Michael Anastassiades’s exhibition *Reload the Current Page* is titled *Jimbutsu-seki*, which is the name for a suiseki stone that evokes the form of a human body. Unlike a suiseki, however, this piece was crafted, not discovered. It is carved from black basalt, a volcanic stone common in Cyprus, according to the dimensions of the Pentadaktylos mountain mass, part of the Kyrenia mountain range that runs parallel to the northern coast of the island. Consisting of five finger-like projections, Pentadaktylos is the best-known section of the Kyrenia mountains to the extent that it is often taken to be synonymous with the entire range. Its resemblance to a hand has generated numerous myths and it is variously said to be a handful of earth that was flung at or pushed toward an enemy or the handprint of the island’s saviour as he emerged from the sea. These myths have accrued resonance over the last forty years – since 1974 when the mountains were suddenly on the Turkish side of the island – yet have remained highly visible from the Greek. Pentadaktylos can be seen from the island’s divided capital Nicosia.\r\n\r\nMichael Anastassiades was a child when Cyprus was partitioned in 1974. He grew up in the shadow of the conflict and as a young adult served 24 months in the military – the period that remains compulsory for Greek Cypriot men – imagining various conflict scenarios. Had he remained in Cyprus, he would have been obliged to keep a gun in his home to use against invaders. For Michael, as for many Cypriots, Pentadaktylos loomed large both literally and figuratively. It was as if the island was waving at them from beyond enemy lines. \r\n\r\nThe Greek-Turkish conflict remains live, but times have changed. Currently the Cypriots’ most pressing concern is the state of the island’s finances. Yet somehow one crisis has merged into another and national anxieties have become non-specific. In taking the emotionally resonant and physically reminiscent form of Pentadaktylos and scaling it down, Michael has made an emblem for all of the islanders’ concerns. *Jimbutsu-seki* embodies both the Greek Cypriots’ fears of invasion and their unease about economic collapse. While the act of miniaturisation and simplification usually implies some kind of manageability, in this case worries are represented, perhaps even mitigated some, but the underlying problems remain stubbornly unsolved. \r\n\r\nWhile the landscape represented in *Jimbutsu-seki* has a basis in physical reality, the landscape suggested by another of the pieces in the exhibition, *Economic Sentiment Indicator*, is purely imaginary. Following the line of a graphic representation of Cypriots’ perceptions of their economic state from 2008 to 2013, the piece was CNC (computer numerically controlled)-carved from sandstone. The chart on which it was based is striking. In line with global sentiment, economic optimism in Cyprus plummeted in late 2008, then it held on and even rallied a little, only to plunge dramatically in mid-2011 during the time of the Greek government’s debt crises. From there the fall is pretty steady until the first quarter of 2013. On 25 March 2013 the Cypriot government accepted a ten-billion-euro international bailout that came with a number of extremely stern conditions. Many ordinary Cypriots lost a significant proportion of their savings. At that point, unsurprisingly, Cypriot economic sentiment took a nosedive.  \r\n\r\nAnastassiades’ miniature three-dimensional graph of this tumult is a lovely thing. In spite of plotting financial woes, it looks like a model of a place you might want to spend your holidays. A boom becomes a hill you could clamber up and a recession a valley you could roll into. As yet there are no suiseki categories for the representation of emotional states, but such a thing doesn’t seem unfeasible. There are certain sorts of rocks that imply pattern or texture—for example, *tori-ishi*, a stone that resembles a tiger pelt, or *raiko-seki*, a stone that suggests a lightening bolt. Why not a stone that brings to mind optimism or gloom?\r\n\r\nCyprus has a serious long-term problem with its water supply. This has been exacerbated by lack of cooperation and in some cases outright competition between the Greek and Turkish sides of the island. With both sides competing to tap scarce underground streams, there is even talk of a ‘water war’. The proposed solution on the Greek side is desalination plants and on the Turkish an undersea pipe bringing fresh water from mainland Turkey. Both will be expensive and difficult to engineer. In the meantime, Cypriots monitor the level of water in their existing reservoirs obsessively and anxiously. Kouris is the largest dam on the island and it creates a reservoir that collects water from four different rivers. In good times this is a ‘Y’ shape, stretching deep into the valleys in the north, but in moments of drought it is reduced to a small uncertain ‘l’.\r\n\r\nWith the aim of expressing this perpetual concern, Anastassiades has made three ‘water tables’. Their titles are a series of dates – 150321011, 15032012 and 15032013 – and the surface area of each table is a to-scale representation of the Kouris Reservoir on those three days carved in Cypriot sandstone. The dates mark the various stages in Cyprus’s economic crisis: March 2011 was a critical month in the Greek government’s debt crises that sent a shudder down the Cypriot spine. In March 2012 Cyprus’s credit rating was reduced to junk status, and March 2013 was the month of the aforementioned international bailout and the imposition of its punishing conditions. Between 2011 and 2013 the economic situation in Cyprus only got worse, but by contrast the water reserves actually improved. In 2011 the Kouris reservoir was reduced to a thin ribbon, but by 2013 it had more than doubled in size. The tables are respectively 1.164 meters and 1.9 meters long. The relationship between natural and economic resources is of constant concern for economists. Notably, famines are less likely the outcome of bad harvests, than of poor distribution, inequality and corruption. Cyprus’s need for water is inarguable, but rain alone cannot solve the problem. In order to reach an effective and lasting solution, the islanders must address the political and economic dimensions of the problem. \r\n\r\nWhile Cypriots worry about water, they distract themselves with football. The British introduced the sport to the island in the early 20th Century and Cyprus’s football league was founded in the early 1930s. Since then it has become the island’s consuming passion, so much so that the idea that football is merely entertainment would be an anathema to many Cypriot fans. Some teams are allied to political parties and the sense that supporters are siding with the right or the left adds heat to the competition. The island’s teams have enjoyed triumphs that are disproportionate to their resources, with the most successful of them all, APOEL, reaching the Champions League competition several times. \r\n\r\nAnastassiades evokes this enthusiasm through the titles of two of the pieces in the exhibition: *Keepie Uppie* and *Foul*. Both are CNC-carved sandstone models of a series of hills that drivers see en route from Nicosia to Larnaca Airport, which has served as the island’s major airport since the Turkish invasion put the newly constructed Nicosia Air Terminal out of action forty years ago. *Keepie Uppie* is simply a 1.5-meter-long representation of a series of peaks. *Foul*, meanwhile, is a model of three peaks on two of which, in reality, sit a church and United Nations military outpost. Instead of modelling these features in the piece, however, Anastassiades has placed an opaline sphere in the valley between the three hills. Again there is a suggestion of suiseki. Football fans channel life’s messy tapestry of joy and despair through a single simple channel. By connecting the peaks and troughs of the island’s landscape with the notion of sporting and political fortune, he implies that the sentiments of the football supporter might be more complex than they appear.  \r\n\r\nThe most personal of all the pieces in this exhibition are *Large Zap* and *Small Zap*. Both approximate spheres made from rough Cypriot stone, they are respectively 300mm and 45mm in diameter. When Michael was a teenager, his father commissioned a house from Cyprus’s most respected architect, Neoptolemos Michaelides. Born on the island in 1921, Michaelides studied in Milan both immediately before and after the Second World War and he is known for combining austere modernist form with local craft traditions. Michaelides became a mentor to Anastassiades and the two of them would go on outings to look at architectural and geological sites. On one such trip, Michaelides handed Anastassiades a stone that was a near-perfect sphere, which Anastassiades has kept to this day. This same stone is *Small Zap*, while *Large Zap* is the same thing scaled up several times. The larger the form becomes, the more apparent it is that it’s not quite spherical. \r\n\r\nWhile reduction and simplification are used to render things manageable—from economic relationships to train networks—magnification is employed to create complexity and reveal hidden truths. It is all a matter of perspective and proportion. It’s all about scale. Significantly, in this exhibition Anastassiades reduces the features of Cyprus as a whole, but enlarges the small piece of the island that he has kept as a souvenir these past 25 years. It’s interesting that he feels safe to expand and explore his personal connection with Michaelides, but, when it comes to the state of the nation, he feels the need for reduction and containment. \r\n\r\n(Emily King)\r\n\r\n--\r\n\r\nII:\r\n\r\nHe spread out the drawings, photocopies, and photos on the long wooden table, and glanced up at me, his eyes brimming with a familiar combination of innocence and awareness that sets him apart.\r\n\r\n‘I felt the need to create something from the beginning,’ he told me, referring to his desire to engage in a ‘creative dialogue’, and to facilitate a shared but altered observation of reality through a balanced journey of discovery. He had lately been driven by an increasing realisation that, in order to be able to hold up the mirror to ourselves, we need to look closely at others around us. \r\n\r\n‘Believe in yourself.’ That had been his advice to me, time and time again, and he repeated it as we walked along snowy London streets some months ago. Bundled in long coats and woolly scarves, we talked about upheaval and new beginnings, about taking chances and re-defining ourselves. Naturally, at the forefront of our minds was the financial crisis, whose rippling effects had up-ended our convictions and played havoc with the notion of a ‘secure’ life. ‘Nothing is secure,’ he reiterated, ‘except your determination and your belief in yourself.’\r\n\r\nIn this latest endeavour, he had started afresh, seeing no reason to refer to his established recognition, or to flaunt his success. Certainly, he would have had every right to do so, considering how hard he has fought to defend that which defines and commends him. He has battled with the same demons that plague all those who decide to confront their fears and live their dreams, rather than simply dreaming their life away.\r\n\r\nI cherished the truth in those words, coming, as they did, from someone who knew first-hand what it meant to spend countless nights far from the comforting familiarity of your childhood home. In doing so, he had faced the unknown and had dealt with turmoil, having learnt the hard way that life is ultimately shaped by events seemingly beyond our control. Often, it is those events that push our limits and force us to change our point of view.\r\n\r\n‘So what do you mean when you say you want to “create something from the beginning”?’ I asked him later, on an evening out in Nicosia. As he sat opposite me, with a glass of red wine, he explained that he was seeking equilibrium between discipline and spontaneity. He nurtured the hope, he clarified, that current anxieties would give way to a more tranquil awareness. ‘It’s not random,’ he added, referring to his wish to return ‘home’ in order to share his experiences and his realisation that each end comes with a new beginning. ‘History repeats itself, and life isn’t a straight line,’ he said. ‘There is, though, something that stays constant throughout.’\r\n\r\n‘And what’s that?’ I asked. \r\n\r\nHe didn’t answer my question right away, delving instead into childhood tales of long walks with his friend Neoptolemos, where they would while away the hours searching for the perfect pebble, and of car journeys with his parents where the ‘scenic’ route was the only one available. He remembers sitting in the back, gazing out of the window at the three hills, a church and one red and one blue guard post perched on each hilltop. That was the point in time where paradox and contradiction defined his generation’s experiences as they wrestled with issues of separation and ghostly remnants, and where even the water level was a daily measure of our collective vulnerability. \r\n\r\n‘What stays constant?’ I insisted. \r\n\r\n‘The beauty that we find both inside and all around us,’ he replied. In order to appreciate it, he added, you have to ‘reload your page’ and filter the text, editing it and replacing it with language that values the essence of life, instead of trying to put a price on it. \r\n\r\n‘Is that what “reload” means?’ I posed the question, although I already knew that it means you can only trace reality with your fingertips once you’ve realized that the world is defined by your perception of touch. \r\n\r\nIt means gazing at the three rounded hilltops, having first understood that straight lines deaden the soul. It means placing your faith in a falling star, instead of wishing on one that shoots away. It means believing that, as long as life gives you the time to reload, there will always be beauty inside and all around us.\r\n\r\n‘So that’s the meaning of “reload the current page”?’ I asked once more. \r\n\r\nAnd this time, his answer was simply that same look, eyes brimming with a familiar combination of innocence and awareness.\r\n\r\n(Eleni Xenou)',NULL),(263,0,'2016-04-19 10:11:07','2016-10-18 21:48:25',83,'STORAGE',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'storage---state-art-gallery',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'State Art Gallery, Cyprus',NULL),(264,1,'2016-04-19 15:34:54','2017-10-16 15:32:23',196,'YIANNIS PAPADAKIS',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'yiannis-papadakis',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\nBio\r\n\r\nDr [Yiannis Papadakis](http://ucy.ac.cy/dir/en/component/comprofiler/userprofile/papada) (b. 1964, Cyprus) studied Economics at the University of Cambridge, 1983–1986, and Philosophy at the University of California, Santa Cruz, 1986–1988. He received his doctorate in Social Anthropology from the University of Cambridge in 1993.\r\n\r\nHe is Associate Professor of Social Anthropology at the University of Cyprus. He is the author of the book *Echoes from the Dead Zone: Across the Cyprus Divide*, I. B. Tauris, 2005, and he has edited, among others, the publications *Divided Cyprus: Modernity, History and an Island in Conflict*, Indiana University Press, 2006, and the special issue of *Postcolonial Studies*, 2006, on Cyprus.\r\n\r\n(2013)',NULL),(265,1,'2016-04-19 15:39:08','2017-05-26 11:01:20',197,'COSTAS M. CONSTANTINOU',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'costas-m.-constantinou',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\nBio\r\n\r\n[Costas M. Constantinou](http://ucy.ac.cy/dir/el/component/comprofiler/userprofile/kostisk) (b. Cyprus) studied Law and Politics at the University of Keele and received a diploma in International Law from the University of Helsinki. He has an MA in Diplomacy as well as a Doctorate with Scholarship from the University of Lancaster. \r\n\r\nHe was Associate Lecturer at Hull University and a Professor at the University of Keele and the University of Nicosia. Currently, he is Professor of International Relations at the University of Cyprus.\r\n\r\nHe has also served on the editorial and advisory boards of the *Review of International Studies*; *Politics*; *Religion and Ideology*; the *International Journal of Euro-Mediterranean Studies*; the *Cyprus Review*, and *Millennium*, as well as for the book series *Rethinking Peace and Conflict Studies* (Palgrave Macmillan).\r\n\r\n(2013)',NULL),(266,1,'2016-04-19 15:50:22','2017-05-25 16:37:36',195,'ELENA PARPA',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'elena-parpa',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\nBio\r\n\r\nElena Parpa (b. 1976, Kuwait) is currently a PhD candidate at Birkbeck, University of London. \r\n\r\nShe has worked as an arts editor at *Phileleftheros* newspaper, 2000–2013, and as the managing editor of the arts and culture magazine *Ysterografo* (2007–2010). She was also a part-time lecturer at the School of Architecture, Fine and Applied Arts, Frederick University, 2003–2006 and 2009–2010. She has curated exhibitions on contemporary Cypriot art including *Notes to Self* (Omikron Gallery, Nicosia, 2011), *How to Make a Garden* (Visual Artists Association, Nicosia, 2012), and *Utopia* (Lanitis Foundation, Limassol, 2012).\r\n\r\n(2013)',NULL),(267,1,'2016-04-20 08:56:10','2016-04-20 08:58:33',NULL,'Bronze cast Pendadaktilos',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'bronze-cast-pentadaktilos',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(268,1,'2016-04-20 09:15:15','2017-05-04 15:17:11',8,'PRIVATE VIEW',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'view',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(269,1,'2016-04-20 09:50:19','2017-05-30 23:10:19',80,'CAMPAIGN FOR CULTURE',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'cultural-campaign---project-outline',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />Project outline',NULL),(270,1,'2016-04-20 10:30:32','2017-05-30 23:27:39',82,'CAMPAIGN FOR CULTURE: INTERVIEWS',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'interviewees',NULL,