 Critics (A.I.A.C).\r\n\r\n(2014)',NULL),(273,1,'2016-04-20 13:20:53','2017-05-30 22:12:47',29,'FABRICE FLAHUTEZ',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'fabrice-flahutez',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\nBio\r\n\r\n[Fabrice Flahutez](https://sites.google.com/site/fabriceflahutez/) (b. 1967, France) is a Senior Lecturer of Art History at the University Paris Ouest. He is a permanent member of the Centre de Recherches Histoire de l’Art et Représentations (HAR) and associate member of the Centre de Recherches sur le Surréalisme de Paris-3-Sorbonne-Nouvelle (Mélusine), the Centre de Recherches André Chastel (Erco – History of Contemporary Art team, 20th and 21st Centuries) and the Institut des Textes et Manuscrits Modernes (UMR CNRS / ENS – UMR 8132).\r\n\r\nIn 2011, he co-directed with Fabien Danesi and Adeline Lausson the film *The desert is never wrong, on the road to Land Art*. He is editor of the series *ArTguments* and was the recipient of the Library Grant from the Getty Research Institute, Los Angeles, 2006.\r\n\r\n(2014)',NULL),(274,0,'2016-04-21 08:55:57','2016-04-28 16:53:42',NULL,'untitled',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'274',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(275,1,'2016-04-21 09:40:42','2016-04-21 11:28:51',64,'BETHANIEN INSTALLATION',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'bethanien-installation',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(276,1,'2016-04-21 10:16:33','2017-05-30 22:59:07',63,'GARDEN: OPENING EVENING',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'garden-panayiotis-opening',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(277,1,'2016-04-21 11:30:58','2016-04-21 11:33:14',NULL,'NORA MAYER TEXT',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'nora-meyer-text',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Sketches of uncertain realities\r\n\r\n\r\nA sketch describes something not finished. Depending on the situation sketches can have several purposes - they might document or develop an idea, reflect something an artist sees, or function as a way of illustrating a concept, image or principle. For the artist, Panayiotis Michael, his videos, photographs, installations, interventions and objects function as sketches in the sense of unfinished or unresolved situations.\r\n\r\nThrough his work, the artist sketches images of uncertain realities. We see a pile of window frames titled Seven Window Frames(2013), a column constructed on a cushion in A Second Try (2013) or a framed landscape photograph fixed to the wall by a wooden-lath-construction in Landscape (2013). Panayiotis Michael’s pieces create strong visual images based on concentrated and simple set ups. Almost like parabolas or metaphors, his conceptual works tell universal and adaptable stories about the uncertainty of life. In this sense, the pile of window frames conveys not only a part of his parents’ unfinished house and personal memory, but talks more broadly about our vanished dreams and hopes. The complicated hanging of an image seems to be an ironic comment on the fact that we tend to lose sight of a simple solution, whether it is in our daily lives or in politics. It is this ability to transport private memories and experiences into a larger abstract image that is significant to his works. \r\n\r\nOften with a sense of humor, Panayiotis Michael consciously creates works of absurdity. Speed Fix (2013) shows a deconstructed chair perfectly balanced on its own seat and everyday objects like a level and masking tape. Viewers might be conflicted between the poetic beauty of the object and the absurdity of balancing a chair without function for the sake of balance only. In a similar way, Golden (2014) focuses on deconstructing gestures of measurement. Dating from the Renaissance, the “Golden Section” is considered to be the core of a perfectly balanced composition in a picture. Panayiotis Michael deconstructs this myth by literally displaying the calculation of this magical section on a wall in the exhibition. \r\n\r\nFurthermore, the works of the artist oftenreveal processes or remain in flux rather than appearing in status quo. Much of his artistic practices involve the activation of processes, whether they are realized in a performance-like action by himself, Luxury Home 41 h2 (2013) and Luxury Home 41 h1 (2013), or by others, as, for example, the artist’s parents, who became part of the production process for the piece, Photograph (2012-2013). To focus on processes rather than a final product challenges the notion of control in artistic practice, and opens up once again the notion of uncertainty. \r\n\r\nPanayiotis Michael’s works often function as a projection platform for dreams, tragedies and hardships. This is probably most directly addressed in the work, Untitled (2013). This piece is a picture of a demonstration’s banner that is empty. Any form of protest, any form of outrage or wish can find its place on this banner. Similar to a time loop, this visual loop displays future, past and present at the same time, and stands symbolically for fights that have been fought, revolutions that are happening right now and proclamations that still need to be made. Panayiotis Michael’s works not only incite uncertainty but also invite viewers to feel, and fill them, with their own projections and solutions for balance.\r\n\r\n\r\nNora Mayr\r\nIndependent curator and Co-director insitu, Berlin.\r\n',NULL),(278,1,'2016-02-22 16:26:34','2016-04-21 11:34:30',62,'\'ENTITLED\'',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'panayiotis-michael-entitled',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'10.09. - 10.10.2014\r\n\r\nIn 10 September 2014 the exhibition entitled by Cypriot artist Panayiotis Michael opened at Point. The works presented were the outcome of the artists’ residency at the renowned Berlin - based institution [Künstlerhaus Bethanien](http://www.bethanien.de/exhibitions/panayiotis-michael/) in 2013. [Nora Mayer](http://dev.o-r-g.com/point/edit/annual-reports/2014/bethanien-installation/nora-meyer-text), co-director of the institution writes the text in the annual booklet.  The collaboration between Point and Bethanien has been established long before Point had found a space, when it only existed as a platform under the name UNDO, and by 2014 it counted 7 years.\r\n\r\n\r\n“In the last years, Panayiotis Michael’s work has been preoccupied with what may be described, indeed, ‘entitled’, a house. The [Künstlerhaus exhibition](http://dev.o-r-g.com/point/annual-reports/2014/bethanien-installation) is less gripped with the social happiness that a structure and its contents may signify, and more pleasurably associative in its flow of forms and metaphors, related, and not, to the artist’s family house, planned and never constructed. Vacant window edges are seductively abstracted in a horizontal line (age) of plank wood, hence, the piece’s title,[7 Window Frames](http://dev.o-r-g.com/point/annual-reports/2014/7-window-frames). Entities “belonging” to a house are taken apart into another time when they existed otherwise. Feather paddings quietly foster the history of a house, in [A Second Try](http://dev.o-r-g.com/point/annual-reports/2014/a-second-try), and enigmatic interiors weave remains of future memories in cabinets of curiosities. In the spaces of Künstlerhaus Bethanien, Panayiotis Michael creates an ambience, gracefully evoking moods prompted from what we feel entitled to experiencing. The show generously offers a leveling kind of playground from which no one seems to be in a favorable position to grasp the boundaries of a house of entitlement. Perhaps, the lost dream house of the child is not imagined as an enduring house of the future but as small, passing gestures of tranquil moods, where we can renegotiate our entitlements. (From a text by Maria Petrides, 2013)”',NULL),(279,1,'2016-04-21 11:40:49','2017-05-30 22:55:35',63,'SKETCHES OF UNCERTAIN REALITIES',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'booklet-text',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br/>\r\nBy Nora Mayr, Independent Curator and Co-director of [insitu](http://insitu-berlin.com/), Berlin.\r\n\r\nA sketch describes something not finished. Depending on the situation, sketches can have several purposes – they might document or develop an idea, reflect something an artist sees, or function as a way of illustrating a concept, image or principle. For the artist Panayiotis Michael, videos, photographs, installations, interventions and objects function as sketches in the sense of unfinished or unresolved situations.\r\n\r\nThrough his work, the artist sketches images of uncertain realities. We see a pile of window frames titled *Seven Window Frames* (2013), a column constructed on a cushion in *A Second Try* (2013), or a framed landscape photograph fixed to the wall by a wooden-lath-construction in *Landscape* (2013). Panayiotis Michael’s pieces create strong visual images based on concentrated and simple set-ups. Almost like parables or metaphors, his conceptual works tell universal and adaptable stories about the uncertainty of life. In this sense, the pile of window frames conveys not only a part of his parents’ unfinished house and personal memory, but talks more broadly about our vanished dreams and hopes. The complicated hanging of an image seems to be an ironic comment on the fact that we tend to lose sight of a simple solution, whether it is in our daily lives or in politics. It is this ability to transport private memories and experiences into a larger abstract image that is significant in his work. \r\n\r\nOften with a sense of humour, Panayiotis Michael consciously creates works of absurdity. *Speed Fix* (2013) shows a deconstructed chair perfectly balanced on its own seat and everyday objects like a level and masking tape. Viewers might be conflicted between the poetic beauty of the object and the absurdity of balancing a chair without function for the sake of balance only. In a similar way, *Golden* (2014) focuses on deconstructing gestures of measurement. Dating from the Renaissance, the ‘golden section’ is considered to be the core of a perfectly balanced composition in a picture. Panayiotis Michael deconstructs this myth by literally displaying the calculation of this magical section on a wall in the exhibition. \r\n\r\nFurthermore, the works of the artist often reveal processes or remain in flux. Much of his artistic practice involves the activation of processes, whether they are realised in a performance-like action by himself – *Luxury Home 41 h2* (2013) and *Luxury Home 41 h1* (2013) – or by others, as, for example, the artist’s parents, who became part of the production process for the piece *Photograph* (2012–13). To focus on processes rather than a final product challenges the notion of control in artistic practice, and opens up once again the notion of uncertainty. \r\n\r\nPanayiotis Michael’s works often function as a projection platform for dreams, tragedies and hardships. This is probably most directly addressed in the work *Untitled* (2013). This piece is a picture of an empty banner from a demonstration. Any form of protest, any form of outrage or wish can find its place on this banner. Similar to a time loop, this visual loop displays future, past and present at the same time, and stands symbolically for fights that have been fought, revolutions that are happening right now and proclamations that still need to be made. Panayiotis Michael’s works not only incite uncertainty but also invite viewers to feel, and fill them, with their own projections and solutions for balance.',NULL),(280,1,'2016-04-21 13:47:27','2017-04-19 20:53:16',166,'SOUND LIBRARY',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'sound-library',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\nA collection of books, online texts and media exploring sound, listening, and experimental and contemporary music, selected by Yiannis Christofides, will be available for study throughout the exhibition.\r\n\r\n**Books**\r\n\r\n<br/>1. The Audible Past, Jonathan Sterne \r\n<br/>2. Sonic Mediations: Body Sound Technology\r\n<br/>3. In the Blink of an Ear, Seth Kim-Cohen\r\n<br/>4. Background Noise, Brandon LaBelle\r\n<br/>5. Sound, Caleb Kelly\r\n<br/>6. Spaces Speak, Barry Blesser and Linda-Ruth Salter\r\n<br/>7. The Sight of Sound, Richard Leppert\r\n<br/>8. Ο Ντεμπισί, οι μινιμαλιστές και η ηλεκτρονική αποκάλυψη, Χρήστος Τσανάκας\r\n<br/>9. Ωκεανός του ήχου, David Toop\r\n<br/>10. 41 Writers of 41 \'Writings\', Kenneth Gaburo\r\n<br/>11. Science: Lectures and Writings, John Cage \r\n<br/>12. The Soundscapes, R. Murrey Schafer\r\n<br/>13. In Search of a Concrete Music, Pierre Schaeffer\r\n<br/>14. Deep Listening: A Composer’s Sound Practice, Pauline Olivieros\r\n<br/>15. Almost Nothing with Luc Ferrari, Jacqueline Caux\r\n<br/>16. Sound, Caleb Kelly (ed.)\r\n<br/>17. Background Noise: Perspectives on Sound art, Brandon LaBelle\r\n<br/>18. Noise, Water, Meat: A history of Sound in the Arts, Douglas Khan\r\n<br/>19. Listening, Jean-Luc Nancy\r\n<br/>20. Noise: The Political Economy of Music, Jacques Attali and Brian Massumi\r\n<br/>21. Listening through the Noise: the Aesthetics of Experimental Electronic Music, Joanna Demers\r\n<br/>22. Ocean of Sound, David Toop\r\n<br/>23. Audio Culture: Readings in Modern Music, Christoph Cox and Daniel Warner\r\n<br/>24. Varieties of Audio Mimesis, Allen S. Weiss\r\n<br/>25. Listening to Noise and Silence: Towards a Philosophy of Sound Art, Salomé Voegelin\r\n\r\n**Videos**\r\n\r\n<br/>1. Worldizing: A Sound Design Concept, Walter Murch\r\n<br/>2. Toshimaru Nakamura, Egrets\r\n<br/>3. Composing the Composer: A Workshop, Karkowski\r\n<br/>4. John Butcher, John Edwards & Okkyung Lee Trio @ cube\r\n<br/>5. Henri Chopin Live in France 2005\r\n<br/>6. Electrical Walks, Christina Kubisch \r\n<br/>7. Amplified Gesture, David Sylvian\r\n<br/>8. The Colour Of Sound, Chris Watson\r\n<br/>9. Biennale Musica 2012, Alvin Lucier\r\n<br/>10. First sound ever recorded, Édouard-Léon Scott de Martinville (1860)\r\n<br/>11. Intonarumori, Amelia Cuni and Werner Durand\r\n<br/>12. About Silence, John Cage\r\n<br/>13. Performing Water Walk, John Cage\r\n<br/>14. Luc Ferrari composing music\r\n<br/>15. Marshall McLuhan et Pierre Schaeffer (INA, 1973)\r\n<br/>16. Pierre Boulez on John Cage\r\n<br/>17. Risveglio di una città (1914), Luigi Russolo\r\n<br/>18. Monotone-Silence Symphony, Yves Klein\r\n',NULL),(281,1,'2016-04-21 16:00:42','2017-10-13 14:22:59',175,'NEOPTOLEMOS MICHAELIDES\'S CYPRUS ARCHITECTS ASSOCIATION AWARDS CEREMONY SPEECH',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'neptolemos-speech',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\n25.01.1991, Cyprus International Conference Centre\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nI’m not used to awards and this is the first time I find myself in the front row of the audience. [1] \r\n\r\nIf you still have some patience after the previous, very kind speeches, I could also add some words, especially for the young people.\r\n\r\nI believed in some ideas because I studied at the greatest school with no teachers: the *School of Kyrenia*. I spent my childhood there, full of experiences that have been part of my life since then. I still remember there were no playgrounds back then, no silly games to destroy children’s initiatives. \r\n\r\nThere was a ship in the old town of Kyrenia, the skeleton of a ship near Katsellis’ Hotel. [2] We used to sneak into it through a hole near its keel, climbing and thinking of long journeys, while watching Kyrenia’s sea, bluer than any other, through the ship’s black structure. Many years later I visited that place again: the ship wasn’t there. [3] I was wondering why, but no one could give me a proper explanation. I asked my friend, Andreas Kariolou, [4] if he would search for that ship while he was diving for sponges. \r\n\r\nNearby, mister Panagos the carpenter used to work with boats. We were young kids, full of excitement for a spectacle like that: a couple of workers sawing the thick planks of wood, making the parts of a new boat one by one. We desperately wanted to help, to feel like we were part of that process. \r\n\r\nLiving in Kyrenia and its stone alleys I remember in the wintertime walking upon the tiny colourful stones after the rain. Many years later, and after an analysis of myself, those stones became a part of my work. Without any intention of offending any aristocrat, I was originally blue-blooded: [5] all my father’s ancestors were deeply related to the sea. I remember captain Michalis -not Kazantzakis’ character- my uncle, [6] who introduced me to astronomy when we went up to the lighthouse and he showed me the Pole star with the rest of the stars around it. ‘What is that like in the daytime with no stars?’ I asked him. ‘Let me show you,’ he replied. \r\n\r\nAnd so he led me to the ship, *Archangelos*. He showed me the compass and I was spinning it around, but the needle was always showing North. These were my baby steps in astronomy. \r\n\r\nI was a student at a school were the headmaster was my uncle, George Karayiannis, who pinned ancient Greek dictums to the walls. We used to memorise them all, without actually understanding their meaning. I remember I once asked him to explain the meaning of *Midén ágan* (Nothing in excess), and he gave me a vivid example: ‘Think of a hook, so perfect we do not need to add anything.’\r\n\r\nIn Kyrenia we lived in an upper-storey house, which we were actually sharing with swallows. There was a nest underneath. My *steté* (grandmother) used to place a piece of newspaper in it for the bird droppings with four stones at the corners that I collected myself. We changed the paper and the stones every day. For us, that became an installation of great importance through the years. \r\n\r\nMy bedroom was oriented to the South, and I always insisted on leaving the window shutters wide open so that I could look towards the mountain, *Ayios Ilarionas*. I was excited, expecting lightning during those winter nights to show me the silhouette of the mountain. \r\n\r\nApart from *Tsiakkileri*, [7] I was also collecting stones from the mountain, using old tools to try to cut and smooth them and wet them so that I could see their grains. \r\n\r\nBack then there were no toys -we created them. The kites and the ships made by *anathrika*, [8] with a hen’s feather as a sail and an old blade as a keel to keep them floating. \r\n\r\nAs we were growing up, our ships improved, carved on wood with fabric sails. We used to through them up from the lighthouse when the west wind was blowing. We would run to the other side, where the dock was, competing against each other. \r\n\r\nI was sketching the old houses of Kyrenia with pencil on paper or on the back side of my uncle’s packets of cigarettes. \r\n\r\nThen I moved to Nicosia. I studied at the *Pancyprian Gymnasium*; new experiences, new context. We weren’t allowed to use the bike, because we lived in the old center of the town, so we went to school on foot. It was at that time when I started using watercolors. \r\n\r\nAfter my graduation from high school, I was determined to study architecture. My father was a tailor and, although he already knew about my decision, I remember him saying, ‘Within a year, when you will come back, regretful for your decision, please do not blame me for that.’ And after that: ‘You have two younger brothers.’  \r\n\r\nI knew that the word *architect* meant *the first among builders*. There was also a Chinese proverb I had heard years ago. It went like this: *I heard something and I think I remember it. I saw something and I remember it.* I made something and I know it. With that proverb in mind, I tried to construct whatever I could so that I would be more familiar with the builders’ language and with construction itself. \r\n\r\nFrom my first trip I brought back many stones and that caused me trouble at the customs office. I was lucky to meet Liperos Tsekkinis, a friend of my father -and co-worker of mine later on- who was a marble worker. He took those stones to his father, who cut them and burnished them, and it was then when I realised that what I was dreaming about was real: Pentadaktylos [9] was a mountain made of marble. \r\n\r\nThe Second World War began and I had to return to Cyprus after two years in university in Italy. I collaborated with George Paraskevaides back then. We built some houses, and I had the chance to observe how the builders worked, to learn many things from them that would help me later on as an architect. \r\n\r\nI used to sketch old houses as I was walking in Kyrenia, their flat roofs, their simplicity, the doors with the wooden parts, weathered by the rain. \r\n\r\nI went back [10] in 1947, after seven years of hiatus. During that period the British Council offered me a two-year scholarship for civil engineering studies. I told them I needed three years and they said, ‘Take that amount and we will see later about the rest.’ I asked them how was I suppose to pay off that scholarship, and they said that I would work in the government for five years and I could retire in thirty. ‘But then I will become a government employee,’ I said. “I have chosen to be an architect because I did not want to lose my freedom in any way.” When they informed me that I will not have any promotion, unless a senior employee retires, I immediately refused the scholarship, thinking that I didn’t want to pray for my senior’s death in order to get his position.\r\n\r\nDuring the war I worked on the project of the airport and the little money I earned would help me during my studies. I left Cyprus by boat -on the deck of course- and when I arrived in Italy I got another boat to Genova. It took me twelve hours to get to Milan by train. I began to study.\r\n\r\nI’d left Cyprus with a ‘suitcase’ full of experiences and questions, but also with a strong belief deeply cultivated since my childhood from those simple and plain Mediterranean houses.\r\n\r\nAfter I completed my studies in Italy, there were many good offers to stay there and an excellent proposal from a friend and classmate of mine, who invited me to Brazil. But I followed the lead of Odysseus, who did not stay on Calypso’s island. \r\n\r\nWhen I returned to Cyprus, the trend in architecture was to show off and bow to the client’s demands. I remember talking to the late Polis Michaelides, [11] an architect who had studied with Le Corbusier and who had built a house with Gothic arches near the Town Hall of Nicosia. When I asked him ‘Polis, how did you do that?’, he replied, ‘I copied the arches from the Doge’s Palace!” ‘Polis,’ I said, ‘I’m not commenting on *how* you did that, I just want to know the reason.’ ‘The clients were very rich and I just couldn’t refuse.’ I asked him whether his belief was based on his heart or his pocket. I …\r\n\r\n*The speech was interrupted*\r\n\r\nN. Michaelides: They say I need to end my speech.\r\n\r\nA. Stylianou: What we said, Mr. Michaelides, is that you have to conclude your thoughts, because we need to follow the schedule. \r\n\r\nN. Michaelides: But there is no timer here to give a warning. \r\n\r\nWe created a series of urban planning rules, but still with no mention about respecting the sun, whereas in the 5th century, in the city of Olynthos, there was a certain law forbidding any building from interrupting the insolation of another.\r\n\r\nTo the youngsters, I would like to say a few words: *They need to get to know our country, our real homeland. Not the one with those structures that are foreign to us, those 60-degree rooftops built on a drought-stricken island.*\r\n\r\nThank you\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nNotes:<br />\r\n<br />\r\n[1] The speech was transcribed and published in Greek in *Arhitekton* magazine, January/May 1992, issue 18, p.39.  <br />\r\n[2] *Dome* hotel was near the *First Tsiakkileri*, the last place where fishing boats and barges were constructed in Kyrenia. <br />\r\n[3] That ship was bought by Costas Katsellis, founder and owner of *Dome* hotel, in order to use its parts as firewood for the hotel’s cauldrons. Eventually, the material was never used because of the loads of smoke produced during the combustion. <br />\r\n[4] Andreas Kariolou (1925-1977) was the first Cypriot diver to discover the ancient Hellenistic shipwreck on Kyrenia’s seabed, which today is exhibited at the town’s fort. <br />\r\n[5] He means the sea’s blue colour. <br />\r\n[6] Captain Michalis Michaelides-Poupas was his beloved uncle from his father’s family. <br />\r\n[7] Place in Kyrenia. <br />\r\n[8] Wild plant, a giant fennel called *ferula communis*. <br />\r\n[9] Pentadaktylos, the mountain range of Kyrenia. Pentadaktylos is one of its many peaks. <br />\r\n[10] Neoptolemos Michaelides studied at Milan Polytechnic during the 1940’s. <br />\r\n[11] Polivios (Polis) Michaelides (1907-1960) was a Cypriot architect from Lapithos, Kyrenia who studied at the National (Metsovian) Technical University of Athens, worked at Le Corbusier’s office in Paris (1930-1932), had his own architectural office in Athens (1932-1945), and returned back to Cyprus, where he collaborated with his brother until his death.\r\n\r\nRina Katselli, *Neoptolemos Ant. Michaelides, the architect*, Laografikos Omilos Kerynias, Nicosia 2011, pp. 50-56.',NULL),(282,1,'2016-04-22 14:52:41','2017-06-04 22:53:59',148,'POINTâ€“ELENEIO: THREE WORKSHOPS',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'workshops',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\nA series of workshops were designed and implemented around the three major exhibitions organised by Point and hosted in its galleries between October 2014 and April 2015. \r\n\r\nThe workshops were tailored to the needs of Eleneio Elementary School’s students.\r\n\r\n31.10 – 29.11.2014:\r\n<br />Yiannis Chistofides\r\n<br />[*The Blind Ear*: ‘Connecting Senses’](http://dev.o-r-g.com/point/annual-reports/2015/the-blind-ear-workshop) \r\n\r\n05.12.2014 – 31.01.2015:\r\n<br />Hélène Binet\r\n<br />[*Maria and Neoptolemos Micahelides’ Residence by Neoptolemos Michaeleides*: ‘Urban Footsteps’](http://dev.o-r-g.com/point/annual-reports/2015/urban-footsteps)  \r\n\r\n07.03 – 08.05.2015:\r\n<br />Christodoulos Panayiotou\r\n<br />[*Stories from the Lives of My Friends*: ‘Exploring Objects’ Secrets’](http://dev.o-r-g.com/point/annual-reports/2015/exploring-objects-secrets)',NULL),(283,1,'2016-04-22 15:38:54','2017-06-04 22:47:26',149,'â€˜CONNECTING SENSESâ€™ WORKSHOP',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the-blind-ear-workshop',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\nIntroduction:\r\n\r\nYiannis Christofides’ sound installation *The Blind Ear* constitutes the first exhibition to be included in Point Centre’s educational programme formed in partnership with Eleneio Primary School. The educational workshop designed by the organisation’s learning team was carried out on 20 and 28 November 2014 with the participation of all school years.\r\n\r\nContemporary art practices often move beyond the confines of our traditional notion of what a work of art should be or look like. Yiannis Christofides’ *The Blind Ear* is no exception. It invites us to comprehend, perceive and appreciate even the most trite sound in its purest form—as the music of our everday lives. Drawing from the artist’s own ‘consideration of the interdependencies and interactions’ taking place ‘between different sensory faculties’, the educational workshop *Connecting Senses* invites students to engage with the notion of sound synaesthetically. Objects, colours, feelings, and sounds intermingle not only so as to trigger old memories and create new ones, but also to unveil the view that ’the multitude of subjective interpretations’ and differences describing our world are the attributes of its wholeness and uniqueness. \r\n\r\nPlease note that the workshop was designed and delivered in partnership with the artist Yiannis Christofides. The proposed learning activities were designed according to the needs and learning objectives of the specific workshop, but simultaneously remain in line with the general objectives of the educational programme. \r\n\r\nLearning objectives:\r\n\r\nThe proposed workshop encourages students …\r\n\r\n• To use their senses and bodies to respond to the artwork presented\r\n\r\n• To use their imagination and freely interpret the work of art\r\n\r\n• To be self-mobilised and develop their confidence and creative identity\r\n\r\n• To advance their personal skills while at the same time respecting the opinions and creativity of others\r\n\r\n• To work collectively and sustain team spirit\r\n\r\n• To comprehend that contemporary art has multiple forms\r\n\r\n• To become aware and sensitive to the local environment in which they live by recording and listening to its own soundscape\r\n\r\n• To identify that difference describes the whole by combining objects, colours, feelings and sounds to create their own artworks\r\n\r\n• To meet and work with the artist Yiannis Christofides',NULL),(284,1,'2016-04-22 16:09:41','2017-06-04 22:49:47',150,'â€˜URBAN FOOTSTEPSâ€™ WORKSHOP',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'urban-footsteps',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\nA Children’s Art Workshop\r\n\r\nIntroduction:\r\n\r\nThe *Maria and Neoptolemos Michaelides’ Residence by Neoptolemos Michaelides* is an exhibition featuring photographs by Hélène Binet. It constitutes the second exhibition to be included in Point Centre’s educational programme formed in partnership with Eleneio Elementary School. The educational workshop, designed by the organisation’s learning team, was carried out on the 16 and 23 January 2015 with the participation of all school years.\r\n\r\nThe photographs of Maria and Neoptolemos Michaelides’ residence taken by Hélène Binet and Petros Phokaides, and pick nick’s parallel readings, are important sources of information testifying to the outstanding work carried out by the architect Neoptolemos Michaelides. Both the photographs as well as the objects on display invite the viewer to comprehend the architect’s continuous effort to carefully marry the international elements of modernism with local architectural characteristics. The educational workshop ‘Urban Footsteps’ was created upon and inspired by these notions. The local and the international/universal, the specific and the general, the small and the grand are all presented and perceived within the context of a relationship of interdependence rather than that of conflict. From the house out to the city and from the city reaching out to the whole world, in this workshop the students are invited to envision and construct a town of their own. \r\n\r\nThe proposed learning activities were designed according to the needs and learning objectives of the specific workshop, but simultaneously remain in line with the general objectives of the educational programme. \r\n\r\n<br />Learning objectives:\r\n\r\nThe proposed workshop encourages students …\r\n\r\n• To develop and enhance their knowledge and vocabulary around the exhibition’s main themes (photography and architecture)\r\n\r\n• To consider notions of home, city (local) and global narratives (universal)\r\n\r\n• To consider the notion of urban life and the similarities and differences between different cities around the world\r\n\r\n• To comprehend the use of public spaces and to develop an understanding of the multicultural context describing an urban environment\r\n\r\n• To become young urban planners and use recyclable materials to create 3D objects\r\n\r\n• To use their senses and observation skills to engage with the photographs and objects on display.\r\n\r\n• To use their imagination and respond freely and creatively to the exhibits\r\n\r\n• To demonstrate initiative and development in their creative thinking\r\n\r\n• To advance their personal skills (conceptual and practical), while at the same time respecting the opinions and creativity of others\r\n\r\n• To work collectively and sustain team spirit',NULL),(285,1,'2016-04-22 16:24:17','2017-06-04 22:51:19',151,'â€™EXPLORING OBJECTSâ€™ SECRETSâ€™ WORKSHOP',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'exploring-objects-secrets',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\nA Children’s Art Workshop\r\n\r\nIntroduction:\r\n\r\nChristodoulos Panayiotou’s solo exhibition *Stories from the Lives of My Friends* constitutes the third and final exhibition to be included in Point Centre’s Educational Programme formed in partnership with Eleneio Elementary School. The educational workshop, designed by the organisation’s learning team, was carried out on 20 and 27 March 2015 with the participation of all school years.\r\n\r\nThe artist’s body of work is primarily interpreted within the confines of conceptual art, which encourages an in-depth reading of the ideas and contexts embedded in the objects and works of art presented. The educational workshop ’Exploring Objects’ Secrets’ was conceived as an attempt to introduce students to and bring them in contact with the ideas of hidden meaning, aura and history traced in objects and works of art and to assist them in freeing their thoughts and expression and using their observational skills and imagination to interpret the world around them.\r\n\r\nThe proposed learning activities were designed according to the needs and learning objectives of the specific workshop, but simultaneously remain in line with the general objectives of the educational programme.\r\n\r\nLearning objectives:\r\n\r\nThe proposed workshop encourages students …\r\n\r\n• To engage with contemporary art practices\r\n\r\n• To consider and discuss notions of Cypriot history and archaeology\r\n\r\n• To explore and investigate the ideas and contexts characterising and emerging from the exhibition’s objects and works of art\r\n\r\n• To discuss objects and works of art in reference to their materiality\r\n\r\n• To use their imagination to freely and creatively interpret their findings\r\n\r\n• To interact with images and analyse them using the Visual Thinking Strategy method\r\n\r\n• To use their senses and observation skills and support their opinions by presenting facts\r\n\r\n• To aesthetically enjoy the objects and works of art and express their impressions\r\n\r\n• To be self-mobilised and develop their confidence and creative identity\r\n\r\n• To advance their personal skills while at the same time respecting the opinions and creativity of others\r\n\r\n• To work collectively and sustain team spirit',NULL),(286,1,'2016-04-22 16:36:41','2017-04-15 20:20:33',230,'HAVIVA PEDAYA',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'haviva-pedaya',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br/>\r\nBio\r\n\r\nDr [Haviva Pedaya](http://www.daat-hamakom.com/team/prof-haviva-pedaya/) is a  poet, author and cultural critic born in Jerusalem in 1965 to a family of rabbis and kabbalists. She lives in Beersheba. \r\n\r\nShe studied at the Hebrew University and the School of Visual Arts in Jerusalem. Pedaya is at present Professor of Jewish history at Ben-Gurion University of the Negev, and head of the Elyachar Center for Sephardi Heritage. She has published articles on religion, sociology, art, history, and mysticism, as well as three full-length studies and three volumes of [poetry](http://www.archipelago.org/vol7-2/pedaya.htm). She is also involved in musical and artistic [projects](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=EB5ZyPpYtSg), and founded the Yonah Ensemble, which has succeeded in revitalizing liturgical and mystical music of the Near East. Pedaya has won many awards, among them the Harry Harshon Award, the Warburg Prize, the Bernstein Prize for Poetry (1997) and the President`s Prize for Poetry (2004).\r\n',NULL),(287,1,'2016-04-22 16:58:24','2017-04-19 21:08:47',232,'STEPHANOS STEPHANIDES',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'stephanos-stephanidis',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br/>\r\nBio\r\n\r\nProf. [Stephanos Stephanides](https://stephanosstephanides.com/) is a poet, essayist, [translator](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gPzepHQRnZs), cultural critic and documentary film maker. He is fluent in English, Greek, Spanish and Portuguese, [English being his dominant and literary language](http://iwp.uiowa.edu/sites/iwp/files/Stephanides_I_Land_Home.pdf). Selections of his poetry have been published in more than twelve languages, and he has held writing residencies and research fellowships in the UK, US, Italy, India and Greece. \r\n\r\n\r\nIn 1992 Stephanides joined the founding faculty of the University of Cyprus, where he is Professor of English and Comparative Literature. In 1989 he was awarded the poetry award of the Society for Humanistic Anthropology of the American Anthropological Association, and he has served as a judge for the Commonwealth Writers Prize (2000 and 2010). He was made Fellow of the English Association in 2003, and Cavaliere of the Republic of Italy in 2007.\r\n',NULL),(288,1,'2016-04-22 17:10:02','2017-04-15 20:33:50',237,'DEGE FEDER',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'dege-feder',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br/>\r\nBio\r\n\r\nDege Feder is an established dancer, choreographer and musician. She is the artistic director of the\r\n[Beta Dance Troupe](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jFBeMnezeBg) and is the founder of [Lela](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=iRMaMKId6-U), an Ethiopian fusion musical group dedicated to performing songs that she writes and performs. \r\n\r\nBorn in Ethiopia, in an Ethiopian Jewish majority village, she left her village to move to Israel. In 1998, she started studying at Haifa University, majoring in Arts and Education. During that time she danced and toured with Eskesta, an Ethiopian dance troupe. She also sang in different music groups and recorded dance soundtracks with the Israeli composer Oded Zehavi. She teaches Ethiopian dance and song workshops in order to bring the youth closer to their culture and make them proud of it.\r\n',NULL),(289,1,'2016-04-22 17:21:13','2017-04-18 06:35:04',227,'CULTURAL GEOGRAPHIES ',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'cultural-geographies',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br/>\r\n23.06.2015 – 01.07.2015\r\n\r\n\r\nPoint Centre for Contemporary Art hosted two events organised in cooperation with the Embassy of Israel in Cyprus under the theme Cultural Geographies.\r\n\r\n\r\n*Wandering, Walking, Trauma and Art*\r\n\r\nA conversation between Prof. Haviva Pedaya and Prof. Stephanos Stephanides\r\n\r\n\r\nTuesday, June 23 2015 | 20:00 \r\n\r\n\r\nA conversation about the geography of culture as a means of ‘mapping’, where and how certain modes of creativity and their traditions became uprooted and transported to new contexts and transformed. Prof. Haviva Pedaya, a philosopher, researcher of Judaism, Mysticism (East and West), Kabbalah and Hasidism, examines some light motives as walking, the two extremes of land and sea, between Jewish history and Israel. Prof. Stephanos Stephanides, a Cyprus based scholar, poet and cultural critic, will discuss the act of art and poetry as a kind of healing with Prof. Pedaya.\r\n\r\n*Dege Feder: The Voice of the Journey*\r\n\r\n\r\nPerformance and artist talk\r\n\r\n\r\nWednesday July 1 2015 | 20:00\r\n\r\n\r\nA performance with original Ethiopian music and dance. A musical journey that expresses the double identity, Ethiopian and Israeli, which Dege Feder, an established dancer, choreographer and musician, has embodied since immigrating to Israel as a child in 1985. Before the performance Point will host a conversation between the artist and actor, theatre maker, educator and cultural operator [Diomedes Koufteros](http://dev.o-r-g.com/point/annual-reports/2015/diomedes-koufteros). \r\n',NULL),(290,1,'2016-04-22 17:31:08','2017-04-18 07:19:38',238,'DIOMEDES KOUFTEROS',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'diomedes-koufteros',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Bio\r\n\r\n[Diomedes Koufteros](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mxjyowBkLFg) (MFA Acting, Brandeis University, Massachusetts, USA) is an actor, theatre maker, educator and cultural operator based in Nicosia, Cyprus. He is a part-time lecturer at the University of Nicosia’s Department of Music and Dance, where he has taught Mask Improvisation. In the past he has also taught at Brandeis University (USA), Satirikon Acting School (Cyprus) and been a guest lecturer at Boston University. As a producer and co-producer, he has worked on numerous projects including *Evelyn Evelyn*, *My Dying Body*, and *The Eye of Cassiopeia*. Between 2014-2015 Diomedes coordinated *Songs of My Neighbours*, an EU-funded theatre project between Cyprus, Italy and Poland, which aimed at increasing dialogue and social justice.\r\n',NULL),(291,1,'2016-04-25 09:13:40','2016-10-18 23:40:56',81,'CATALOGUE',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'displays-book',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(292,1,'2016-04-25 10:26:30','2017-06-18 12:45:59',158,'FRAGMENTS: SUBMISSIONS TABLE',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'fragments-submissions-table',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Here is the pdf [http://dev.o-r-g.com/point/media/00274.pdf](http://dev.o-r-g.com/point/media/00274.pdf)',NULL),(293,1,'2016-04-25 12:29:45','2017-06-07 21:20:00',183,'CONTEMPORARY MUSEUM AND EDUCATION PRACTISES: PROGRAMME ',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'programme',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(294,1,'2016-04-25 12:46:10','2017-06-07 21:18:13',165,'CONTEMPORARY MUSEUM AND EDUCATION PRACTISES: LOCAL COMMUNITIES MEET GLOBAL NARRATIVES',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'contemporary-museum-gallery-education-practices-local-communities-meet-global-narratives',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br/>\r\nAn International Conference\r\n\r\n22 – 23.05.2015\r\n\r\n<br/>Conference Description:\r\n\r\nIncreasing attention is being placed on the social responsibility of contemporary museums and galleries. The implementation of social responsibility projects and community outreach is often carried out through an institution’s education department.\r\n\r\nMuseums and galleries are no longer solely focused on what they present (collections and artworks), but also on their visitors and on ways to involve them in their practices. Galleries and museums have never before involved as many individuals through their diverse programming structures or fostered so many cross-institutional collaborations. This could, in fact, be interpreted as a direct result of the changing structure of funding mechanisms that have increasingly placed more emphasis on the involvement of diverse social groups and new communities. \r\n\r\nThe need to sing to the tune of multiculturalism has created museum and gallery educational narratives that aim to represent the voices of minority and marginalized social groups. At the same time, the notion of cultural diversity has been embraced by institutions even as the role of centres of art and culture in processes of regeneration and gentrification is acknowledged and accepted as a complicated one.\r\n\r\nThis conference, hosted by Point Centre for Contemporary Art and the University of Nicosia, is being organised in connection with Eleneio Elementary School within the framework of a local EEA-funded programme entitled *Promoting Anti-Discrimination through Arts Education for the Local Community*. The conference wishes to map out relevant knowledge and encourage scholars, professionals and practitioners to share good practices, educational and social theory, critical thinking, and on-the-ground expertise. \r\n\r\n<br/>Keynote lectures:\r\n\r\n‘Museum Education with Communities: Using feminist-hermeneutics to challenge prejudice and stereotype’ by [Dr. Viv Golding](http://dev.o-r-g.com/point/annual-reports/2015/viv-golding), President of ICME, Programme Director of Learning & Visitor Studies, Senior Lecturer in Communication and Education, School of Museum Studies, University of Leicester\r\n\r\n‘Poetic spaces = Ethical Languages: Laboratories of Art & Social Practice in Brazil’ by [Jessica Gogan](http://dev.o-r-g.com/point/annual-reports/2015/jessica-gogan), Director of Instituto MESA, Rio de Janeiro, PhD candidate in Art History at the University of Pittsburgh, USA\r\n\r\n<br/>Conference Abstracts [Wordcloud](http://dev.o-r-g.com/point/annual-reports/2015/international-conference)\r\n\r\n<br/>[Workshops](http://dev.o-r-g.com/point/annual-reports/2015/298)',NULL),(295,0,'2016-04-25 14:36:47','2016-04-28 18:15:54',156,'THE SOUND AND THE CITY: A SOUND WALK',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the-sound-and-the-city-a-sound-walk',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Activity 1\r\n\r\n\r\nNote: The first activity is initiated at the school’s premises, is carried out during the students’ transfer to the art centre and is completed upon arrival at the art centre.  \r\n\r\nWe commence by meeting the students at the school’s premises and introduce them to the artist (Yiannis Christofides). We ask students to imagine and discuss about the sound that represents each the most. E.g. «If you were a sound, which one do you think you would be? », «Is there a sound that could describe you or your personality? »\r\n\r\nThe artist encourages students to participate in a game that requires them to carefully listen and remember as many sounds as possible during the walk from the school to the art centre. E.g. « We are part of the city, but we never listen to what it has to say to us. Wouldn’t it be nice if today we let it talk to us? Let’s play a game – we will start by listening to the sounds close to us, we will try and remember them, and then we will attempt to hear the ones that are further away. Let’s see how many each of us can remember! » \r\n\r\nDuring the route from the school to the art centre the students can discuss between them any sound that catches their attention, but we also encourage them to reflect on their own. \r\n\r\nUpon arrival at the art centre, we ask students to respond to a set of questions regarding the set of sounds each managed to pick up. E.g.  «What kind of sounds did we listen to on our way here? », «What type of differences did these sounds have? », «Which sounds were strong and which ones appeared more subtle? », «Which sounds did you prefer? », «What kind of feelings do they trigger? »\r\n\r\nThe activity is completed with an explanation of what a sound walk is, i.e. the amassing of different sounds captured during a walk at a certain place.  \r\n',NULL),(296,1,'2016-04-25 15:33:08','2017-06-07 19:48:41',167,'VIV GOLDING',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'viv-golding',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\nBio\r\n\r\nDr. [Viv Golding](http://www2.le.ac.uk/departments/museumstudies/about-the-school/people/dr-viv-golding) received her PhD in Museum Studies from the University of Leicester, UK in 2000. She is Programme Director of Learning and Visitor Studies and Senior Lecturer at the School of Museum Studies, University of Leicester.\r\n\r\nShe has been on the  editorial board of *Curator: The Museum Journal*; *Horniman Museum Publications*, and *Best in Heritage*. In 2013, she was elected President of [ICME](http://icme.icom.museum/), the International Council of Museums of Ethnography.\r\n\r\n(2015)',NULL),(297,1,'2016-04-25 15:39:01','2017-06-07 19:55:11',168,'JESSICA GOGAN',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'jessica-gogan',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\nBio\r\n\r\n[Jessica Gogan](http://www.haa.pitt.edu/news-events/jessica-gogan-colloquium) is currently a PhD candidate in Art History at the University of Pittsburgh, USA, as well as director of [Instituto MESA](http://institutomesa.org/?lang=en), Rio de Janeiro. She has previously served as curator of special projects at the Andy Warhol Museum in Pittsburgh. \r\n\r\nRecent projects include: *Contemporary Laboratory: Proposals and Discoveries of What Art Is (Or Could Be)* with the Latin American Art Institution Casa Daros; *Experimental Nucleus of Education & Art* at the Museum of Modern Art, Rio de Janeiro; evaluation of the expanded pedagogic project of the 8th Mercosul Biennial, Porto Alegre, Brazil, and the exhibition and residency by José Rufino at the Andy Warhol Museum, Pittsburgh, USA. She is also coordinator of the periodical [Revista MESA](http://institutomesa.org/RevistaMesa/?lang=en).\r\n\r\n(2015)',NULL),(298,1,'2016-04-25 15:58:33','2017-06-07 20:01:14',171,'CONTEMPORARY MUSEUM AND EDUCATION PRACTISES: WORKSHOPS',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'298',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />22.05.2015, 16:45–18:15\r\n\r\nWorkshop I: [Thinking Through Art with Local Audiences](http://dev.o-r-g.com/point/annual-reports/2015/workshop-i) \r\n\r\nJulie Carmean, Museum Educator and Coordinator of Professional Development for Art Around the Corner, National Gallery of Art, Washington\r\n\r\nJulie Carmean will present an interactive experience modelling Artful Thinking Routines and Gallery Education, facilitating two routines with a projected image of The Farm by Spanish artist Joan Miró. Individual art reproductions will also be given to participants. The group will play the Elaboration Game followed by the Creative Questions routine. The audience’s thinking will be made visible by recording group responses and participants will receive individual leaflets. A brief informational story will be told. The group will then divide into smaller working groups to write Word Pile Poems, using the words and ideas generated through the routines. The group will debrief the interactive experience by discussing the qualities of the routine, the role of information, and connections to literacy skills and community themes. Lastly, specific discussion opportunities will help participants consider next steps in planning arts-integrated approaches in their own settings.\r\n\r\n<br />23.05.2015, 9:30–11:15 \r\n\r\nWorkshop II: [Gender in the Cyprus Museum: Towards an Open Educational Package](http://dev.o-r-g.com/point/annual-reports/2015/workshop-handout) \r\n\r\nA Re Aphrodite project, proposed by Chrystalleni Loizidou, [Despo Pasia](http://dev.o-r-g.com/point/annual-reports/2013/despo-pasia), Evanthia Tselika\r\n\r\nThe conference participants are invited to actively explore the Archaeological Museum (the Cyprus Museum), an historic institution in terms of its archaeological wealth and its colonial heritage that may also be considered, as some have argued, a valuable example of a ‘museum within a museum’, due to the fact that it has remained curatorially intact for a number of years with only a few isolated recent attempts to update it to modern exhibition-design standards. Treating the Museum as a largely untouched educational resource, the workshop is proposed as an opportunity for international experts to collaborate towards an open source, independently produced educational package that will be made freely available online. As a starting point, it proposes a re-reading of the collection through the lens of non-prescribed gendered identities, as well as issues of the body in a more general sense. Participants are invited to divide into teams and work freely together to consider and propose activities and ways the collection could be approached. The results of the workshop will be made freely available online and all contributors will be credited as co-authors.',NULL),(299,1,'2016-04-25 16:23:33','2017-04-19 07:05:34',174,'JULIE CARMEAN',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'julie-carmean',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\nBio \r\n\r\nJulie Carmean holds a BA in Elementary Education from Oral Roberts University, USA, and an MA in Arts in Education from the Harvard Graduate School of Education, UK.\r\n \r\nCarmean works as a Museum Educator and Coordinator of Professional Development for [Art Around the Corner](http://www.nga.gov/content/ngaweb/education/teachers/art-around-the-corner.html), the National Gallery of Art’s outreach programmes to under-resourced schools in DC. She writes curriculum and educational publications, and plans and implements local and national professional development for classroom teachers and museum educators. She also teaches in galleries and studios, evaluates programmes, and presents at national conferences. Formerly, Julie taught elementary grades in underserved and Arts Integration schools. ',NULL),(300,1,'2016-04-25 16:43:52','2017-06-07 21:50:11',219,'KOSTIS VELONIS',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'kostis-velonis',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\nBio\r\n\r\n[Kostis Velonis](https://kostisvelonis.blogspot.com.cy) (b. 1968, Greece) studied Fine Arts and Aesthetics at Université Paris 8 (Maitrise, D.E.A) and holds an MRes in Humanities and Cultural Studies from London Consortium (Birkbeck College, ICA, AA, Tate) and a PhD from the Department of Architecture, N.T.U.A., University of Athens, Greece. \r\n \r\nRecent group shows include: *Adventures of the Black Square: Abstract Art and Society 1915–2015*, Whitechapel Gallery, UK, 2015; [*This is Not My Beautiful House*](http://www.kunsthalleathena.org/UserFiles/EN%20PRESS%20This%20is%20Not%20My%20Beautiful%20House.pdf), Kunsthalle Athena, Greece, 2014, and [*No Country for Young Men*](http://www.bozar.be/en/activities/5120-no-country-for-young-men), BOZAR, Belgium, 2014. \r\n\r\n(2015)',NULL),(301,1,'2016-04-26 09:51:21','2017-10-16 16:03:55',141,'POINTâ€“ELENEIO: OUTCOMES',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'outcome-descriptions',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\n<br />Among the outcomes of the educational project exhibited at Point were: \r\n\r\n<br />[Audiovisual Mapping](https://vimeo.com/164249358), a film and a sound recording by Eleneio elementary students\r\n\r\nFrom the workshop based on Yiannis Christofides’ exhibition *The Blind Ear*, an optional after-school activity executed with the help of teachers Pieros Kezou and Andri Moustaka\r\n\r\nHow is our (urban) environment structured and navigated and then interpreted and perceived? How do we recognise and agree on a city’s landmarks? How do we decide what’s notable or significant? Which of its layers do we notice and which do we ignore? What would Nicosia look like and sound like to us if we could encounter it afresh, removed from pre-existing associations and memories?\r\n\r\nWe gave a camera and a sound-recorder to Eleneio Elementary students and let them circulate it amongst themselves. We invited those who were so inclined to put together visual and acoustic documentation of their experience of the city outside the school day.\r\n\r\nThrough our workshops we had previously encouraged the students to think about urban pockets, unnoticed architectures and soundscapes, social corners, hidden stories, and overlooked places. Within all this, we also encouraged them to think of ways to present their own voices and perspectives.\r\n\r\nThe video also makes use of soundmaps of Nicosia produced during workshops on Yiannis Christofides’ exhibition *The Blind Ear*.\r\n\r\n<br/>[Sound and light piece – play session](https://vimeo.com/164257161)\r\n\r\nFrom the workshop based on Yiannis Christofides’ exhibition *The Blind Ear*\r\n\r\nThis interactive piece was developed with Yiannis Christofides specifically for his sound installation *The Blind Ear*. It was an experiment in active listening that invited the students (and later, at Urban Gorilla’s Fouskopolis, the passersby) to respond bodily to an abstract soundscape.\r\n\r\nEarlier we used paper and paint to capture Yiannis’s sound-piece in colour. We then performed our painting using the sound-making properties of everyday objects, and with this final invitation to play, we used movement and light to translate the piece with our bodies.\r\n\r\nWe asked ourselves questions like: How would we go about translating these sounds with movement? If you were this sound what would you move like? What if sound and movement and colour where one single thing?\r\n\r\nThis piece asks us to consider how difference characterises a whole by combining colours and movements and responding to sound to create a fleeting sensory experience.\r\n\r\n<br/>[Intervention piece](https://vimeo.com/164249321)\r\n\r\nFrom the workshop based on Hélène Binet’s exhibition *Maria and Neoptolemos Michaelides Residence*\r\n\r\nWe encouraged the students to respond to Point Centre’s exhibition of Hélène Binet’s photographs of Neoptolemos Michaelides’ architectural work. We asked them to do so performatively and kinaesthetically, and to think about ideas of the house, the home and their structures. We invited them to draw on printouts of Binet’s images.\r\n\r\nFor this activity we asked the older students to choose a copy of an image they wouldn’t mind putting up in their bedrooms and to respond to a series of questions while circulating the copy of the image among themselves. \r\n\r\nThe questions were: Come up with five words that relate to the image. What is your favourite room in the house and why? What would you tell Nicosia if it were a person? In which cities or countries do you feel at home and why?\r\n\r\n<br/>[Magic carpet](http://dev.o-r-g.com/point/annual-reports/2015/point-eleneio-exhibition-magic-carpet)\r\n\r\nFrom the workshop based on Christodoulos Panayiotou’s exhibition *Stories from the Lives of My Friends*\r\n\r\nThis piece responds to Christodoulos Panayiotou’s piece *Operation Serenade*, made up of a rolled-up red carpet from the Oscars. We took strips of black carpet from Yiannis Christofides’ installation (which accidentally got stained with tempera while we produced our colour-sound scores during our sound-themed workshops) and used them to hide objects and ideas. Although the results were meant to be secret, we couldn’t resist unfolding Constantinos’s snail, at the very least.',NULL),(302,1,'2016-04-26 09:56:38','2017-06-04 21:57:01',142,'POINTâ€“ELENEIO: THE CHILDREN ',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'an-exhibition-of-work-by',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br/>Μουχαμμάντ Σιαζίλ\r\n<br/>\r\nΜπεζανίδης Γεώργιος\r\n<br/>\r\nΜωυσίδης Ηλίας\r\n<br/>\r\nΤσερμίδης Ηρακλής\r\n<br/>\r\nGhinea George-Albert-Mihai\r\n<br/>\r\nΜουκουλισβίλι Λουκά\r\n<br/>\r\nΜουκουλισβίλι Νικολόζ\r\n<br/>\r\nΤσαντεκίδης Αχιλλέας\r\n<br/>\r\nΙορδανίδου Αλεξάνδρα\r\n<br/>\r\nKiknadze Nino\r\n<br/>\r\nΜουραντίδου Ηλιάνα\r\n<br/>\r\nΠαρτζίλη Κατερίνα\r\n<br/>\r\nSasheva Kamelia \r\n<br/>\r\nΑζναουρίδης Γρηγόριος\r\n<br/>\r\nΘεοδωρίδης Δαυίδ\r\n<br/> \r\nΒασίλειος Μοχάμμεντ \r\n<br/>\r\nΓεώργιος Ρεχάν\r\n<br/>\r\nΝαζί Χάιτερ\r\n<br/>\r\nΤαταρίδης Αβραάμ\r\n<br/>\r\nΧαουριάν Φίλιππος\r\n<br/>\r\nΑνθυμιάδη Βικτωρία\r\n<br/>\r\nΔεμουρτσίδου Μαρία\r\n<br/>\r\nΚαντάβος Αλάιβα\r\n<br/>\r\nΚχαν Φατιμά\r\n<br/>\r\nMoanta Mihaela-Miruna\r\n<br/>\r\nΜπούρνεβα Ραντοστίνα Κοσταντίνοβα\r\n<br/>\r\nΝικολαΐδου Συλβάνα Ράνια\r\n<br/>\r\nΣταύρου Έμιλυ\r\n<br/>\r\nΓκαρακλίδου Ιουλία\r\n<br/>\r\nΙωάννου Μαρία\r\n<br/>\r\nΠυσμένα Βικτωρία\r\n<br/>\r\nΧριστοδούλου Ελένη\r\n<br/>\r\nTakov Georgiev Ognyan\r\n<br/>\r\nΆγγελος Αμποβιάν\r\n<br/>\r\nΑντρέι Μοάντα\r\n<br/>\r\nΆλεξ Πετρονέλ\r\n<br/>\r\nΔημήτρης Τζεϊρανίδης\r\n<br/>\r\nΝίκος Τσαντεκίδης\r\n<br/>\r\nΣαμίρα Αλιέβα\r\n<br/>\r\nΕυθαλία Δημητρίου\r\n<br/>\r\nΝικόλ Δρουσιώτου\r\n<br/>\r\nΣαλόμια Νταμοτσίδη\r\n<n\r\nbr/>\r\nΝικολένα Χατζηαθανασίου\r\n<br/>\r\nAttelina Veselinova \r\n<br/>\r\nΑγαπίου Στέφανος\r\n<br/>\r\nΑρμέντσια Γιάννης Γαβριήλ\r\n<br/>\r\nΓεωργίου Μάριος\r\n<br/>\r\nΔημητρίου Χρίστος\r\n<br/>\r\nΠαρτζίλης Μάρκος\r\n<br/>\r\nΣαρίδης Αναστάσης\r\n<br/>\r\nJin Patrick Gustaham\r\n<br/>\r\nΜορφίτη Λορένα\r\n<br/>\r\nΜουραντίδου Γιολάντα\r\n<br/>\r\nΡεβαζισβίλι Ταμάρι\r\n<br/>\r\nΜωυσίδης Θεοχάρης\r\n<br/>\r\nΠαπαδόπουλος Λάζαρος\r\n<br/>\r\nΣαββίδης Σταντσιουλέσκου Κωνσταντίνος\r\n<br/>\r\nΣιακαλλής Αντώνης\r\n<br/>\r\nΧρυσάνθου Αντρέας\r\n<br/>\r\nΔρουσιώτου Μελίνα\r\n<br/>\r\nΜωυσίδη Βαλέρια\r\n',NULL),(303,1,'2016-04-26 10:20:25','2017-06-04 21:59:52',143,'POINTâ€“ELENEIO:  RELATIONSHIPS',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'point-eleneio-building-relationships',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\n<br />Afternoon Sessions:\r\n\r\nPoint\'s educational team partnered with Panayiotis Panteli, a teacher at Eleneio and a researcher specialising in multi-lingualism and inter-cultural education. Together they worked for the development and implementation of additional activities involving the 5th and 6th grade students attending the optional Eleneio All-Day School.\r\n\r\nThe afternoon sessions incorporated the results of a series of brief dialogic and improvisational activities. The workshops took a critical pedagogical perspective and attempted to engage with the students democratically, on a horizontal, dialogic, and collaborative basis, and to design creative learning activities that used as springboards their own interests and choice of subjects and engaged with their particular group dynamic. The afternoon class chose to split in two groups, one of which worked with the theme of a magic door, while the other chose to work around the theme of football. \r\n\r\n<br />Community events:\r\n\r\nActivities developed through the workshops were distilled and re-created as community events which addressed the local community, the community of Eleneio and the wider public. This included an [event](http://dev.o-r-g.com/point/annual-reports/2015/urban-gorillas) at Urban Gorillas’ Fouskopolis in the centre of Nicosia, an exhibition at the 2nd Diversity Arts Festival at Ammochostos Gate. \r\n\r\n<br />Community engagement:\r\n\r\nWe then met with the Eleneio Parents Association and with school alumni. Through these meetings, Point created an Alumni Committee to help fundraise and address certain needs of the school. The Committee was headed by the Parents Association and took on a life of its own, organising a large fundraising event for Eleneio, which was not, however, part of the Point-Eleneio Programme.',NULL),(304,1,'2016-04-26 10:56:59','2017-06-07 21:32:21',205,'HARRY POTTER AND THE MATRICIDAL PRINCE',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'presentation-excerpt',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\nA Comparative Analysis of the *Oresteia* of Aeschylus and the *Harry Potter* Series\r\n\r\nSupervisor: Jakob Stougaard-Nielsen, Comparative Literature, Centre for Intercultural Studies, University College, London\r\n\r\nAbstract:\r\n\r\nThis paper aims to compare the [*Oresteia*](http://public.wsu.edu/~hughesc/oresteia_summary.htm) of Aeschylus with J.K. Rowling’s [*Harry Potter*](https://www.pottermore.com). The starting point of the comparison is the epigraph from *Choephoroi* quoted in *Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows*. The paper starts with an analysis of the epigraph, tracing its connections to the plot of the *Harry Potter* books. This is followed by a comparison of the protagonists.\r\n\r\nSubsequently, the focus is on the comparison of the cosmogonic tone of the works, which is closely related to the recurrent serpent and lion imagery. The analysis is based on close reading, contextual information and secondary readings. The comparison, aside from revealing the striking similarities between *Harry Potter* and the *Oresteia*, leads to the questioning of the restoration of order in both works. Reading the works comparatively reveals an unsettling situation which indicates that order is not completely restored.',NULL),(305,1,'2016-04-26 11:05:15','2017-06-04 22:11:29',147,'POINTâ€“ELENEIO TEAM',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the-point-eleneio-team',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'</br>\r\nChrystalleni Loizidou <br />\r\nEvanthia Tselika <br />\r\nAndre Zivanari <br />\r\n\r\nwith:\r\n\r\nMarina Andreou <br /> \r\nNatalia Antoniou <br />\r\nYiannis Christofides <br />\r\nAnastasia Magniti <br />\r\nIoanna Maki <br />\r\nPanayiotis Panteli <br />\r\n\r\nin collaboration with the Eleneio Elementary School educators:\r\n\r\nLia Kitromilidou, Maria Pantzara, Andri Moustaka, Efi Magniti, Pieros Kezou, Aristi Parperi-Mihail, Mikaella Natar, Katerina Christaki, Sissi Psimolofiti, Nektaria Hadjithoma, Elena Tziampazi, and the school inspector Demetra Messiou\r\n\r\nplus thanks to the Eleneio Parents Association:\r\n\r\nEspecially Rena Fotsiou and Costas Georgiou and the Eleneio Alumni Committee\r\n\r\nand special thanks to:\r\n\r\nAnnie Damianou and Demetra Ignatiou',NULL),(306,1,'2016-04-26 13:11:06','2017-06-07 21:05:55',176,'WORKSHOP II',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'workshop-handout',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />Handout',NULL),(307,0,'2016-04-26 14:51:49','2017-06-04 21:30:20',NULL,'MAGIC CARPET',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'magic-carpet',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(308,1,'2016-04-26 14:54:07','2016-04-28 18:06:28',144,'SOUND PIECE IN COLOUR',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'sound-piece-in-colour',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(309,1,'2016-04-27 09:33:00','2017-06-07 19:58:32',172,'WORKSHOP I ',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'workshop-i',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />Handout',NULL),(310,1,'2016-04-27 10:31:53','2017-06-07 22:18:48',250,'FIRST ANNUAL CYPRIUS CIRCLE: â€˜PEOPLE OF CYPRUSâ€™  REPORT',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'people-of-cyprus',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\n07.2015\r\n\r\n<br />Introducing the idea:\r\n\r\nWe often talk about the two communities of Cyprus. Each of these two communities receives an education heavily oriented towards the so-called ‘mother country’, often neglecting our common history on this island. But in this way, not only is the history and background of the other community not taught, we also ignore a great number of other, much smaller but proud, communities living in Cyprus. This ignorance can lead to a distorted view of the island, its inhabitants and influences.\r\n\r\nVery few young people are aware of who or what the Maronites, the Armenians or the Latins are. In addition to these ‘other’ Cypriot communities, in the recent past, we have also seen a rise in the numbers of immigrants and refugees living among us—Syrians, Filipinos, Pakistanis, European Union nationals, Turks and many more.\r\n\r\n\r\n<br />Methodology:\r\n\r\nWe created a series of four informational animations titled *The People of Cyprus*, targeted mainly towards the youth. The main body of the work was carried out by students across the island and coordinated mainly by the [Cypriot Puzzle](http://www.thecypriotpuzzle.org), an informal youth group committed to informing and engaging the Cypriot public (mainly the youth) in constructive debate on the Cyprus Problem in its various manifestations. We contacted universities across the island and called students to contact us if they were interested. We created two teams of students (the ‘data team’ and the ‘design team’). This process took a month to be completed and the selected students were notified by mid-May.\r\n\r\nThe data team had four team members, two Turkish Cypriots and two Greek Cypriots, one of whom was a professional in the field and acted as a consultant for the data gathering. The design team consisted of five students and one professional animator, who acted as a consultant for the visualisation of the data gathered and the production of the animations. In both teams, members of the Cypriot Puzzle acted as coordinators and had little input in the actual production of the media content. Basically, the teams had considerable freedom and the Cypriot Puzzle acted as a facilitator of the whole process.\r\n\r\nA total of 26 individuals participated in the production of the four animated videos. A detailed list of names can be found in Appendix B. The whole project was carried out at the Point Centre of Contemporary Art, a space which was kindly given to us rent-free by the owner. From September onwards the production of the animated videos was carried out by professional animators and sound designers upon our request. You can find more information about them in Appendix B.\r\n\r\n<br />Data Research Team:\r\n\r\nThe data research started in mid-June and was completed by early July. There were two fulltime students researching *The People of Cyprus*, one part-timer and a professional who assisted the students. The first part of the research was devoted wholly to gathering data from governmental sources, particularly from the Census surveys. Unfortunately, the last census was carried out in 2011. Therefore, the data are representative of that year and cannot accurately depict the reality today. Up-to-date data, such as population figures, were difficult to find for 2015, and therefore all numbers in the videos should be viewed with caution and should only be used as approximations.\r\n\r\nThe second part of the research involved analysis of the data gathered from the census and other official sources. This analysis included, but was not limited to, the creation of population trends and graphs.\r\n\r\nThe last part of the research focused on an extensive list of secondary sources, such as articles, books and academic opinions. The data research team produced short summaries of the secondary literature and compiled them in a single document resulting in a 50-page report, which was then given to the design team, which used the most interesting material to produce the animation videos. Our data research team also visited academics from various institutions and had a chance to discuss and ask questions relevant to our research topic. A bibliography is provided at the end of this report, in Appendix A, outlining the official and secondary sources we consulted for our research.\r\n\r\nIt is hard to identify specifically which sources are used in each video, since the design team used as a reference the processed and analysed material of the data research team. The data research team carried out a quantitative analysis of all official/governmental data and generally of all data in numerical form and then carried out a qualitative analysis on secondary literature, which concentrated primarily on historical and cultural aspects of the people of Cyprus. All of the videos include data from both sets, i.e. the quantitative and qualitative data. All our sources are listed in Appendix A.\r\n\r\n<br />Design Team:\r\n\r\nThe Design Team started work in early July and finished by early August. First, the design team visited some museums, such as the Severis Foundation, in order to collect visual material that helped the team visualise the data gathered. In the first week the two teams worked together in order to finalise the animation scripts. The data research team provided and explained the analysis and process carried out on the raw data gathered. The rest of the time was spent designing, creating illustrations and ultimately converting them into animated media material with the aid of a professional animator and members of the Cypriot Puzzle, who facilitated the whole process. Most of the work of the design team took place at Point Centre of Contemporary Arts and we are very grateful for this gracious contribution from the owner.   \r\n\r\nWhen the Design team completed its work, the end products were given to a professional animator who carried out some minor adjustments and corrections. This happened between September and December 2015. The sound design and voiceover was recorded in November and the audio and visual were merged into the final product by early January 2016.\r\n\r\n<br />End Products:\r\n\r\nWe have created four animated videos, totalling eight minutes and consisting of high-quality illustrations. Moreover, we created a body of research material including analysis of quantitative data, such as population figures and other demographic data. We also produced summaries and abstracts of more than 50 secondary literature sources. We aim to make this research readily available to the general public for reference or further research on the subject. We also translated the English script into Turkish and Greek and made it available in the form of subtitles in the videos. \r\n\r\n<br />The Aim:\r\n\r\nThe aim of the project was to present the different communities currently living in Cyprus— their populations, languages, religions, times of arrival on the island, cultures, etc. Furthermore, we wanted to start a discussion about who the people of Cyprus really are, which we initially defined as anyone living in Cyprus for more than 2 years, and what each group’s respective role and stake is in the Cyprus conflict.  \r\n\r\nThe way we went about creating these videos was not simply as a means to an end. The process itself engaged youth from different communities who collaborated with one another. At the same time it gave them a chance to work on real life projects, improve their portfolio and learn about the Cyprus Problem by actually working on something relevant to it.\r\n\r\nThis project was undertaken by the Cypriot Puzzle, an informal youth group committed to informing and engaging the Cypriot public (mainly the youth) in constructive debate on the Cyprus Problem in its various manifestations. By looking at the island’s political problem as a puzzle of which each of us is a piece, we are helping bring to the foreground the multitude of opinions that define it. At the same time, we’re serving the aims and goals of our funding partners, Youthopia, since our videos raise significant issues regarding human rights and the rights of minorities on the island.',NULL),(311,1,'2016-04-27 10:57:39','2017-06-07 22:11:29',248,'FIRST ANNUAL CYPRUS CIRCLE: DEBATES',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'debate-i',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br/>\r\n<br/>09.07.2015, 20:00\r\n\r\n[Cyprus Circle I](https://vimeo.com/208752739)\r\n\r\n‘Will a truth commission investigating the 1963–74 atrocities help or hinder current solution attempts of the Cyprus Problem?’\r\n\r\nSpeakers: Dr Bulent Kanol, Dr Erol Kaymak, Dr Yiannis Laouris, Achilleas Demetriades\r\n\r\nModerator: Andromachi Sophocleous\r\n\r\n<br/>16.07.2015, 20:00\r\n\r\nCyprus Circle II\r\n\r\n‘Should Cypriot architecture be driven by context?’\r\n\r\nSpeakers: Dr Pavlos Philippou, Dr Rita Severis, Lora Nicolaou, Margarita Danou\r\n\r\nModerator: Branka Cuca',NULL),(312,1,'2016-04-27 11:54:32','2017-06-07 22:41:50',281,'THE DRUMHEAD: READINGS',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'312',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\nA series of readings by artist-in-residence Gerry Bibby \r\n\r\n<br />Press Release:\r\n\r\nBook Launch + PART I: Tuesday 10 November 2015, 19:00\r\n\r\nPART II: Sunday 15 November 2015, 16:00\r\n\r\nPART III: Friday 27 November 2015, 19:00\r\n\r\nAs might be readily assumed, the drumhead is the top, or head, of a drum. It has in times past come to perform the role of a mobile writing table, an ersatz altar, and a gathering point for orders to be heard when military campaigns were on the field.\r\n\r\nThe handsome sailor, Billy Budd, was sentenced to death by hanging after a drumhead court martial on the Bellipotent found him guilty in Herman Melville’s all-male story, taking its title from the condemned character. Melville began writing the novella *Billy Budd, Sailor*, in 1888. It was published posthumously in 1924.\r\n\r\nCommissioned by If I Can’t Dance, I Don’t Want to be Part of Your Revolution, and published by Sternberg Press last year, Gerry Bibby’s *The Drumhead* was written on the move. Natasha Soobramanien notes, ‘[It was] written in just six months, in six cities, in the space between three shows.’\r\n\r\nAlthough not as mobile as some media, the printed novel was compiled on a laptop. A lap is a lot easier to move around than a drum, and both it and a novel can find themselves in spaces they might never have expected to land. \r\n\r\nHenrik Olesen writes, ‘*The Drumhead* inaugurates a world of pure presence – (un)scrupulously amalgamating sexual politics, right-wing deliriums, and contemporary art.’\r\n\r\nAs one of the inaugural residents of Point Centre for Contemporary Art’s Residency Programme, artist Gerry Bibby will read the entirety of his novel over a series of gatherings at Point during his stay, the first of which will happen in the presence of Athens-based curator and fellow resident Evangelia Ledaki this Tuesday, 10 November 2015 at 7pm. Copies of the book will be offered at a special launch price.\r\n',NULL),(313,1,'2016-04-27 12:26:49','2017-06-07 23:08:44',287,'EVANGELIKA LEDAKI: STUDIO VISITS AND DISCUSSION',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'studio-visits-and-open-discussion',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\n2–18.11.2015\r\n\r\nAthens-based curator and art critic Evangelia Ledaki engaged in a dialogue with the local art scene through a series of scheduled studio visits followed by an open discussion. The studio visits were organised within the framework of Ledaki’s residency at Point (2015–2016) and happened 12–15 November 2015. The discussion took place at Point, 18 November 2015 at 19:00. In order to ensure an open and pluralistic process requests were accommodated on a first-come, first-served basis.',NULL),(314,1,'2016-04-27 13:14:58','2017-06-07 23:19:21',292,'VASSILIS CHRISTOFI',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'vassilis-christofi',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\nBio\r\n\r\n[Vassilis Christofi](http://cargocollective.com/vassilis) (b. 1990, Cyprus) holds a BA in Painting from Camberwell College of Arts, University of the Arts, London, UK.\r\n\r\nHe has participated in group exhibitions at the Municipal Gallery of Larnaca; EKATE, Nicosia; Zmart Gallery, Nicosia; Apothiki, Larnaca, and at Peri Technis, Larnaca.\r\n\r\n(2015)',NULL),(315,1,'2016-04-27 13:21:55','2017-06-07 23:18:31',292,'EVANGELIA LEDAKI: PRESENTATION OF VASSILIS CHRISTOFI',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'solo-presentation',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\n5.12.15, 15:00\r\n\r\nThe presentation, featuring paintings and drawings by the young Cypriot artist Vassilis Christofi, opened at Point and was curated by Evangelia Ledaki. On the day of the opening Ledaki had a discussion with Christofi on the occasion of their collaboration that emerged from the studio visits programme, implemented within the framework of Point Residency.\r\n\r\n<br />Artist’s statement:\r\n\r\n‘Everyone carries a room about inside him. This fact can even be proved by means of the sense of hearing. If someone walks fast and one pricks up one’s ears and listens, say in the night, when everything round about is quiet, one hears, for instance, the rattling of a mirror not quite firmly fastened to the wall.’\r\n\r\n– Franz Kafka, *The Blue Octavo Notebooks*\r\n\r\nMy practice involves paintings and drawings that deal with subject matter rooted in daily life and memory that feels both familiar and puzzling. A sense of precariousness emanates from the way memories co-exist and arrive at the present. The work attempts to make these experiences visible and to ground or to situate the viewer in relation to them. This is a starting point, through which themes of alienation, time, ritual and place emerge. The work is informed by a personal understanding of film and literature and ideas that emanate from them as they relate to experience.\r\n\r\nIn Yasujiro Ozu’s films, people’s lives are represented in such a way as to decentre the individual with regard to the objects that surround them, the rooms they inhabit, the cities they live in. Ozu’s pillow shots are particular film shots that serve no clear narrative function. They appear between scenes of dialogue and serve to transition from one scene of narrative information to the next. They operate both within a space relating to a linear, incremental projection of time relevant to the story, but also imply a sense of time independent from the narrative framework. \r\n\r\nThis suspended space, and the sense of time made possible as expressed within it, exist visibly and in relation to personal moments and suggest possibilities for reflection. I seek to activate, through personal subject matter, a sense of place, an apparently tangible yet fleeting presence.',NULL),(316,1,'2016-04-27 13:37:25','2017-06-07 23:24:28',295,'THOSE THAT BREAK ',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'those-that-break',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\nby Evangelia Ledaki\r\n\r\n<br />*Things that break*\r\n\r\nDistinction and division unavoidably lead to a process of loss. Parallel to the distinction itself, a transition takes place during which the divided entity reaches a dual state of understanding, a self-definition which includes an unavoidable crack and leads to the fragmentation of data. The two occurrences, the incision and the distinction, are not synonymous, they are interconnected, the second presupposing the first.\r\n\r\nThe word ‘distinction’ states a process. It creates the image of a movement – a piece distancing itself from another piece. Then the two remain distanced, standing still at a distance, each one separately. This position – to be accurate, these two positions, as well as the space between them – comprise what we call civilisation. Civilisation is defined through difference. Civilisation is, if we imagine it as a metaphor, like things that break. If things didn\'t break, we wouldn\'t have the world as we know it.\r\n\r\n<br />*There are some things that break*\r\n\r\nSome things are especially fragile, and even though not all things break, those that do cannot escape this fate. Such things are human relations. Not only relationships and friendships, but also alliances, agreements, compromises. All these things will crack at some point and sometimes will break. Independently of whether there is the chance of future reconciliation of the two surfaces of a broken thing, nevertheless it is established that this possibility is sporadically attempted. It was accepted that it must be confirmed whether they continue to fit together and consequently merge again, since they had, at a previous point, undergone an incision and in time seemed incompatible. In time, one might say that it seems impossible that these two surfaces were once compatible.\r\n\r\n<br />*Cyprus (one or two)*\r\n\r\nSomething similar perhaps happened with Cyprus. Any random Internet surfer or an almost clueless listener of international news might rationally wonder, ‘How many Cypruses are there?’. The question is not completely without basis, even if it suggests a certain, perhaps inexcusable, distance from things. The island itself is certainly an entity which cannot break. This is an unquestionable fact, which allows some kind of disturbance: the island, even if it is geographically a mass, has undergone other forms of breakage. In the specific case, the island has been divided. Among the various opinions, expectations and developments that have come about through various factors, there has also been a noticeable line applied to the ground that has since been called the Green Line. It is said that the Green Line was etched as a small accent by the hand of a British commander on a map in 1963, because there were some events between the communities that were to be settled in this manner. All the inhabitants today know the history, but few realise that this line in reality looks more like a dense adhesive substance, like glue, rather than a boundary.\r\n\r\nWhen I reached the island\'s capital, I stayed for a time near the Green Line. At the time I had not yet managed to form this useful image, which would have given my approach a rather cheerful attitude. On the contrary, I was in the awkward position that you find yourself in when dealing with something so intensely that you close yourself up in thought and time goes by slowly and without variation; where you almost cannot do anything else other than think of the one and only thing that you are dealing with, the object that rules your attention—and you can’t even admit that it interests you. At these moments I usually sat on the couch somewhat bored, thinking incessantly of the line until at some point the phone rang. While on the phone, I watched the TV, sometimes at low volume, which did not allow me to follow the speakers, and sometimes on mute. Most times, the news was on. I preferred Euronews because there was a programme which, without having timed it, I had the sense was repeating every seven minutes, and this repetition gave me great pleasure and functioned as an unofficial measurement of time. Whatever the case, one thing was for sure: I was not concentrating on the speakers on the phone. Between the two distractions, that of the TV and that of the phone, my concentration was attempting to remain focused on the informal object of my interest. And it is a fact that Euronews, with all its explicit images of bombardments, plane crashes, suicide bombings, mass wailing, grief and so on, kept me levelled as far as the enigma and the dead end I was experiencing in relation to the line. During all this, I was visualising a powerful image: I was going down a road, Ledra Street, and passing a small canopy, and the other canopies that were placed in order, not noticing the subtle signs. But even so, this moment I was so actively picturing in my head was not occurring. Only the image remained and repeated itself intensely, disturbing every other thought and errand, especially at times when I was home alone.\r\n\r\nI remember the first week, I heard the muezzin a little after 11 am. In the beginning I stood, focused my attention on the sound, then opened the window. Many times I didn’t do anything until the voice stopped; I observed it, listened carefully. After a few weeks, I don\'t remember even noticing it at all. Maybe I could no longer hear it, which even now impresses me. I cannot recall any moment in the past few days in that apartment when I stood to listen to the call for prayer from the other side of the line. I only remember that the days were going by and I continued to estimate possible routes that would lead me to the one or other spot I had found on the map or that I had discovered on the Internet, and as I sank into my thoughts, the image of the canopied road seemed more distant, and the line became more impenetrable and more visible. It was a merging that remained raw and if you tried even in your mind to cross it, your feet would stick to the green surface.\r\n\r\n<br />*Finally, the vertical route*\r\n\r\nThree weeks went by before I crossed for the first time. They seemed like months. When I eventually reached the other side, a tall thin man greeted me. He was not a stranger, he had been waiting for me and maybe I was a bit late. If he had not invited me that afternoon, I probably would never have gone. I know that this is not entirely true though. I would have certainly gone at some point, but it is not clear to me how, when and why. All this, of course, makes no difference because on that afternoon, I went.\r\n\r\n<br />*The text written afterwards*\r\n\r\nAs I was writing this small text, I thought of Simon, who I met in South Africa and with whom we discussed his own things that break and the apartheid as ‘aparthood’ in comparison to neighbourhood. Looking back on those conversations, I looked up *neighbourhood* in the dictionary.[1] The instance of close co-existence. And *aparthood*. Paraphrase of the Afrikaans word *apartheid*: the instance of separation.\r\n\r\n<br/>1. ‘neighbour’ is derived from the words *neah* (near) and *gebur* (inhabitant). It also relates to the words *bur* (residence), *bower*, the medieval Germanic *nachgebur* and the modern German *Nachbar*.',NULL),(317,1,'2016-04-27 15:15:35','2017-04-19 07:26:54',306,'LIFE ZONE â€“ LIFE POINT PROGRAMME',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'lifezone-lifepoint-programme',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\nTeam I: