Mediterranean. Her book in progress is tentatively titled *Stammering the Nation. Transnational Patriotism in the Mediterranean, 1800-1830*.',NULL),(408,1,'2017-03-14 11:57:32','2017-10-13 15:12:46',NULL,'KONSTANTINA ZANOU',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'408',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\nBio\r\n\r\n[Konstantina Zanou](https://columbia.academia.edu/KonstantinaΚωνσταντίναZanouΖάνου) (b. 1976, Cyprus) is a postdoctoral researcher at the Centre de Recherche en Histoire Européenne Comparé, Université Paris-Est Créteil. She received her PhD from the Università di Pisa in 2007 and since then has held research fellowships and teaching positions at the University of Nicosia, New York University; the Centre for Advanced Studies, Sofia, Bulgaria, and Queen Mary University of London. \r\n\r\nShe is the co-editor (with Maurizio Isabella) of *Mediterranean Diasporas: Politics and Ideas in the Long Nineteenth Century* (Bloomsbury, forthcoming July 2015) and the author of numerous articles on Greek expatriate intellectuals and national consciousness in the post-Venetian Adriatic, as well as on the spaces of the in-between in the Mediterranean. Her book in progress is tentatively titled *Stammering the Nation: Transnational Patriotism in the Mediterranean, 1800–1830*.\r\n\r\n(2013)',NULL),(409,1,'2017-03-14 12:02:55','2017-06-07 19:38:26',NULL,'EVANTHIA TSELIKA',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'evanthtia-tselika',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\nBio\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n[Evanthia Tselika](https://evanthiatselika.com/) (b. 1982, Cyprus) studied Fine Art and History of Art at Goldsmiths and SOAS and received her doctorate in Social Engagement through Arts from Birckbeck, University of London. She is Assistant Professor and Programme Coordinator of the [Fine Art Programme, University of Nicosia](https://fineartuniccy.wordpress.com). Her practice-led research has been exhibited in London, El Salvador, Cyprus, Greece, Mexico and Brazil, in venues such as the Nicosia Municipal Arts Centre, the Department of Antiquities of Cyprus, October Gallery in London, the Modern Art Museum of El Salvador, and the Federal University of Pelotas, Brazil, among others.\r\n\r\n(2013)',NULL),(410,1,'2017-03-14 12:07:57','2017-05-25 16:39:25',NULL,'DESPO PASIA',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'despo-pasia',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\nBio\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nDespo Pasia (b. 1969, Cyprus) is a museologist and museum educator. She is currently a PhD candidate at the UCL Institute of Education, University of London. Her research concerns the educational use of museum photographic archives and centres on a phenomenological investigation of children’s encounters with photographic constructions of gender in urban Cyprus between the 1940s and the 1960s.\r\n\r\nShe has curated contemporary art exhibitions and has designed educational programmes for archaeological, historical and contemporary art museums in Cyprus and Greece and the Erasmus+ and Marie Curie research programmes. Her research interests include photography, hybrid displays, museum studies and museum education.\r\n\r\n(2013)',NULL),(411,1,'2017-03-27 09:29:31','2017-05-30 23:17:12',NULL,'NENAD BOGDANOVIC',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'nenad-bogdanovic',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\nBio\r\n\r\nNenad Bogdanovic (b. 1975) is a Serbian/Cypriot musician and cultural and social entrepreneur. He holds an MA in Fine Arts from the P. I. Tchaikovsky National Music Academy of Ukraine and an MA in Cultural Management from Northumbria University, UK.\r\n\r\nSince 2002 he has performed as a soloist for the Cyprus State Opera and has given hundreds of concerts all over Cyprus, while teaching at the Music Lyceum in Limassol. He is the founder of [Jeunesses Musicales Cyprus]( http://jmi.net/members/jm-cyprus), within whose framework he initiated the creation of the Cyprus Big Band Jazz Orchestra and the Limassol Camerata Chamber Orchestra. Bodgdanovic also designs and manages international cultural and youth programs and EU funding applications. Since 2013 he has been the Executive Director of the Cyprus Symphony Orchestra.\r\n\r\n(2014)',NULL),(412,1,'2017-03-27 09:50:52','2017-05-30 23:17:45',NULL,'MONICA NICOLAIDOU',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'monica-nicolaidou',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\nBio\r\n\r\nMonica Nicolaidou is a production manager and producer. She studied Computer Graphics and Animation at the Instituto Europeo di Design in Milan, Italy. Her career is focused on the production of short and feature films and she collaborates mostly with Cypriot directors.\r\n\r\nNicolaidou received various awards for her work from international cinema festivals. Since 2007 she has been running her own production company, [Filmblades Productions]( http://www.filmblades.com/).\r\n\r\n(2014)',NULL),(413,1,'2017-03-27 10:07:59','2017-05-30 23:13:45',NULL,'STELIOS ANASTASIADES',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'stelios-anastasiades',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\nBio\r\n\r\nStelios Anastasiades studied Mass Media Communications at the University of Delaware, USA. In 1982 he founded the advertising company [TELIA & PAVLA BBDO]( http://www.tpbbdo.com.cy/), which later entered the global network of BBDO, handling and promoting many well-known international brands. Being the company’s CEO, he has led many successful projects. Anastasiades is also the President of the Cyprus Communications Agencies Association.\r\n\r\n(2014)',NULL),(414,1,'2017-03-27 10:23:31','2017-05-30 23:16:17',NULL,'MARIA A. IOANNOU',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'maria-aioannou',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\nBio\r\n\r\nMaria A. Ioannou (b. 1982, Cyprus) holds a BA in English Literature from the University of Reading and an MA in 20th Century Literature from King’s College London, UK. \r\nHer first collection of short stories, *The Giant Fall of an Eyelash*, received the Cyprus Literature Award for Newcomer Writer in 2011. She is one of the founders of  [Sardam]( https://sardamcy.wordpress.com/), an alternative literary readings festival combining reading with other art forms.\r\n\r\nShe collaborates with visual artist Marina Yerali, writing the short story series *Punctuation Points* for *Parathyro*, the cultural section of *Politis* daily newspaper.\r\n\r\n(2014)',NULL),(415,1,'2017-03-27 10:37:22','2017-05-30 23:14:14',NULL,'STELIOS GEORGIADES',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'stelios-georgiades',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\nBio\r\n\r\nStelios Georgiades works at the Ministry of Foreign Affairs of Cyprus. During his career he has been involved in many cultural activities both in Nicosia and Limassol. He is currently preparing a volume related to the history of Limassol’s carnival over the past 120 years entitled *Limassol Carnival, A Magical Story*. Georgiades is also a member of the Cyprus National Committee of UNESCO.\r\n\r\n(2014)',NULL),(416,1,'2017-03-27 11:28:03','2017-05-30 23:19:46',NULL,'GEORGIA DOETZER',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'georgia-doetzer',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\nBio\r\n\r\nGeorgia Doetzer (b. 1959, Cyprus) studied German, Social Sciences and Economics in Germany.\r\n\r\nShe was on the administrative board of various dance and cinema associations, institutions and committees of the Cyprus Ministry of Education and Culture, and has been involved in the cultural industry of Cyprus for the past 20 years. She served as the Artistic Director of Rialto Theatre, Limassol. She is now the Artistic Director of [European Capital of Culture Pafos 2017](http://www.pafos2017.eu/).\r\n\r\n(2014)',NULL),(417,1,'2017-03-27 12:13:53','2017-05-30 23:22:36',NULL,'PAOLA PAPACOSTA',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'paola-papacosta',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br / >\r\nBio\r\n\r\nPaola Papacosta holds a BA in Economics from the London School of Economics, UK, and an MA in Mathematical/ Quantitative Finance from Bocconi, Milan.\r\n\r\nAfter completing her studies, she worked for five years in an investment bank in London. Upon returning to Cyprus in 2011, she founded [*Cypriot and Proud*](http://www.cypriotandproud.com), an online guide to Cyprus’s places of interest, restaurants and nightspots, and various Cypriot creators.   \r\n\r\n(2014)',NULL),(418,1,'2017-03-27 12:26:12','2017-05-30 23:23:37',NULL,'ALEXIA ROIDER',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'alexia-roider',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\nBio\r\n\r\n[Alexia Roider]( https://www.alexiaroider.com/) (b. 1975, Germany) holds a BA in Film and Video from University of the Arts London, UK. \r\n\r\nSince 1998 she has been working in Cyprus as a film director, directing television commercials, corporate videos, documentaries and special events. She has worked on numerous independent film productions and on feature films. Her short film [*STYX*](http://www.styxmovie.com/) has screened at numerous international film festivals around the world and has received six major awards. In 2011 she was appointed Artistic Director of the [International Short Film Festival of Cyprus](http://www.isffc.com.cy/program-2011). She is currently the president of the Directors Guild of Cyprus.\r\n\r\n(2014)',NULL),(419,0,'2017-03-27 12:47:58','2017-04-03 13:18:58',NULL,'RITA SEVERIS',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'rita-severis',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\nBio\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nRita Severis, living in Nicosia, studied Philosophy and Journalism and conducted her PhD in History of Art. After working for Sotheby’s for 14 years, she opened her own antique shop.\r\n\r\nShe has been collecting artworks with her husband Costas since 1983. Together they founded [Costas and Rita Severis Foundation]( http://www.severis.org/). The Foundation’s Centre of Visual Arts & Research, inaugurated in 2014, hosts the couple’s collection, comprised of more than 1.500 works of art by artists travelling to Cyprus during the 18th, 19th and 20th  centuries; many Cypriot memorabilia; Cypriot costumes from the 18th to the 20th centuries, and more than 10.000 books.\r\nShe is the author on numerous publications on subjects related to the history and art of Cyprus, has curated a number of exhibitions and organsed numerous cultural events.\r\n',NULL),(420,1,'2017-03-27 13:23:24','2017-05-30 23:31:19',NULL,'LOUKIA LOIZOU-HADJIGAVRIEL',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'loizou-hadjigavriel',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\nBio\r\n\r\nLoukia Loizou-Hadjigavriel (b. 1959, Cyprus) studied History of Art and Archaeology in Paul Valery University in Montpellier, France, and also obtained a Museum Management Diploma from the Smithsonian Institute, USA.\r\n\r\nShe has long experience in the coordination, organisation and curation of exhibitions, seminars, lectures, publications and other cultural activities, and has been a member of many committees involved in the Cyprus culture-museum sector. From 1984–2014 she served as the Director-Curator of the [Leventis Municipal Museum]( http://leventismuseum.org.cy/home) in Nicosia. She is currently the Director of the A.G. Leventis Gallery. Hadjigavriel is also President of the UNESCO National Committee of Cyprus.\r\n\r\n(2014)',NULL),(421,1,'2017-03-28 11:40:45','2017-05-30 23:15:34',NULL,'HARIS IOANNIDES',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'haris-ioannides',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\nBio\r\n \r\nHaris Ioannides (b. 1972, Cyprus) studied Journalism in Albany, New York, 1995, and International Business and Marketing at Hawaii Pacific University, 1997, 2002 (BSc and MBA).\r\n\r\nEver since his repatriation in 2002, he has been employed by [Armida \r\nPublications]( http://www.armidabooks.com/), a company he now manages. Through collective efforts, the company has become an innovator in the local publishing industry with many successes to its name, including European Union literary awards and distinctions, multiple local awards, and a growing fan base all over the world. Armida was the first company in Cyprus to conceptualise and implement a strategy in the field of ebooks. \r\n\r\n(2014)',NULL),(422,0,'2017-03-28 13:17:20','2017-04-25 14:13:24',NULL,'PERIKLEOUS STUDIO',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'perikleous-studio',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\nThe architectural office and former family house of Neoptolemos Michaelides at 39 Perikleous Street, in Nicosia, was abandoned since the office’s closing in the early 1990s. The building and its contents were exposed to physical deterioration and most likely to theft for decades. Despite the considerable destruction, a significant number of architectural magazines and books remained on its shelves, but this important archival resource continued to be exposed to humidity, dust, and other forms of destruction. In light of these threats, some concerned individuals (architects Georgia Frangoudi, Aimilia Siandou and Petros Phokaides, and visual artist Kyriakos Lyras) rescued the material by collecting what remained in the architectural library of the office. In collaboration with the Cyprus Architects Association, which was in charge of safeguarding the building, the material was transferred to the Mesarch Lab of the University of Cyprus’s Department of Architecture, which began to clean, catalogue and make efforts to preserve the material for future researchers.\r\n\r\n*The volume was produced with the collaboration of Georgia Frangoudi, Kyriakos Lyras and Alkis Hadjiandreou.* \r\n',NULL),(423,1,'2017-03-29 10:14:44','2017-06-03 17:13:04',NULL,'SUBTEXT',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'subtext',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\nThe Method:\r\n\r\nThe theatre practitioner Stanislavski maintained that only 10% of what’s actually going on in our heads is expressed through words; the remaining 90% lies embedded in the script. This is subtext, and in Stanislavski’s own words ‘subtext flows uninterruptedly beneath the words of the text, giving them life and a basis for existing… It is the subtext that makes us say the words we do in a play.’',NULL),(424,0,'2017-03-29 12:44:34','2017-06-04 10:51:45',NULL,'CYPRUS CINEMAS',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'cyprus-cinemas',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br/>\r\n\r\nDescription\r\n<br/>\r\nCyprus, the idyllic “island of Aphrodite,” is better known as a site of conflict and division between Greek Cypriots and Turkish Cypriots, rather than for its film production. Constandinides and Papadakis work to rectify this dearth of information by discussing the ouevre of filmmakers engaging with the island\'s traumatic legacies: anti-colonial struggles, post-colonial instability, interethnic conflict, external interventions and war. Starting with the cinema of the 1960s, when the island became a republic, the collection focuses on the recent decades of filmmakers exploring issues of conflict, memory, identity, nationalism, migration and gender, as well as the work of filmmakers who chose to cooperate across the ethnic divide. Cypriot Cinemas utilizes a methodology that engages all necessary perspectives for an illuminating critical discussion: historical, theoretical and comparative (Greek Cypriot and Turkish Cypriot films in relation to regional film cultures/practices). While the volume develops a discussion based on the reading of the political in Cypriot films, it also looks at other film cultures and debates such as (s)exploitation films and transnational cinema.\r\nTable of contents\r\nAcknowledgments\r\n\r\n\r\nIntroduction: Scenarios of History, Themes and Politics in Cypriot Cinemas\r\nCostas Constandinides, University of Nicosia, Cyprus, and Yiannis Papadakis, University of Cyprus, Cyprus\r\n\r\n1. Archive, Evidence, Memory, Dream: Documentary Films on Cyprus\r\nElizabeth Anne Davis, Princeton University, USA\r\n\r\n2. Aesthetics, Narratives and Politics in Greek Cypriot Films: 1960-1974\r\nTheopisti Stylianou-Lambert, Cyprus University of Technology, Cyprus, and Nicos Philippou, University of Nicosia, Cyprus \r\n\r\n3. Cyprus Past, Present and Future: The Dervis Zaim Trilogy\r\nLaurence Raw, Baskent University, Ankara, Turkey \r\n\r\n4. Tormenting History: The Cinemas of the Cyprus Problem\r\nCostas Constandinides, University of Nicosia, Cyprus and Yiannis Papadakis, University of Cyprus, Cyprus\r\n\r\n5. Transnational Views from the Margins of Europe: Globalization, Migration and Post-1974 Cypriot Cinemas\r\nCostas Constandinides, University of Nicosia, Cyprus\r\n\r\n6. Women and Gender in Cypriot Cinema: (Re)claiming Agency Amidst the Discourses of its Negation\r\nNayia Kamenou, University of Cyprus, Cyprus\r\n\r\n7. Postscript Cypriot Cinemas: Borders of Categories and Categories of Borders\r\nCostas Constandinides, University of Nicosia, Cyprus\r\n- See more at: http://www.bloomsbury.com/us/cypriot-cinemas-9781623560027/#sthash.DjIgwk4K.dpuf',NULL),(425,1,'2017-03-29 12:46:32','2017-10-16 16:00:33',NULL,'CYPRUS CINEMAS',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'cyprus-cinemas',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br/>\r\nDescription:\r\n\r\nCyprus, the idyllic ‘island of Aphrodite’, is better known as a site of conflict and division between Greek Cypriots and Turkish Cypriots than for its film production. [Dr Costas Constandinides](http://dev.o-r-g.com/point/annual-reports/2013/costas-constandinides), and [Dr Yiannis Papadakis](http://dev.o-r-g.com/point/annual-reports/2013/yiannis-papadakis) work to rectify this dearth of information by discussing the ouevre of filmmakers that have engaged with the island\'s traumatic legacies: anti-colonial struggles, post-colonial instability, interethnic conflict, external interventions and war. \r\n\r\nStarting with the cinema of the 1960s, when the island became a republic, the collection focuses on filmmakers who have explored issues of conflict, memory, identity, nationalism, migration and gender, as well as the work of filmmakers who chose to cooperate across the ethnic divide. Cypriot Cinemas utilises a methodology that engages all necessary perspectives for an illuminating critical discussion: historical, theoretical and comparative (Greek Cypriot and Turkish Cypriot films in relation to regional film cultures/practices). While the volume develops a discussion based on the reading of the political in Cypriot films, it also looks at other film cultures and debates such as (s)exploitation films and transnational cinema.\r\n\r\n‘Introduction: Scenarios of History, Themes and Politics in Cypriot Cinemas‘ by Dr Costas Constandinides, University of Nicosia, and Dr Yiannis Papadakis, University of Cyprus\r\n\r\n‘Archive, Evidence, Memory, Dream: Documentary Films on Cyprus‘ by Elizabeth Anne Davis, Princeton University, USA\r\n\r\n‘Aesthetics, Narratives and Politics in Greek Cypriot Films: 1960–1974‘ by Theopisti Stylianou-Lambert, Cyprus University of Technology, Cyprus, and Nicos Philippou, University of Nicosia, Cyprus \r\n\r\n‘Cyprus Past, Present and Future: The Dervis Zaim Trilogy‘ by Laurence Raw, Baskent University, Ankara, Turkey \r\n\r\n‘Tormenting History: The Cinemas of the Cyprus Problem‘ by Costas Constandinides, University of Nicosia, Cyprus and Yiannis Papadakis, University of Cyprus, Cyprus\r\n\r\n‘Transnational Views from the Margins of Europe: Globalization, Migration and Post-1974 Cypriot Cinemas‘ by Costas Constandinides, University of Nicosia, Cyprus\r\n\r\n‘Women and Gender in Cypriot Cinema: (Re)claiming Agency Amidst the Discourses of its Negation‘ by Nayia Kamenou, University of Cyprus, Cyprus\r\n\r\n‘Postscript Cypriot Cinemas: Borders of Categories and Categories of Borders‘ by Costas Constandinides, University of Nicosia, Cyprus',NULL),(426,0,'2017-04-03 12:58:29','2017-04-03 12:58:48',NULL,'2016',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2016',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(427,1,'2017-04-03 12:59:26','2017-10-28 13:15:05',40,'2016',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2016',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'In the early days of 2016 Point’s first full time employee, Demetra Ignatiou announces that she will leave Cyprus in the Spring to move to Spain to study. She will be missed.\r\n\r\nAt the start of February Andre travels to Berlin to talk to Haris Epaminonda about her proposed work *Museum of Objects and Ideas*, a project that will concern Cyprus but will occupy neither a specific space nor a particular time. Haris’s aim is explore the acquisition of meaning by objects as they migrate across locations and eras. To that end she collaborates with the cultural geographer [Polina Nikolaou](http://dev.o-r-g.com/point/annual-reports/2016/polina-nikolaou). The subject is broad hence the choice of a theme is problematic. Books are bought, research trips are made, lists are drawn up, [Warburgia](http://dev.o-r-g.com/point/annual-reports/2016/warburgian) mood boards are assembled, buildings are imagined (with the help of the curator Pavel Pys) and on 16th September the full moon is filmed as it rises from the sea at 18.46. Haris has shows at both Rodeo Gallery in London (December 2016) and at the [Aspen Museum](https://www.aspenartmuseum.org/exhibitions/128-haris-epaminonda-vol-xxii) (March 2017) that touch on the project, but it remains a work in progress. \r\n\r\nAndreas Vrahimis, philosopher and long-time friend of Point, collaborates with fellow philosopher [Christos Hadijoannou](http://dev.o-r-g.com/point/annual-reports/2016/christos-hadjioannou) on a series of seminars concerning [phenomenology and the arts](http://dev.o-r-g.com/point/annual-reports/2016/phenomenology-and-the-arts). The [seminars](http://dev.o-r-g.com/point/annual-reports/2016/phenomenology-and-the-arts-seminars), the first of which is held on February 13th and the last on the 27th May, are well attended and, uploaded to [Soundcloud](https://soundcloud.com/user-281493574/sets/phenomenology-and-the-arts), they attract listeners worldwide. Contributions came from guest lecturers Dr [Zöe Dominique Sutherland](http://dev.o-r-g.com/point/annual-reports/2016/zoe-dominique-sutherland) and [Susan Kozel](http://dev.o-r-g.com/point/annual-reports/2016/suzan-kozel). As the weather got warmer discussions move to the garden. \r\n\r\nOn the 28th May the Cypriot artist [Socratis Socratous](http://dev.o-r-g.com/point/annual-reports/2016/socratis-socratous) opens his solo show [*Casts of an Island*](http://dev.o-r-g.com/point/annual-reports/2016/casts-of-an-island) curated by [Michelangelo Corsaro](http://dev.o-r-g.com/point/annual-reports/2016/michelangelo-corsaro). Socratis is a long-time friend of Point, a relationship cemented when he represented [Cyprus at the Venice Biennale in 2009]. As assistant curator of the national pavilion, Andre managed to procure, on Socratis’s request, an [Indian snake charmer](http://dev.o-r-g.com/point/annual-reports/2016/indian-snake-chramer) to live and perform in Venice for the duration of the event.  \r\n\r\nSocratis creates several dozen sandcasts of everyday objects. In the month before the exhibition, he passes by Point almost every afternoon to update Andre on the progress of the work via [photographs]() of his most recent creations. Once in the gallery, he takes several days to arrange the pieces into a [constellation of compositions]() on the lower floor. At first the plethora of objects that don’t make the final cut are packed way in the basement, but later they are retrieved and displayed in the form of an extensive [archive](http://dev.o-r-g.com/point/annual-reports/2016/catalogue) in the upper gallery. Point’s usual baker is unable to supply goods for the private view, so Socratis himself bakes a feast of olive and halloumi koulouri in various shapes and sizes: an edible echo of the abundance of works in the show.  \r\n\r\nThe exhibition closes on 16th July.\r\n\r\nThe Cypriot summer sets in. \r\n\r\nBetween the 10th and 18th September Point hosts [*Plus Motion: Live performance art series*](http://dev.o-r-g.com/point/annual-reports/2016/plus-motion-live-performance-art-series), the first performance art event staged by the artists’ collective [Sensorium Space](http://dev.o-r-g.com/point/annual-reports/2016/sensorium-space). On 9th September at 7pm four artists’ activities take place in the galleries. Various props are used including a wooden plank, branded sports bags, china tea cups of various patterns, a feather, red string and a ram’s skull. The aim is to “reach the outer limitations of a physical and mental exhaustion” for both performer and viewer. \r\n\r\nThe artist [Lito Kattou](http://dev.o-r-g.com/point/annual-reports/2016/lito-kattou), a graduate of the Athens School of Fine Art and a student the Royal College of Art in London, proposes a project on the theme of [“new materialism”](http://dev.o-r-g.com/point/annual-reports/2016/matters-as-pleasures-forces-as-things-bodies-as-matters). Encompassing both a collaboration with architects connected to the digital curating project at the [Cyprus Institute](https://www.cyi.ac.cy) and a duo of guest lectures, its first manifestation is a visit by the writer [Federica Bueti](http://dev.o-r-g.com/point/annual-reports/2016/federica-bueti). Not only speaking for four hours on the theme of [*Matter as a Wondering Substance*](http://dev.o-r-g.com/point/annual-reports/2016/matter-is-a-wandering-substance) on the 1st October, Federica also undertakes a series of studio visits during her stay in Cyprus. It is a fruitful, if somewhat exhausting few days. \r\n\r\nResponding to the second of the invitations initiated by Lito, the curator of the Kassel\'s Fridericianum [Susanne Pfeffer](http://dev.o-r-g.com/point/annual-reports/2016/susanne-pfeffer) arrives in Cyprus on the 24th November. She spends two days exploring the island, taking in its archaeological past, its political present, its food and its art scene. On 26th November she gives a [talk](https://vimeo.com/213121044) on her work in Kassel in the upper gallery. Meanwhile, in the lower gallery, Lito creates a digital installation titled [*Whistles of Surfaces*](http://dev.o-r-g.com/point/annual-reports/2016/whistles-of-surfaces) with her architect collaborators [Eftychios Savvidis](http://dev.o-r-g.com/point/annual-reports/2016/eftychios-savvidis) and [Charalampos Ioannou](http://dev.o-r-g.com/point/annual-reports/2016/charalampos-ioannou). The work is experienced through an Oculus Rift Virtual Reality device. According to the trio, the piece involves a collection of artworks that “inhabit the digital space as sound versions of their visual form dispersed in the environment as sonic areas.”\r\n\r\nBetween the 14th and 28th October Point hosts the Xarkis Festival’s first exhibition. [Xarkis](http://xarkis.org/) is an organisation that “envisages a Cypriot citizenry that is active, participatory and socially engaged.” The exhibition encompasses material from the [annual festival](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Qporw-txems) and reflections on that event. Among Xarkis’s aims is to explore links between contemporary art and design with folk and vernacular culture.\r\n\r\nArriving on the 17th October the artist duo [Julia Rometti and Victor Costales](http://dev.o-r-g.com/point/annual-reports/2016/julia-rometti-victor-costales) take residence. Almost perpetually in residence somewhere or other, the couple have no fixed abode, although for administrative purposes they live in Mexico City. In Nicosia they stay in a two-bedroomed apartment in the Old City. Over several weeks they explore the island and the city. Their idea for a piece, which will become part of a group exhibition *completely something else* curated by Jacopo Crivelli Visconti, is to project shadows cast by leaves on a set of curtains within the galleries. An echo of the shadows cast by leaves as the morning sun strikes Point’s wall-to-wall window, the piece also relates to a previous work by the artists. \r\n\r\nOn the 4th November [Petros Moris’s](http://dev.o-r-g.com/point/annual-reports/2016/petros-moris) solo show [*Transformation of Commons*](http://dev.o-r-g.com/point/annual-reports/2016/transformation-of-commons) opens. Described as “an evolving visual [essay](http://dev.o-r-g.com/point/annual-reports/2016/perpetual-prologue) […] that negotiates the transformative interrelations and the mutual stratifications of the material, technological and cultural environment”, it is created in collaboration with the Cyprus Institute, in particular with Professor [Nikolas Bakirtzis](http://dev.o-r-g.com/point/annual-reports/2016/nikolas-bakirtzis) who joins Petros for the opening [lecture](https://vimeo.com/212315907). In his initial proposal Petros writes, “The potential product of this artistic research is understood to be the combinational and structural production of textual work and visual systems, introduced as aesthetic interfaces exploring the relationships between digital and materiality, phenomena of the infrastructure and the archive, as well as the processes of knowledge production and cultural translation between Informational typologies and aesthetic forms.” In the gallery he displays ghostly renderings of archaeological objects. \r\n\r\nThe show closes on the 26th November.\r\n\r\nOn the 16th November the artist [Maria Loboda](http://dev.o-r-g.com/point/annual-reports/2016/maria-loboda) joins Julia and Victor in residence, moving into the same flat. Maria is interested in the plaster-casts of classical elements that are a feature of many Cypriot homes. Her work, a collaboration with fellow artist [Constantin Thun](http://dev.o-r-g.com/point/annual-reports/2016/constantin-thun) who joins her later, also becomes part of the exhibition ‘completely something else’.\r\n\r\n[*completely something else*](http://dev.o-r-g.com/point/annual-reports/2016/completely-something-else), a group show curated by [Jacopo Crivelli Visconti](http://dev.o-r-g.com/point/annual-reports/2016/jacopo-crivelli-visconti) opens on December 3rd. It is Point’s first group show and also its first exhibition to be advertised on [e-flux](http://www.e-flux.com/announcements/81268/completely-something-else/). \r\n\r\nBased in Brazil, Jacopo makes his first trip to Cyprus in May 2016. He visits archaeological sites and artists’ studios, among them that of [Angelos Makrides](http://dev.o-r-g.com/point/annual-reports/2016/angelos-makrides), a Cypriot artist born in 1942. Jacopo encourages Angelos to show his early conceptual work. Initially the artist is reluctant, but finally he relents. Two works from 1962, both wall hangings made from found wood, will become part of Jacopo’s exhibition. \r\n\r\nJacopo returns to Cyprus on the 28th November to spend a week installing the show. “This is not an exhibition about Cyprus”, he [writes in the gallery guide](http://dev.o-r-g.com/point/annual-reports/2016/text-by-jacopo-crivelli-visconti), “it aims at recreating an atmosphere rather than directly addressing a place, theme or a topic.” “A small displacement can change everything,” he concludes.\r\n\r\nAll the artists - Haris Epaminonda, [Mario García Torres](http://dev.o-r-g.com/point/annual-reports/2016/mario-garcia-torres), [João Maria Gusmão and Pedro Paiva](http://dev.o-r-g.com/point/annual-reports/2016/joao-maria-gusmao-pedro-paiva), [Phanos Kyriacou](http://dev.o-r-g.com/point/annual-reports/2016/phanos-kyriacou), Angelos Makrides, [Tiago Mestre](http://dev.o-r-g.com/point/annual-reports/2016/tiago-mestre), Maria Loboda and Constantin Thun, Christodoulos Panayiotou, Julia Rometti and Victor Costales, [Daniel Steegmann Mangrané](http://dev.o-r-g.com/point/annual-reports/2016/daniel-steegmann-mangrane) – attend the opening.\r\n\r\nJulia, Victor and Maria all leave Cyprus on the 6th December. Julia and Victor invite Maria and Andre to visit them in Mexico City.',NULL),(428,1,'2017-04-03 13:01:34','2017-10-12 16:34:37',NULL,'CHRISTOS HADJIOANNOU ',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'christos-hadjioannou',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br /> \r\nBio \r\n<br /> \r\n<br /> \r\n[Christos Hadjioannou](http://ucd.academia.edu/ChristosHadjioannou) (b. 1979, Cyprus) studied Philosophy in Old Dominion University, USA and Warwick University, UK and obtained his PhD from Sussex University, UK. His thesis was entitled *The Emergence of Mood in Heidegger’s Phenomenology*. \r\n\r\nHe is currently an Associate Tutor at Sussex University, UK. He has published essays on Heidegger and Aristotle; co-edited a book on *Heidegger on Technology* for Routledge, and has been commissioned to edit a book on *Heidegger on Affect* by Palgrave-Macmillan. \r\n',NULL),(429,1,'2017-04-03 13:31:19','2017-10-11 14:33:06',NULL,'PHENOMENOLOGY AND THE ARTS',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'phenomenology-and-the-arts',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\nSeminars led by Dr Christos Hadjioannou and Dr Andreas Vrahimis\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nFebruary – July 2016\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nPress Release:\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThis series of seminars, led by Dr Christos Hadjioannou and Dr Andreas Vrahimis, will focus on ideas about art and aesthetics developed by the twentieth century philosophical movement known as Phenomenology.\r\n\r\nA number of seminal texts in the phenomenological movement have devoted significant attention to the\r\narts, e.g. Martin Heidegger’s thought on the relationship between world and work of art, Maurice Merleau Ponty’s writings on Cezanne, Impressionism and perception, Roman Ingarden’s work on aesthetics, to name but a few. Phenomenological ideas have been influential in various fields relating to the arts such as architectural theory (e.g. in the work of Christian NorbergSchulz), the theorisation of acousmatic music (e.g. in the theoretical work of Pierre Schaeffer), literary theory (in particular through the influence of hermeneutics), visual art, poetry, drama, film, etc.\r\n\r\nThe seminars will begin by introducing basic concepts in the phenomenological tradition, and move on to a careful reading and group discussion of a selection of texts that relate phenomenology to the arts. Texts in the phenomenological tradition are often notoriously difficult to read, and require some guidance.\r\n\r\nThus, the seminar conveners will give a series of presentations that will acquaint the participants with the background of each text. These presentations will lead up to a series of group discussions in which the participants will discuss the texts from various perspectives, including those informed by more practical concerns regarding the arts.\r\nThe seminars are addressed to anyone interested in the arts broadly conceived (i.e. including music, architecture, dance, literature, film, etc), art theory, or philosophy. They will take place twice a month over a period of 6 months. They will commence on the second week of February 2016, and will run until the third week of July 2016. Each seminar will last for three hours. \r\n\r\nThe seminars are organised by Point Centre for Contemporary Art, where they will take place. They are undertaken in collaboration with the ‘Format’ group.\r\n',NULL),(430,1,'2017-04-03 13:33:56','2017-10-11 10:40:03',NULL,'ZÃ–E DOMINIQUE SUTHERLAND',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'zÃ¶e-dominique-sutherland',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br /> \r\nBio \r\n<br /> \r\n<br /> \r\nZöe Dominique Sutherland holds a BA in Continental Philosophy from Middlesex University, UK, an MA in Analytic Philosophy from King\'s College London, and a DPhil entitled *The Phenomenology of Conceptual Art* from Sussex University, UK. She is a Senior Lecturer of Philosophy at Brighton University, UK. \r\n \r\nSutherland\'s [research interests](https://brighton.academia.edu/ZoeDominiqueSutherland) include contemporary artistic practices, the politics of aesthetics, feminist theory and continental philosophy.',NULL),(431,1,'2017-04-03 13:56:35','2017-04-05 12:09:37',NULL,'FROM A PHENOMENOLOGY OF THE SENSES TO A PHENOMENOLOGY OF AFFECT',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'from-a-phenomenology-of-the-senses-to-a-phenomenology-of-affect',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\n27 May 2016 | 17:30\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nPress Release\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nA lecture by Professor Susan Kozel, hosted within the context of the *Phenomenology and the Arts* Seminars series.\r\n\r\n\'Subtle shifts in phenomenological practice from attending to the senses to attending to motion occurred in the fields of dance and performance over the past 15 years. Now I am interested in expanding phenomenological reflection to take into account both affect and the processes involved in devising or creating artistic works.\r\n\r\nThis has particular relevance when the area to be explored is under-determined and highly experimental, or when working in a multidisciplinary collaborative team where the vocabularies, techniques/technologies and goals of an artistic research project themselves are open to being shaped through the artistic process. Resonance, listening and affective exchanges take on greater significance, the archived traces of artistic processes (notes, journals, tangential thoughts) are in some ways as much of interest than the end product, and the scope for shared participation in a performative experience becomes an important consideration.\'\r\n',NULL),(432,1,'2017-04-03 14:05:42','2017-04-05 12:09:06',NULL,'THE USES OF PHENOMENOLOGY IN POSTWAR ARTISTIC PRACTICE',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the-uses-of-phenomenology-in-postwar-artistic-practice',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\n<br />\r\n16 April 2016 | 18:00\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nPress Release\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nJoin us on Saturday 16 April, 18:00 at Point for a workshop with Dr Zöe Dominique Sutherland. \r\n\r\nThe workshop will examine *The Uses of Phenomenology\r\nin Postwar Artistic Practice* and it is organised within the context of the *Phenomenology and the Arts Seminars*.\r\nBetween the mid1950s to the mid1970s, many parts of the world saw an explosion of experimental artistic practices. Though often radically diverse in artistic style, as well as in political position, many artists drew directly upon phenomenological theories, in the search for a fundamentally new orientation.\r\n\r\n\r\nThis workshop will draw out the distinct artistic responses to phenomenology during this period, with the aim of better understanding its reception.\r\n',NULL),(433,1,'2017-04-03 14:10:59','2017-10-12 16:46:37',NULL,'SUZAN KOZEL',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'suzan-kozel',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br /> \r\nBio \r\n<br /> \r\n<br /> \r\n[Susan Kozel](http://forskning.mah.se/en/id/kssuko) is a dancer, performance and installation artist and philosopher based at the School of Art and Culture, K3, Malmö University, Sweden. She is Project Director of Living Archives Research Project, funded by the Swedish Council (Vetenskapsrådet) Digitalized Society Initiative.  \r\n\r\nShe is the author of the book [*Closer: Performance, Technologies, Phenomenology*](https://mitpress.mit.edu/books/closer). Her forthcoming book (expected 2017) is entitled *Mobile Choreographies: Affect and Encryption in the Performance of Mobile Media*. Kozel has written extensively on phenomenology, dance and new technologies. \r\n',NULL),(434,1,'2017-04-03 14:33:03','2017-10-18 10:58:17',NULL,'SOCRATIS SOCRATOUS ',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'socratis-socratous',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br /> \r\nBio \r\n<br /> \r\n<br />  \r\n[Socratis Socratous](http://thebreedersystem.com/artists/socratis-socratous-artist-page/) (b. 1971, Cyprus), living in Greece and Cyprus, studied in Athens School of Fine Arts, Greece. \r\n \r\nSelected solo exhibitions of his work have been held at The Breeder, Athens; The Cycladic Museum, Athens, Greece ([DESTE Prize Award Shortlisted artist](http://deste.gr/deste-prize/deste-prize-2015/)), both in 2015, and Omikron Gallery, Nicosia, Cyprus, 2011. He has also participated in many group shows in Paris, Brussels, Thessaloniki, Tirana etc. Socratous represented Cyprus at the 53rd Venice Biennal 2009. ',NULL),(435,1,'2017-04-03 14:34:31','2017-10-17 11:58:46',NULL,'MICHELANGELO CORSARO ',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'michelangelo-corsaro',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br /> \r\nBio \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n[Michelangelo Corsaro](http://michelangelocorsaro.hotglue.me/) completed his curatorial studies at the IUAV University of Venice, Italy in 2012.  \r\n \r\nCorsaro was curator at Kunsthalle Athena, Athens, Greece from 2013 to 2015. Other selected exhibitions curated by him include *Handsome, Young, and Unemployed*, Komplot, Brussels, Belgium, 2016; *Heirs of the Greek Catastrophe*, Parallel, Vienna, Austria; 2015, and *The terrestrial globe is covered with volcanoes, which serve as its anus (G. Bataille)*, DADA DA Academy, Athens, 2014. Texts of his were published in *CAC Interviu*, *South as a State of Mind* and *ArtReview*, amongst others.',NULL),(436,0,'2017-04-03 16:29:48','2017-10-17 12:00:07',NULL,'INTERVIEW OF SOCRATIS SOCRATOUS BY SOPHIE DUPLAIX',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'interview-of-socratis-socratous-by-sophie-duplaix',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\n\r\nSophe Duplaix: The Venice Biennale project follows from a previous project of yours. Can you explain what motivated that project, where it came from?\r\n\r\nSocratis Socratous: I started to work on that project after an event which took place in August 2006 in the northern part of Cyprus1. \r\n\r\nThousands of palm trees had been imported there from neighbouring Africa, Egypt more precisely, as part of an attempt to add a more exotic, eastern feel to the local environment. Almost as soon as planting started along the northern coast, stories began emerging. Rumour had it that cobras’ eggs were hidden in the roots of these trees and what’s more, that these eggs had started to hatch.\r\nThe climatic conditions were ideal for the survival of the reptiles, and as snakes are not bound by political frontiers, the fear grew that they would be able to move freely to the other side of the island. The whole story remained stuck in my mind and I began a project centred on it, which I called *Naja Haje*, a work in progress. I first presented it in July 2008 in Paris in the context of *Paris/ Chypre - La Saison Culturelle Européenne*, and then the same year in Thessaloniki during *Action Field Kodra*.\r\n\r\nThis seemingly trivial incident with the cobras gave me a chance to explore and discuss the political situation on my island, Cyprus, where the two ethnic communities, Greek Cypriot and Turkish Cypriot, remain to this day separated by outside forces against their will, seemingly unable to find a way to coexist. Their political leaders are caught in a perpetual cycle of negotiations, with no obvious end in sight.\r\n\r\nS.D. What did your project consist of in Paris and Thessaloniki, and how did you develop it for Venice?\r\n\r\nS.S. In Paris, I showed a series of photographs in an art gallery about the story of the snakes and palm trees. I also staged a performance in a boat where there is a bar and a restaurant moored along the banks of river Seine. People gathered in the boat and they were shown a video on the theme of the cobras and the palms.\r\n\r\nThe curtains fell and when they came up, spectators were confronted with the arrival of a small boat carrying a palm tree, which was desperately trying to draw up alongside the big boat. Suddenly, it was no longer clear in people’s mind whether the whole story was going to come true or if it was all a masquerade. They never found out, since the small boat never managed to reach the one they were on. Then a girl recited a poem by the Greek Nobel Prize winner Giorgos Seferis *The Cats of Saint Nicholas* (1969)2, which has a lot of politically loaded metaphors.\r\n\r\nIn Thessaloniki, I showed a photo installation and a video, and I also did a performance. I was on a small boat together with a big palm tree, and we were tugged along by a larger boat. We moored at a dock where there was an actor who had just finished reciting the poem. She got on the boat and we left.\r\n\r\nFor Venice, I initially imagined a more complex project in three parts. The idea of a boat with a palm tree is still present. The boat is drifting along various canals in the city during the first five days of the Biennale’s opening. The interior and exterior of the boat are entirely decorated with graphics and there is a crew. \r\n\r\nThe tree is an Egyptian date palm, and the way it is mounted on the deck of the ship makes it look like an emerging cannon. The tree seems to be looking for a place to be planted -which should be the destiny of every tree. \r\n\r\nIn the city there are two snake-charmers in their traditional outfits: you can see them wandering with their cobra baskets, carpets and pillows, while stopping to perform from one place to the next (preferably on top of wells, including at the Campo San Stefano, at the Piazzetta dei Leoncini, or on the Esplanade close to the Giardini).\r\n\r\nThey live inside the Cyprus Pavilion, on the second floor of Palazzo Malipiero, in a part of the flat. A visitor has access to their room, which looks like an Indian-style bedroom, but can only see it through a glass window. They will be staying here for the duration of the Biennale looking after the snakes, which will be kept in a cage specifically designed for them.\r\n\r\nThe third aspect deals with transmission and the circulation of news, stories, and information about the project. It not only involves people intervening in various places (and you cannot be sure whether they are actors or people who, for one reason or another, feel implicated in the problematics surrounding the project and are reacting spontaneously).\r\n\r\nIt also involves all kinds of transmission “props”: flags, posters, flyers, newspaper ads, internet (the creation of a website with viral e-mails with people sending them to their contacts, thus generating a large number of unverified messages about the project).\r\n\r\nThese “props” deal with various versions and interpretations of the story, so that it is almost impossible to distinguish the truth from the untruth.\r\n\r\n\r\nS.D. What meaning do you attach to snakes and particularly cobras?\r\n\r\nS.S. Snakes are historically connected with Cyprus. It’s been said that in the 4th century AD, after a long period of water shortage (a phenomenon that still occurs today with water being shipped from Greece), snakes had infested the island.\r\n\r\nThen, Constantine the Great, together with Saint Helen -the first Byzantine emperors- sent a ship full of cats and set them loose to exterminate the reptiles. You can find echoes of this story in modern literature. In the aforementioned poem by Seferis, for instance, the author uses the metaphor of the snake to represent the evil conqueror, thus commenting on the political history of Cyprus. This poem is a very important part of my project. \r\n\r\nCobras are the co-stars of this project (together with the palm trees). The principal meaning I give them is that the cobras hatched in the northern part of Cyprus are crawling freely into the southern part, as if to unify the inhabitants of the island.\r\n\r\nSo the cobras, being snakes, are connected with the history of the island. But they also are imbued with many other meanings. In other religions and mythologies they have the place of a “royal” snake. Moreover the cobra is a snake-eating snake that feeds on its own species and can be found in almost all the neighbouring Middle Eastern countries.\r\n\r\n\r\nS.D. What does the boat meandering through Venice represent?\r\n\r\nS.S. The boat is part of the ritual. It is the medium which carries the history of the project (palm trees and cobras) and is connected with the boat that Constantine the Great sent, with the boat in the Seferis’s poem and even with the boats landing Turkish troops οn the island in 1974.\r\n\r\n\r\nS.D. What is the significance of the palm tree?\r\n\r\nS.S. It is an uprooted tree that needs to be replanted somewhere. It is the starting point of the story and also a part of the whole ritual. The boat is carrying the palm tree, and the palm tree is carrying the cobras and their eggs. The tree’s positioning invokes the idea of threat. \r\n\r\nIt is a tree that is connected with exoticism. It could, associatively, connect with an immigrant looking for a new home. These new homes often lack the infrastructure to welcome them and can even be inhospitable most of the time.\r\n\r\nIn a photo documentation made in the northern part of the island, you can see these palms, tired and weather beaten, trying to adapt to the new environment.\r\n\r\nThe palm trees carry their own story and supposedly some kind of invisible danger which has the potential to spill over into their new home. By way of a conclusion to the project, I shall ask the question of whether the palm tree is going to be planted, where it is going to be planted, and if it is going to flourish.\r\n\r\nS.D. How and where did you first imagine planting the palm tree?\r\n\r\nS.S. The idea was to conduct a performance on the opening day of the Cyprus Pavilion, but it would take place next to and inside the Giardini, where many of the Biennale Pavilions are located (should we say: the main ones?).\r\n\r\nThe boat would arrive at the waterfront of the Giardini and upload the palm tree which would then be carried on straps by the crew, like a procession of some kind, leading to the Greek Pavilion, where the tree would be planted. This site came immediately to mind since Greece stood for Cyprus in many cases and bears a sense of solidarity. It could also be symbolically connected with the systematic felling of palm trees in Athens during the military dictatorship (as it was characterised a non-Greek plant), so that the city would lose the image of a “developing African capital”. After this, the empty ship would set sail for the official opening of the Cyprus Pavilion.\r\n\r\n\r\nS.D. Together with the political meaning present in your project, you also raise ecological questions. How do you deal with them, conceptually and practically?\r\n\r\nS.S. Transplanting palm trees, along with the risk of bringing dangerous cobras to a new place or the risk that they will not adapt, deals with the idea of injecting alien species into the environment.\r\n\r\nIt is similar to what people do when they have pets and release them into the wild when they cannot look after them any longer -without anticipating the consequences of their actions. This question of pets also comes to mind when one sees the installation in the Cyprus Pavilion with the cobras’ cage and everything provided for them to be fed.\r\n\r\nWhether the cobras are there or not is to be imagined by the viewer, who is likely to experience the same strange feeling you get in zoos in the presence of the animals which you many never have the opportunity to see if you do not wait long enough.\r\n\r\nBringing the cobras into Venice raised many difficulties and provoked many refusals. But nothing is impossible… These procedures relating to the introduction of palm trees (and the question of whether they will flourish or not) as well as cobras (and whether they will adapt and be accepted or not) strongly echo those that immigrants searching for a new home have to face, giving a new twist to the ecological question.\r\n\r\n\r\nS.D. How do you deal with the gap between the first ideas you had for the project and the feasibility of its present form?\r\n\r\nS.S. I described an ideal project. I would have loved to see it through to completion in its original form. But some ideas that I originally had were difficult to realise, because they were not authorised by the Venice municipality or by the Biennale organisers for various reasons.\r\n\r\nPlanting a tree in the Giardini in front of the Greek Pavilion, for example, creates a problem with heritage regulations as it is a protected area. Likewise, having snakes stay in the Cyprus Pavilion for six months requires many precautions regarding animal protection.\r\n\r\nI chose to document these difficulties and make them part of the whole project: the refusals together with the entire bureaucratic process (messages and requests, etc.) are presented in the Pavilion, as well as other documentation related to the project: videos, photos and other unexpected things that occurred during the preparation of the exhibition and the performance. \r\n\r\nThis documentation does not have the character of a protest, nor does it bear a condemnatory or critical tone. It is simply a testament of a refusal.\r\n\r\nIn this way (asking for a permit, rejection, documentation), the realisation of the project resembles the everyday political reality of Cyprus characterised by continuous negotiations between the two sides. The procedure is closely connected with the notions of “public” and “private” (if something cannot be done in public, then it is done in a private place).\r\n\r\n\r\nS.D. Could you describe the Cypriot political context from the perspective of your own personal history?\r\n\r\nS.S. From a really young age in Cyprus, I had the opportunity to leave the house and wander a lot. I was wandering mostly in the wild. My only fear (fuelled by my childish imagination) was that one day I’d lose my way, cross the “dividing line” 3 and enter the other side. There would be nobody to save me and take me back home.\r\n\r\nThis fear kept growing as I grew older. When I started travelling abroad and would sometimes lose my orientation in a city, I was overcome by the same fear that I’d enter the occupied side. During my 26-month military service at the age of 17, I was stationed in an area called “Kokkina” (meaning “red” in Greek). The area took its name from the blood that was shed there during the intercommunal battles of 1964.\r\n\r\nThere is also a Turkish military base on this site, hundreds of miles away from the Turkish Cypriot –inhabited north. The Greek Cypriots who live there are cut off from the rest of the island and are mostly occupied with the production of wood charcoal (I have also created two of my other projects here: *Illegal Installation* and *My Own Strangers*). The area is of great political importance in the history of the island.\r\n\r\nI was standing guard at one of the checkpoints and my role was to open a gate allowing (or preventing) local people who had farms next to the “Buffer Zone” 4 from passing. One day, I mistakenly opened the gate to a couple of tourists travelling in a car. I had to notify the UN and luckily they made them turn back. At this same spot I saw (again while on guard) a huge unidentified land craft boat all of a sudden coming ashore on the beach in front of me. I was terrified, thinking that the Turks had launched an invasion.\r\n\r\n\r\nS.D. How did the recent changes in the political situation of your own country affect your work? \r\n\r\nS.S. Even though I live in Athens -which was the first place I visited outside Cyprus, and where I fell in love, matured, developed myself and created a large part of my work- I am often in a position to visit Cyprus, stay there and keep in touch with the island.\r\n\r\nI was present during the huge changes in 2003 (the opening of designated checkpoints along the Green Line) and 2004 (the rejection of the UN Referendum 5 proposed to settle the Cyprus dispute) and had the chance to visit the other side of the island for the first time.\r\n\r\nAll of this changed my work. After I physically crossed the line dividing my island in two and went to explore the rest of it, my work became more physical itself. At this point all the myths, the misconceptions and fears that I had in my mind just collapsed.\r\n\r\nI was feeling very free; all of a sudden, the world had grown bigger and became unified. It was the most enjoyable trip I ever made. What shook me was the natural environment, lying untouched and “abandoned” for 35 years. As a Cypriot saying puts it: ‘A man is his land, and his land, alas, in shambles’.\r\n\r\nAfter this visit to the Turkish Cypriot side, my work dealt more directly with nature. Nikos Xydakis, an art critic, has said about my work that it resembles a verse from the Greek poet Constantine Cavafy, raising the artificial and loathing nature. “Give me artificial flowers –porcelain and metal glories neither fading nor decaying, forms unageing.”6\r\n\r\nS.D. “Rumours” are a central theme for your Venice project. How do you articulate this idea with the political question?\r\n\r\nS.S. Rumours are the modern version of myths and legends. Creating myths is a social need. In troubled political situations, rumours run wild since they are fuelled by the unknown, insecurity and fear.\r\nTerrorism has assumed the status of this modern myth through rumours about eminent attacks with a consequence on immigrants who, because of their ethnic origin, often become the first suspects.\r\nIn other contexts, big corporations in the United States nowadays are employing people to create and circulate favourable rumours about their company, thus replacing the advertising industry. These people are not allowed, under contract, to reveal their connection with those corporations. Rumours are a kind of “folkloric” anarchistic expression and in some cases they serve as a way of “letting off steam”. \r\n\r\nS.D. Through the idea of rumours and snakes, you deal with the question of fear: could you elaborate on this?\r\n\r\nS.S. Fear is a feeling that has existed on the island throughout its history because of the political situation and also its geographic position. Rumours and fuss about cobras also created fear, since the Cypriots are not familiar with this kind of reptile. In this instance, it is the fear of the unknown.\r\n\r\nWhen it comes to the project now, cobras, which are an integral part of it, emphasise the feeling of fear, since many people are afraid to even look at them, or even visit the project, knowing that cobras are a part of it.\r\n\r\nThe archetypal terror (which rests on the basis of fear and religious awe) is spontaneously triggered when we confront these snakes, the sacred beings of the ancient civilisations with whom we share the oldest part of our brain (reptile brain). This gives the project a totally different dynamic.\r\n\r\nS.D. Rumours also pertain to noise. Is this “noise” emanating from the Cyprus Pavilion a tool to give the island’s political questions more visibility on the international scene where the public would not already be aware of the issues?\r\nS.S. Yes. In the same way that a barker was needed to gather people when a travelling theatre was approaching town, I think the rumours emanating from the project could serve as a kind of “barker” to persuade people to take a deeper look at the political situation in Cyprus.\r\n\r\n\r\nS.D. Do you think that through your work you can make a comment not only on the Cypriot political situation, but also on similar situations elsewhere in the world? If this is the case, do you think that the artist can play a part in changing history?\r\n\r\nS.S. The project deals with a variety of symbolisms but never addresses the political problem directly. Instead it uses a tale, a lot of parables. The viewer can be provoked by it and try to learn something about the actual problems of the island.\r\n\r\nI hope the project is open to a lot of different interpretations and will connect with people in other parts of the world who deal with similar problems. For example, the snake charmers in the project come from India and are the only ones that can charm the sacred snake or lure it out of its supposed hiding place (if we are to believe the rumours). These people not only add an exotic and ironic touch to the project but also strongly relate to the recent political history of India, which in many respects resembles the history of Cyprus (India, Pakistan, Kashmir, Bangladesh etc).\r\n\r\nI am convinced that an artist can not only change the history of art, but also the way people perceive the political situation of their country. An artist can approach or, to an extent, alter political issues in a totally different manner than a politician would do.\r\n\r\n\r\nS.D. In some scientific research on rumours, you find the idea that rumours are as unlikely as the theories trying to explain them. What do you think?\r\n\r\nS.S. At this point we meet poetry.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nNotes\r\n<br />\r\n1. In 1974, following a short-lived coup by Greek Cypriots and the forces controlled by the Athens junta, Turkey conducted a military offensive capturing approximately 37% of Cypriot territory. The resulting division enforced a strategic split between the Greek Cypriot and Turkish Cypriot communities to the southern and northern parts of the island respectively.\r\n\r\n2. See pages 50-54.\r\n\r\n3. Also known as the “Green Line”, this refers to the cease fire line that de facto divides the island of Cyprus in two. It was first established in 1964, and became impassable following the political events of 1974.\r\n\r\n4. The “Buffer Zone” in Cyprus is a United Nations-controlled security zone established at the limits of the areas occupied by Turkish armed forces. It runs for more than 300 km along the Green Line, and its width\r\nranges from a few meters in Nicosia to a few kilometers in other areas. \r\n\r\n5. On April 2004, the UN Secretary Kofi Annan proposed a new reunification plan which, following twin referenda, failed to be endorsed –certain key terms of the plan were judged to be unacceptable by an overwhelming percentage of Greek-Cypriot voters.\r\n\r\n6 From the poem Artificial Flowers (1903), in the collection C. P. Cavafy’s *Hidden Poems 1882-1923*, ed. G. P. Savvides, Ikaros Publications: Athens, first edition 1968 (Translated in English by. Peter J. King and Andrea\r\nChristofidou).\r\n',NULL),(437,1,'2017-04-05 12:17:39','2017-10-11 14:58:40',NULL,'CASTS OF AN ISLAND',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'casts-of-an-island',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\ncurated by Michelangelo Corsaro\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n01.06 – 16.07.2016\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nPress Release:\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n[Text](http://dev.o-r-g.com/point/annual-reports/2016/text-by-michelangelo-corsaro) by Michelangelo Corsaro, 2016\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nOne would be tempted to forget about wars, interethnic conflicts, refugees, borders, checkpoints, and the holes left by the bullets on the façade of the Ledra Palace Hotel. In front of the sand one would be tempted to speak of the sand and its long journeys, from Africa, to the Middle-East, to the Southern coasts of Europe. But the journeys of the sand follow the same routes of the people fleeing wars, interethnic conflicts, and poverty. \r\n\r\nOnce Socratous’ works are broken down into their constituent elements, it is possible to see how each of these elements is in fact a sign that carries a memory. Like words conceal their history within their etymology, Socratous\' sculptures become legible as soon as we interrogate their genesis. How to separate, in theory and in practice, the artwork from the place where it is made, with its affects, its memories, and its turmoil? In other words, any attempt to subject these works to hierarchies between their visual and conceptual execution would harm the complexity of Socratous\' practice: to speak of symbolism or of sheer beauty would be reductive. \r\n\r\nWhat is truly eloquent here is instead the identity of the artwork: their birthplaces are the workshops where Socratous chooses to work, asking for hospitality while altering their normal working routine; their colour is that of the sandstorms that sweep the  Mediterranean regardless of borders, or that of the old buildings that have been erected both in the north and in the south of Cyprus; their shape is determined by will and by skill, but by contingencies as well, like the shape of mountains and of broken things. \r\n \r\nWith a new series of works presented at the end of a Residency at Point, Socratous reflects once again upon the formalisation of issues of identity, contested territories, and displacement. \r\n',NULL),(438,1,'2017-04-05 13:05:28','2017-10-17 10:24:32',NULL,'SENSORIUM SPACE',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'sensorium-space',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\nInfo\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n[Sensorium Space](http://www.sensoriumspace.com) is a non-profit team founded on January 2016 in Nicosia. The association is dedicated to performance art and supports performance artists by making their art public in different spaces in Cyprus.\r\n\r\nSensorium Space provides a platform for national and international networking and promotes performance artists and performance art in itself. Through festivals, educative workshops and as well theoritical discourse it is the aim of Sensorium Space to bring closer the performance art toward the public of Cyprus.\r\n',NULL),(439,1,'2017-04-05 13:06:33','2017-10-17 10:22:18',NULL,'PLUS MOTION: LIVE PERFORMANCE ART SERIES',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'plus-motion-live-performance-art-series',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\n10-18.09.2016\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nPress Release:\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nSensorium Space proudly presents their first performance art event entitled *PLUS-MOTION: Live Performance Art Series* featuring five internationally renowned artists, [Dagmar I. Glausnitzer-Smith](http://www.dagmarglausnitzer.de), [Zierle & Carter](https://vimeo.com/zierlecarter), [Francesco Kiais](http://www.francescokiais.com) and [PASHIAS](http://pashias.art/) for the *PLUS-MOTION: Live Performance Art Series*.\r\nThe series will involve 4 activities that will take place at Point Centre for Contemporary Art in Nicosia on September 9 at 7pm. The artists will visit Cyprus for 3rd workshop entitled *The Marathon – Cyprus Performance Art Workshop 2016* to take place between September 10-18, 2016.\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nConcept\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nPLUS-MOTION: Live Performance Art Series is influenced from the Ancient Greek word *συγκίνηση* < αρχαία ελληνική συγκίνησις < συγκινέω-συγκινώ < σύν+κινώ’.\r\n\r\nThrough performance art each artist uses their body with movement and chosen materials as objects to become elements and to create distinct and unfamiliar relationships in live performance. The action externalises, communicates and shares inner concerns and sentiments with the viewers who witness it.\r\nThe objective of each artist is to present a situation and an image has been created through the aspiration, individual perception and the sentimental charge originated in the idea process. The roles of performer and viewer can be considered to reach the outer limitations of a physical and mental exhaustion and trails of fiction and reality merge on the threshold of conventional definition.\r\n\r\nCyBC (RIK) Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation is the Media sponsor for the cultural interventions. \r\n\r\nCampaign Coordinators: SLATE PRODUCTIONS – Videos, Campaigns & Events\r\nSupported by epitelesis – Performance Art Foundation & SPACE ZONE Productions\r\n<br/>\r\n\r\nSponsor:Cyprus Youth Board',NULL),(440,1,'2017-04-05 13:10:49','2017-10-12 11:41:23',NULL,'MATTERS AS PLEASURES, FORCES AS THINGS, BODIES AS MATTERS',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'matters-as-pleasures-forces-as-things-bodies-as-matters',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\nA two-part events program on New Material Cultures\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n01.10 and 26.11.2016\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nPress Release:\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nMoving beyond the discursive construction of a present reality, new materialism seeks to understand the relationship between what is conceived as reality and materiality. Described as the “material turn”, new materialism extends the ongoing deconstruction of the human-nature binary and opens up a space in motion that acknowledges the often unpredictable and unwanted actions of human bodies, nonhuman creatures, ecological, organic and machinic systems, chemical agents, and other participants of the life realm. By conceiving matter as an ongoing situation of possession towards modes of self-transformation, self-organisation and directedness, new materialism raises a speculation on ontological hierarchies.\r\n\r\n*Matters as Pleasures, Forces as Things, Bodies as Matters* intents to bring forward the ways in which art allows us to map the complex relations between nature and culture, between body, language and knowledge.\r\n\r\nTo what extent does the “material turn” within the context of cultural production take a different turn from the one of continental epistemology, philosophy and the humanities? How does the agency of matter, the materialistic nature of artistic practice, the embodiment of the creator in the production, the perception of matter networks and the notion of “truth to material” affect what we understand as the new materialism? \r\n\r\n*Matters as Pleasures, Forces as Things, Bodies as Matters* is organised by Point Centre for Contemporary Art in collaboration with Lito Kattou.',NULL),(441,1,'2017-04-05 13:18:01','2017-10-17 20:33:38',NULL,'FEDERICA BUETI ',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'federica-bueti',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br /> \r\nBio \r\n<br /> \r\n<br /> \r\nFederica Bueti (b. 1982, Italy) holds a BA in Media Theory and Communication Studies from Libera Università di Lingue e Comunicazione, IULM, Milan and an MA in Curating Contemporary Art from Brera Academy of Art, Milan, Italy. She is currently a PhD candidate at the Royal College of Art, London, UK. \r\n \r\nShe is editor of [*…ment*](http://journalment.org/author/federica-bueti), a journal for contemporary culture, art and politics. Her writing has appeared in numerous magazines, including *frieze*;  *XTRA journal*; *artagenda*; *CARLA*; *Flash Art* as well as in several artists’ monographs and critical anthologies. Bueti has curated a number of exhibitions and is member of IKT, International Association of Curators of Contemporary Art. \r\n',NULL),(442,1,'2017-04-05 13:22:07','2017-10-18 09:54:34',NULL,'MATTER IS A WANDERING SUBSTANCE',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'matter-is-a-wandering-substance',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\n01.10.2016\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nPress Release:\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nWhat is it that we call ‘materiality’? Depending on whether we approach the question from the field of science, philosophy, art, poetry, technology, or politics, what we call ‘matter’ changes. Yet, there is something we can agree upon; matter is like an awkward thing sticking out of your nose. It is a thing, and it is also more than that thing; it is the reality that comes with having a body, but also the possibility of moulding different realities for bodies. And bodies matter. What do you mean when you say that something matters to you? How does matter come to matter? How do artists, poets, philosophers or scientists think through matter? “Matter is a wandering substance. The mind feels a fatal attraction for the impossible; it turns the body into a tool, and a destination” – writes poet and artist Etel Adnan. In this session, through a series of examples drawn from the field of poetry, visual art, feminist thinking and quantum physics, we will discuss different approaches to the question of matter, and the implications of starting from the body/matter.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe session will be structured in three parts: a presentation, a reading session and an informal discussion.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nReading List:\r\n<br />\r\n1. [Etel Adnan](http://www.eteladnan.com), *From Seasons; From Fog; From Sea* (pp.537/544 and pp.552-591) <br />\r\n2. [Karen Barad](https://people.ucsc.edu/~kbarad/), *Posthumanist Performativity* <br />\r\n3. Karen Barad, *On Touching: The Inhuman that Therefore I Am* <br />\r\n4. Federica Bueti, *Lobsters, Brittlestars and Matter of the World* <br />\r\n5. [Eileen Myles](http://www.eileenmyles.com), *Everyday Barf*  <br />\r\n6.Jan Verwoert, [*Why is Art Met with Disbelief?*](https://translate.google.com/translate?hl=en&sl=zh-TW&u=http://www.heath.tw/nml-article/jan-verwoert-why-is-art-met-with-disbelief-its-too-much-like-magic/&prev=search) <br />\r\n7. [Lisa Robertson](https://www.poetryfoundation.org/poets/lisa-robertson), *lecture/reading* <br />',NULL),(443,1,'2017-04-05 13:24:43','2017-10-12 11:45:46',NULL,'SUSANNE PFEFFER',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'susanne-pfeffer',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br /> \r\nBio \r\n<br /> \r\n<br /> \r\nSusanne Pfeffer (b. 1973, Germany) studied Art History at the Humboldt University in Berlin, Germany. Since 2013, she has served as artistic director of the [Fridericianum Museum](http://www.fridericianum.org/), Kassel. She was artistic director at the Künstlerhaus Bremen from 2004-2006 and chief curator of the KW Insitute of Contemporary Art in Berlin from 2007-2012, curating amongst others exhibitions by Matthias Weischer; Emily Jacir; Jonathan Monk and David Zink Yi.  \r\n \r\nPfeffer also curated the Swiss Pavillon at the 56th Venice Biennale, with a presentation featuring the artist Pamela Rosenkranz, and has been named the curator of the [German Pavilion](http://www.deutscher-pavillon.org/) at the 57th Venice Biennale. ',NULL),(444,1,'2017-04-05 13:29:27','2017-04-05 13:29:27',NULL,'SPECULATIONS ON ANONYMOUS MATERIALS, NATURE AFTER NATURE, INHUMAN',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'speculations-on-anonymous-materials-nature-after-nature-inhuman',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\nPress Release\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nDrawing upon the context of three exhibitions which she curated at Fridericianum, *Speculations on Anonymous Materials*, 2013; *nature after nature*, 2014, and *Inhuman*, 2015, Susanne Pfeffer will present the current debates around new materialism.\r\n\r\nFocusing on the interrelations of visual and experiential qualities, relating natural and cultural matters, and examining technological novelties against human Susanne Pfeffer will talk about new materials in theoretical and practical aspects of contemporary art practice. \r\n\r\nThis event is part of the programme *Matters as Pleasures, Forces as Things, Bodies as Matters*, organised by Point Centre for Contemporary Art in collaboration with Lito Kattou.\r\n',NULL),(445,1,'2017-04-05 13:31:20','2017-10-18 10:00:07',NULL,'WHISTLES OF SURFACES',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'whistles-of-surfaces',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br /> \r\nPress Release:\r\n<br /> \r\n<br /> \r\n[Whistles of Surfaces](http://www.whistlesofsurfaces.com/) is a collaborative project by visual artist Lito Kattou and architects Eftychios Savvidis and Charalampos Ioannou. \r\nMain concern is the collection of artworks and digital artifacts that negotiate the manifestation of materiality and the potential of the sculptural form. The collection is hosted on the omonymous website page that acts as an archival interface. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nOn the occasion of the event *Matters as Pleasures, Forces as Things, Bodies as Matters* at Point Centre for Contemporary Art in Nicosia the collection was presented as an installation that brought together a curatorial process, the design of a digital environment and a spatial and bodily experience. The digital environment is a composition of spatial fragments that is experienced through Oculus Rift Virtual Reality device. The artworks from the collection inhabit the digital space as sound versions of their visual form dispersed in the environment as sonic areas. This conversion occurs as a subjective literary translation hovering between descriptiveness and poeticness as if the viewer would articulate his recorded impression of the work after his viewing. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe collection currently features Dorota Gaweda & Egle Kulbokaite, Enrico Boccioletti, Fenetre Project, Giacomo Rafaelli, Oliver Laric, Petros Moris, Phanos Kyriacou, Valinia Svoronou, Yves Scherer. \r\n',NULL),(446,1,'2017-04-05 13:43:26','2017-10-18 09:39:54',NULL,'LITO KATTOU',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'lito-kattou',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br /> \r\nBio \r\n<br /> \r\n<br /> \r\n[Lito Kattou](http://litokattou.com/) (b. 1990, Cyprus), living in London and Athens, holds a BA in Art from Athens School of Fine Arts, Greece and  the Akademie der Bildenden Kunste Munich, Germany and an MA in Sculpture from Royal College of Art, London, UK. \r\n\r\nSolo exhibitions of her work have been held in London, Bordeaux and Athens whilst she has participated in various group exhibitions in Paphos; Minnesota; Novo Mesto; Brussels; Milan; Gibraltar; Montegiardino; Berlin, and Thessaloniki.  \r\nKattou collaborated with the architects Eftychios Savvidis and Charalampos Ioannou in the project *Whistles of Surfaces*.\r\n',NULL),(447,1,'2017-04-05 13:49:19','2017-10-12 12:16:20',NULL,'TRANSFORMATION OF COMMONS',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'transformation-of-commons',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\n4-26.11.2016\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nPress Release:\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nPetros Moris’ work *Transformation of Commons* is structured as an evolving visual essay, a spatial and narrative construction that negotiates the transformative interrelations and the mutual stratifications of the material, technological and cultural environment. Formed as a synthesis between sculptural and textual production, the work develops through a series of visits by the artist at the Cyprus Institute’s Science and Technology in Archaeology Research Centre, in collaboration with Point Centre for Contemporary Art.\r\n\r\nInvolving a process of conceptual and poetic configuration, *Transformation of Commons* unfolds through conversing chapters. Constitutive material of these chapters is a series of aesthetic materializations of digital three-dimensional models that result from the computational processing of photographic archives, collected by the artist during his visits at urban, institutional and natural landscapes in Cyprus. Fragments of the geological and archaeological substrate, technologies of energy and information management, skins and structures from the inorganic and organic domain interweave in order to trace the historical, epistemological and morphological correlations between natural phenomena, technological infrastructures, the material and intangible manifestations of memory.\r\n\r\nIn *Transformation of Commons* Moris suggests a sequence of displacements on the horizon of matter and time. The movement between systems of knowledge production and sensorial witnessing, between archival documentation and formalistic treatise opens up to a combined field of speculation regarding the past and the future. The dialectics between the local specificity of the territory and the abstract nature of informational processes delineates a space of superpositions and assemblages. A common place of relations, frictions and perpetual translation.',NULL),(448,1,'2017-04-05 13:53:18','2017-10-12 12:31:37',NULL,'COMPLETELY SOMETHING ELSE',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'completely-something-else',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\ncurated by Jacopo Crivelli Visconti\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n3.12.2016 – 11.02.2017\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nPress Release:\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nParticipating artists: <br />\r\nHaris Epaminonda, Mario García Torres, João Maria Gusmão and Pedro Paiva, Phanos Kyriakou, Angelos Makrides, Tiago Mestre, Maria Loboda and Constantin Thun, Christodoulos Panayiotou, Julia Rometti and Victor Costales, Daniel Steegmann Mangrané\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nPoint Centre for Contemporary Art presents *completely something else*, a group exhibition that revolves around the notion of constantly-negotiated and undetermined spaces, gestures and shapes. Personal and subjective, the show was conceived to focus on the specificity of Cyprus by aiming at recreating an atmosphere, rather than directly addressing a place, a theme or a topic.\r\n\r\nPhysically and conceptually dense in some cases, almost rarefied in others, the works on show interact with each other as well as with the audience, like musical instruments tuning in a first rehearsal. Just like ancient statues emerging from the tautological descriptions that abound in archaeology books, they seem to aspire at merely \"being there\", without leaving much room for metaphors and metonymies.\r\n\r\nIt is often the case that the more tautologically precise a description tries to be, the more abstract, partial and misleading it becomes. It is possible, then, that the only way to talk about Cyprus is to talk about *completely something else*, as this exhibition tries to do. In other words, it is possible that by making a point of not addressing the subject directly, the exhibition will imperceptibly touch upon it, even if just for a moment.',NULL),(449,1,'2017-04-05 14:11:12','2017-10-18 10:53:15',NULL,'JACOPO CRIVELLI VISCONTI',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'jacopo-crivelli-visconti',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\nBio\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nJacopo Crivelli Visconti (b. 1973, Italy) holds a BA in Letters and Philosophy from University of Naples, Italy and a PhD from The Architecture and Urbanism College, University of São Paulo, Brazil.\r\n\r\nAs curator of the Fundação Bienal de Sao Paulo (2007-2009), he was responsible for the Brazilian Pavilion in the 52a Biennale di Venezia. Other selected projects as an independent curator include: *Héctor Zamora - Dinâmica não linear*, Centro Cultural Banco do Brasil, Sao Paulo, Brazil; *Sean Scully*, Pinacoteca do Estado de São Paulo, Brazil; 12 Bienal de Cuenca, Ecuador; *Liberdade em movimento*, Fundação Iberê Camargo, Porto Alegre, Brazil, and Alimentário, Museu de Arte Moderna do Rio de Janeiro, Brazil. He has published texts and essays in various magazines, such as *Ars*; *ArteIn*; *Interni*; *Art Monthly*; *Bien’Art*; *ArteContexto*; *Art Nexus*, as well as exhibition catalogues and artists’ monographs.',NULL),(450,1,'2017-04-05 14:12:51','2017-10-11 10:38:16',NULL,'MARIO GARCÃA TORRES',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'mario-garcÃ­a-torres',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\nBio\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nMario García Torres (b. 1975, Mexico) holds a BA in Fine Arts from University of Monterrey, Mexico and an MA in Fine Arts from California Institute of the Arts, USA. \r\n\r\nSolo exhibitions of his work have been, among others, held at [Stedelijk Museum](http://www.stedelijk.nl/en/exhibitions/mario-garcia-torres-a-brief-history-of-jimmie-johnsons-legacy), Amsterdam; [Kunsthalle Zürich](http://kunsthallezurich.ch/en/mario-garcia-torres); Wattis Institute for Contemporary Arts, San Fransisco; Museo Nacional Centro de Arte Reina Sofia, Madrid; Museo Madre, Naples; Hammer Museum, Los Angeles; Modern Art Museum of Forth Worth, USA.\r\n',NULL),(451,1,'2017-04-05 14:14:21','2017-10-18 10:47:17',NULL,'PHANOS KYRIACOU',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'phanos-kyriacou',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br /> \r\nBio \r\n<br /> \r\n<br /> \r\n[Phanos Kyriacou](http://www.phanoskyriacou.com/the_giant_midget/main.html) (b. 1977, Cyprus) holds a BFA from Middlesex School of Fine Arts and an MFA from Goldsmiths University London, UK. \r\n\r\nSolo exhibitions of his work have been, among others, held at Maccarone Gallery, New York, USA; Rupert, Vilnius, Lithuania; Thkio Ppalies, Nicosia, Cyprus; The Temporary Museum, Nicosia, Cyprus; Chypre Culture, Paris, France; Kinderhook & Caracas, Berlin, Germany; Salon Popular Berlin; Kreuzberg Pavilion, Germany; Altes Finamzamt, Berlin, Germany; Omikron Gallery, Nicosia, and Apotheke, Nicosia, Cyprus. He has also participated in a number of group exhibitions in Cyprus and abroad. Kyriacou represented Cyprus (along with artists Constantinos Taliotis, Natalie Yiaxi, Lia Haraki and Maria Hassabi) at the 55th Venice Biennale in 2013. ',NULL),(452,1,'2017-04-05 14:22:17','2017-10-12 12:37:19',NULL,'ANGELOS MAKRIDES',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'angelos-makrides',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br /> \r\nBio \r\n<br /> \r\n<br /> \r\nAngelos Makrides (b.1942, Cyprus) studied Sculpture in  Higher School of Fine Arts in Athens, 1961-1967, where his tutor was Thanasis Apartis.  \r\n<br /> \r\nSolo exhibitions of his work have been held in Nicosia, Athens and Paris. He has also participated, among others, at Alexandria Biennale, 1969; Sao Paolo Biennale, 1969; International Exhibition of Drawings, Rjieka, 1970; Paris Biennale of Young Artists, 1971; Graphic Arts Biennale, Ljubljana, 1973, and Venice Biennale, 1988.  His works are included in many public and private collections in Greece and Cyprus. ',NULL),(453,1,'2017-04-05 14:27:47','2017-10-18 10:59:28',NULL,'TIAGO MESTRE',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'tiago-mestre',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br /> \r\nBio \r\n<br /> \r\n<br /> \r\n[Tiago Mestre](http://tiagomestre.com/) (b. 1978, Portugal) studied Architecture in Lisbon and Sao Paulo. He also attended Maumaus Independent Visual Arts Study Program and an Advanced Course in Painting Ar.co. \r\n\r\nSolo exhibitions of his work have been held at Galeria Central; Kunsthalle; Galeria Virgilio, all in Sao Paulo, Brazil; Centro Cultural Sergio Porto, Rio de Janeiro, Brazil, and Belgium. He has, among others, participated in group exhibitions in Nicosia, Sao Paulo, Porto, Lisbon and Munich.',NULL),(454,1,'2017-04-05 14:29:01','2017-10-18 10:54:48',NULL,'MARIA LOBODA',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'maria-loboda',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br /> \r\nBio \r\n<br /> \r\n<br /> \r\nMaria Loboda (b. 1979, Krakow) studied Fine Arts at Hoch-schule für Bildende Künste, Städelschule in Frankfurt am Main, Germany. She was a visiting artist and scholar of the New York University and Steinhardt School of Culture and also received scholarships from the Dresden Cultural Foundation of Dresdner Bank and the Hessische Kulturstiftung, Germany. \r\n\r\nSolo exhibitions of her work have been, among others, held at Power Plant, Toronto, Ontario; Schleicher/Lange, Berlin, Germany; Museo Reina Sofia, Madrid, Spain; Frieze Projects, New York, USA; Andrew Kreps Gallery, New York, USA; Ludlow 38, New York, USA; Krome Gallery, Berlin, Germany; Maisterravalbuena Gallery, Madrid, Spain, and Ritter & Staiff, Frankfurt am Main, Germany.',NULL),(455,1,'2017-04-05 14:33:20','2017-10-18 10:13:52',NULL,'CONSTANTIN THUN',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'constantin-thun',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br /> \r\nBio \r\n<br /> \r\n<br /> \r\nConstantin Thun (b. 1986, Italy) holds a BFA from École Cantonale d’Art de Lausanne, Switzerland and has also studied at the Lee Strasberg Theatre and Film Institute, New York, USA. \r\n\r\nHe has participated in group shows in Paris, Basel, Venice and Oslo and his first solo exhibition will be held in 2017 at Galleria Fonti, Naples, Italy. Thun proposed the curatorial project *In One’s Own Time* in Naples, 2016, and has also collaborations in theatre plays and performances.',NULL),(456,1,'2017-04-05 14:40:06','2017-10-11 10:36:47',NULL,'DANIEL STEEGMAN MANGRANÃ‰ ',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'daniel-steegman-mangranÃ©',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br /> \r\nBio \r\n<br /> \r\n<br />  \r\n[Daniel Steegmann Mangrané](http://www.danielsteegmann.info/) (b. 1977, Spain) studied at the Escola de disseny i art and the Gris ART School of Photography, both in Barcelona. \r\n \r\nSolo exhibitions of his work have been held at [Esther Schipper](http://www.estherschipper.com/sites/default/files/DSM/2015_ES/Daniel%20Steegmann%20Mangrane%CC%81%2C%20Spiral%20Forest%2C%20Esther%20Schipper%2C%20Berlin%2C%202015_EN.pdf), Berlin; New Museum, New  York; CRAC Centre Rhénan d\'Art Contemporain, Alsace, Altkirch; Casa França Brasil, Rio de Janeiro; Uma Certa Falta de Coerência, Porto, amongst others.  He is one of the organisers of the experimental school Universidade de Verão at Capacete, Rio de Janeiro. Mangrané has been nominated for the [PIPA Prize for Latin American artists](http://www.pipaprize.com/pag/daniel-steegmann-mangrane/) in 2012, 2013 and 2014 and has received numerous prizes and fellowships. \r\n \r\n',NULL),(457,1,'2017-04-05 14:42:02','2017-04-05 14:47:14',NULL,'JOÃƒO MARIA GUSMÃƒO & PEDRO PAIVA',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'joÃ£o-maria-gusmÃ£o-pedro-paiva',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br /> \r\nBios \r\n<br /> \r\n<br /> \r\nJoão Maria Gusmão (b. 1979, Lisbon, Portugal) and Pedro Paiva (b. 1977, Portugal), living in Lisbon, have been collaborating since 2001. As an artistic duo they produce “poetic philosophical fictions” using the mediums of film, sculpture, photograph, installation and anthologies of texts. They have also published a philosophical journal, entitled *Efluvio Magnetico*.  \r\n\r\nSolo exhibitions of their work have been, among others, held at Fundação Eva Klabin, Rio de Janeiro; [Haus der Künst](http://www.hausderkunst.de/en/agenda/detail/capsule-05-joao-maria-gusmao-pedro-paiva/), Munich, Germany; [Aargauer Kunsthaus](http://www.aargauerkunsthaus.ch/en/exhibitions/archive/2016/?showUid=356&cHash=956593b5254204d13179d3b17b2fea82), Aarau, Germany; KW Institute for Contemporary Art, Berlin, Germany; REDCAT, Los Angeles; Camden Arts Centre, London; Le Plateau, Paris. They participated at the Gwangju Biennale, 2010; Manifesta, 2008 and the Sao Paulo Biennale, 2006.   Together they represented Portugal at the [53rd Venice Biennale](https://www.dgartes.pt/veneza2009/artistas_texto_comissario_en.htm) in 2009 and also took part in the 55th Venice Biennale in 2013.  \r\n \r\n\r\n',NULL),(458,1,'2017-04-05 14:45:42','2017-10-18 11:01:35',NULL,'JULIA ROMETTI & VICTOR COSTALES',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'julia-rometti-victor-costales',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br /> \r\nBio \r\n<br /> \r\n<br /> \r\nJulia Rometti (b. 1975, France) and Victor Costales (b. 1974, Belarus) have been collaborating since 2017. Julia Rometti studied at the Ecole Nationale Supérieure D’Arts Paris-Cergy, France and was a member of Glassbox, artist run space in Paris. Victor Costales studied at the Instituto de Diseño Grafico Latinoamericano, Quito, Ecuador, the Riccardo Bauer, Milan and the Instituto Italiano di Fotografia Milano, Italy.\r\n\r\nSolo shows of their work have been, among others, presented at Mx Gallery Merida, Mexico; Jousse Entreprise, Paris, France; CAC Synagogue de Delme, France; Delmesthalle Basel; Germany; Casa del Lago, Mexico City, and Midway Contemporary Art, Minneapolis, USA. Together they participated in various residency programmes all over the word. ',NULL),(459,1,'2017-04-05 15:02:26','2017-10-12 12:34:27',NULL,'TEXT BY JACOPO CRIVELLI VISCONTI',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'text-by-jacopo-crivelli-visconti',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\n<br />\r\n*Now the shadow of the column – the column which supports the south-west corner of the roof – lengthens across the flagstones of the central part of the veranda, in front of the house where the chairs have been set out for the evening. Already the tip of the line of shadow almost touches the doorway which marks the centre of the façade. Against the west gable end of the house, the sun falls on the wood about a yard and a half above the flagstone. Through the third window, which looks out on this side, it would reach far into the bedroom if the blinds had not been lowered*.  \r\n\r\nThe prose of Alain Robbe-Grillet’s *Jealousy* (1957) transmits the uncanny feeling of a reverberating space, one that allegedly exists, but is turned into a fragmented illusion by Robbe-Grillet’s constant effort to describe it too meticulously. A good part of Robbe-Grillet’s screenplay for Alain Resnais’ *L’année dernière à Marienbad* (1961) is also dedicated to descriptions of places and things, but here the illusion is even greater, as the images also seem to deny (or at least not fully coincide with) what is being told. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIt might be possible, then, that the more precise a description tries to be, the more abstract, partial and misleading it becomes. On the other hand, it is often the case that the more dumb and closed in its concreteness an artwork seems to be, the more conceptually dense and direct it is. Just like ancient statues emerging from the tautological descriptions that abound in archaeology books, such works seem to aspire to merely “being there”, without leaving much room for metaphors and metonymies. But they constantly point at something else, lying elsewhere. They point at a specific place, but we don’t know where that place is.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n*Draped female figure, standing on a plinth of a roughly ellipsoid shape (length: 58 cm; depth: 36 cm; height: 13 cm). Lacks head and neck, right hand and front side of plinth. The figure is supported on the right leg, with the left leg drawn to the back, the left foot turning to the side*. [...] *The left arm bends at right angles, with the forearm crossing the body horizontally at the waist; the left hand is slightly lowered to the right hip, holding a spindle and distaff lightly against the body. The elbow of the right arm rests lightly on the left forearm at the wrist*.\r\n\r\nThe sun was slowly setting while we walked around the gymnasium at Salamis. Yellow flowers glowed in the high grass, surrounded by the high marble columns. It was getting cold. The place was totally silent, nobody was around. We stopped in front of the headless statue of a woman with her right arm folded and resting on her left wrist. It was the same pose as the woman’s in L’année dernière, the only difference being that the latter was sitting and holding a book in her right hand. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n*Two people sitting in a room. Silent. Nothing seemingly happens. They slightly change positions from time to time. Window. Room. Furniture. Action between the frames. And the light, between them, around them, over them*. [...] *If Ernie Gehr’s Eyes were a 19th-century “narrative”, these two people who are now sitting in Gehr’s room, no doubt, would be talking, exchanging some lines, performing, going through some psychological bits*. [...] *In a later 20th-century or early 21st-century film, which is where Gehr’s film is, the event is transposed to another level and we don’t give a damn about these people’s emotions or their characters. We are following completely something else, something that cannot be told in words but can be revealed only through certain rhythms of light...*\r\n\r\nThis is not an exhibition about Cyprus. Personal and subjective, it aims at recreating an atmosphere rather than directly addressing a place, a theme or a topic. The more objective a text tries to be, the more subjective it becomes. Maybe the only way to talk about Cyprus is to talk about *completely something else*, as this text tries to do. In other words, it is possible that by making a point of not addressing the subject directly, one will imperceptibly touch upon it, even if just for a moment.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThis text, and the exhibition it accompanies, are personal: they allude to things as I saw them, not necessarily as they are. For example, I noticed that in Nicosia, and throughout the island, the relation of people and things with the space that surrounds them is very specific, as if it were set on a different voltage from the one I experienced elsewhere. And I noticed that every time I asked how things got to be the way they are now, I received different answers, as if, inseparable from space, history was also constantly being negotiated. The thing in itself and its description or account appeared to me as inextricably linked, yet at the same time inevitably contradictory. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n*A rabbi, a real cabalist, once said that in order to establish the reign of peace it is not necessary to destroy everything nor to begin a completely new world. It is sufficient to displace this cup or this bush or this stone just a little, and thus everything. But this small displacement is so difficult to achieve and its measure is so difficult to find that, with regard to the world, humans are incapable of it and it is necessary that the Messiah come*. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nA small displacement can change everything, turn one world into another, completely different and yet exactly the same. None of us actually knows where to move the cup, the bush or the stone, or where it is they really belong. It is probably the same place ancient statues and some contemporary artworks point at, possibly near, but totally unknown, invisible to us. And despite that, we have all felt, at some point, that things were suddenly in the right position, inexplicably tuned to everything around them. And that something very tangible, material, even dull, like a stone, a feather or a lighter was the key that had once tuned the world and could eventually tune it again, by moving things just a little bit, by placing everything, at least for a moment, exactly where it should be.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe quotations are from: <br />\r\nAlain Robbe-Grillet, *La Jalousie* <br />\r\nVassos Karageorghis, *Sculptures from Salamis I* <br />\r\nJonas Mekas, *Movie Journal; The Rise of New American Cinema, 1959-1971* <br />\r\nGiorgio Agamben, La comunità che viene.',NULL),(460,1,'2017-04-07 09:16:22','2017-10-11 15:50:38',NULL,'TEXT BY MICHELANGELO CORSARO',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'text-by-michelangelo-corsaro',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\n<br />\r\nOne would be tempted to forget about wars, interethnic conflicts, refugees, borders, checkpoints and the holes left by bullets on the facade of Ledra Palace Hotel. In front of the sand, one would be tempted to speak of the sand, of its long journeys and of the cities, from North Africa, to the Middle-East, to the Southern coasts of Europe. But the journeys of the sand follow the same routes of the people fleeing wars, interethnic conflicts and poverty.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe first photograph in Socratis Socratous’ book, *The History of the War of Cyprus,* is an image of the southern slope of the Kyrenia mountain. To be precise, it is an image of the portion of the mountainside where an enormous flag of the self-declared Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus is painted in white and red - from Nicosia, the flag is visible also at night when it turns monochrome as hundreds of glowing lights reproduce the crescent and the star in-between two horizontal strips. <br />\r\n<br />\r\nIn the next page, a double spread hosts a photograph of a banner in the middle of a crop field reading ΟΧΙ, as part of the campaign to reject the Annan plan for the resolution of the Cyprus dispute. The third photo of the series represents a group of people queuing at a checkpoint on the Turkish-Cypriot side of the buffer zone. What follows is a series of photographs taken between 2003-2004, when Socratous visited for the first time the other side of the island: people, houses, ruins, cafes, abandoned places of a neighbouring *patrida* that for all of his life he had seen only from afar.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIn the next series of pictures, shot a couple of years later in 2006, a photo of a gorgeous landscape of dark green trees in a field of yellow grass seems to work as a picturesque intermission in the midst of a dense political commentary. In fact, the photograph does nothing else than continuing the political commentary, calling into question the very notion of national borders. In the middle of the image, three black triangles hang from gallows: it’s an insect trap, deployed to limit the spread of the red palm weevil, a parasite of palm trees that was possibly introduced to the island when some palms were imported from Egypt to Northern Cyprus in the attempt to give a more eastern and exotic touch to the landscape. The insects quickly spread on both sides of the island. After all, what do national borders mean to animals? <br />\r\n<br />\r\nA similar question was to be raised a few years later, when Socratous represented Cyprus at the 2009 Venice Biennale with *Rumours*, an exhibition composed of an installation and a series of performative actions. Here, Socratous invited two Indian snake charmers and their cobras to live in a venetian palazzo; he transported a ten-meter palm tree on a boat up and down the Canal Grande, in the attempt to eventually plant it somewhere on the island; he staged performances warning Venetians of potential snake invasions. The work commented on the rumours circulating on local news that some cobra eggs had been hid in the roots of the palm trees that Northern Cyprus imported from Egypt, and that once the eggs would hatch the cobras would be free to move to the south of the island. Once again, Socratous makes us think about how the checkpoints might be equipped to face a military invasion but not that of poisonous reptiles. But Socratous also resorts to narratives that seem to be deeply embedded in a very subjective gaze, insofar as he translates past traumas into a symbolic language that persists into a form of quasivisual political consciousness. How does Socratous transpose facts into symbols and into images? <br />\r\n<br />\r\nIn 2005 the artist installed a charcoal floor in Archimede Staffolini Gallery. The work was a black sculpture, titled *Illegal Installation*, on which people walked freely. It was the result of a research in the traditional coal industry of Pyrgos, a small town on the northern coast of Cyprus. Socratous knew the place because he had spent one year in Kokkina, a few kilometres away, during his military service. Kokkina is a territory of historical importance and a strategically valuable Northern Cyprus beachhead where in 1964, for days, Greek-Cypriot and Turkish- Cypriot factions engaged in violent fights. It was there that Socratous returned to collaborate with the local workers, asking them to work with him on the production of his piece. He provided the material that is generally used to build wooden floors and processed it into a charcoal pile to turn it into a sculptural installation. The whole production process weaves together different research threads: the experimentation with traditional production processes and techniques; the collaboration with workers from the workshops, who are asked to work with the artist and to produce objects in unorthodox ways; the desire to return to places and landscapes that are imbued with personal as much as with historical memories. <br />\r\n<br />\r\nOnce Socratous’ works are broken down into their constituent elements, it is possible to identify what unites them in their artistic methodology. Like words contain their history within their etymology, Socratous’ sculptures become legible as soon as we interrogate their genesis. How are we to separate, in theory and in practice, the artwork from the place where it is made, its affects, its memories, and its turmoil? Any attempt to establish hierarchies between the material and the conceptual would harm the complexity of Socratous’ practice; to speak of symbolism or of sheer beauty would be reductive. What is truly eloquent here is -instead- the identity of the artwork. <br />\r\n<br />\r\nIn 2011 the artist produced a large aluminium and bronze piece titled *Module of Urban Landscape*. The metal for the sculpture was obtained from discarded shells and ammunitions used in the Libian Civil War, purchased at an auction in Cyprus and then melted together by the artist. In a second installation of the piece, exhibited in 2015 at Galerie Saint-Severin, Paris, Socratous added bullets and ammunitions, confiscated from a Syrian ship and stocked in Cyprus. Looking at Socratous’ sculptures, it is difficult to ignore the time he spends in industrial workshops, which become a place for reflection, where the thinking is done. Some of the ammunitions exhibited in Paris happened to bear the etched words “Made in France” or “Made in Belgium” and this is no accident but rather the outcome of political, cultural and economic relations that are embedded in the very choice of the materials employed. The workshops are the places where such observations are first made, where the materials are handled, weighted and engaged. Here, Socratous gets to know the metal, its structure and its consistency, but also the workplace, the people, and their histories, moulding all this information together into the identity of his sculptures. The artist developed a collaborative practice of his own so as to produce these works, moving from one workshop to another, asking for hospitality and for help while granted licence to alter their normal working routine. It is in workshops that collaboration becomes itself a research strategy, to learn traditional techniques or to revise them as needed.  <br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe same could be said for almost all of Socratous’ most recent production. The works from the series *Stolen Garden* (2009-ongoing) are made using mainly two techniques: traditional metal casting for the bigger pieces and microsculpture for the smaller parts that need jewelry techniques. These works are realised in three Athenian workshops, where for years Socratous returned to work adopting them as some of his many studios. The inspiration for these works comes from the National Gardens of Athens, an island of peace and quiet in the middle of a hectic city. The park was commissioned in 1838 by Queen Amalia of Oldenburg to Friedrich Schmidt, a German agronomist who designed the garden with hundreds of exotic plants that he tried to introduce into the dry Mediterranean climate of Athens, in many cases unsuccessfully. Amalia, who commissioned the garden to be built next to the Royal Palace, was born in Germany and became the first Queen of modern Greece when in 1936 she married King Otto of Greece. One year after surviving an assassination attempt, her regency ended, in 1862, when the King dismissed his Prime Minister provoking a military rebellion. The Queen left Greece on a British warship and returned to her home in Bavaria where she died in exile. In such a historically loaded place Socratous wandered among native and exotic species of plants, looking at forms and shapes to produce his sculptures and reflecting on the character of a city that for two centuries has been contended between the West and the Middle-East, between European Standards and exoticism. The result is a tangle of metal branches and leaves, often installed directly on the floor or on low plinths. Their appearance is diverse, according to the techniques used to produce them: the gold-plated parts are shiny, when the copper is treated in long chemical baths with electricity it takes warty forms, some bronze trunks and leaves bear an opaque patina.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nSocratous’ sand casts add another variant to his vocabulary of materials. Exhibited for the first time at Point Centre, Nicosia, in the exhibition Casts of an Island, these objects are obtained by casting fine sand in moulds and cooking it at high temperatures. The result is an unfamiliar material as light as plastic and as fragile as glass, of which Socratous determines hues, textures and forms. The objects are rendered in the colour of the old buildings erected in both the north and the south of Nicosia, which is the colour of Cyprus when in the summer the soil is dry and the fields turn yellow. The shapes of these sculptures are reminiscent of industrial machinery, engines, pipes and tools, of Mycenaean pottery, of medieval bastions, of the Great Mosque of Samarra, and of the tower of Gonbad-e Qabus. Sometimes, where the edges split off, they assume jagged shapes dictated by contingencies, like islands, mountains, and broken things. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAmong the images consulted by Socratous during the making of these works there is some satellite footage of a sandstorm covering the entire Middle-East, from Egypt, to Israel, Palestine, Jordan, Syria, to the southern border of Turkey. In this photo, Cyprus is almost invisible, cloaked as it is by a thick ochre plume of sand‑to gauge the shape and position of the island one should have in mind an exact representation of its map, for having seen it too many times. To locate the island on the map, to ask “where is Cyprus?” means to raise another question: on which criteria can we base a clear distinction between Europe and the Middle-East?\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n In a paper republished in 2006 in Global Media Journal, Yiannis Papadakis noted how, after the Republic of Cyprus joined the European Union in 2004 “the Dead Zone became the easternmost border of the EU, a problematic boundary that has not allowed the EU to precisely delimit itself in the East.” (1) That of precise territorial delimitations seems to be one of the motives that haunts Socratous’ practice. At once a Cypriot, an Athenian, and a European citizen from the Middle-East, his artistic practice cannot but return where the borders are not understood. Hence the obsession for the red palm weevil, for the cobras, for the refugees, and for the parrots that escaped their cages to find a new home in the National Garden of Athens. Contended as they are between East and West, between sand beaches and the hectic premises of a metal foundry, it would be pointless to ask “where do these works belong?” They materialise a mental place in a cast of sand.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n(1). Yiannis Papadakis. Nicosia after 1960: A river, a bridge and a dead zone. *Global Media Journal, Mediterranean Edition*, 1(1). (2006). p.13.',NULL),(461,1,'2017-04-07 09:23:58','2017-10-12 12:22:40',NULL,'PERPETUAL PROLOGUE',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'perpetual-prologue',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\nSea turns into mountain. Earth plates collide. The one subdues underneath the other. Rock masses detach, they shift, rotate and attach together again in new formations. Magma veins fill the void of the tectonic displacements with the Earth’s melted mantle. Flowing into the atmosphere through the cracks, the fluid rock creates mountains that look alike the skin of serpents. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nSo much is shared between terrains and bodies. Resembling rocks, bone structures are formed by the crystallization of minerals, by the hardening of collagen and calcium around entrapped cells, producing composite matrixes of organic and inorganic matter. Bones entangled in the soil. Relatives. An embrace. \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nStones build cities and adorn them. Tree trunks induced the morphology of columns. Their roots inspired the rhizomatic infrastructures of water distribution. The metabolic mechanism of their leaves incited the crystalline systems that digest the sun into electrical energy. Seen from above, cities look like mosaics. \r\n<br /> \r\n<br />\r\nBooks crafted from tree mass. Recordings and representations inscribed on vegetal substance. Attempts to both sustain and reconcile the impulse for abstraction. Museums are like books, conditioning the distance between subject and object through archives, taxonomies and inscriptions. Displayed behind glass showcases, opened books claim the possibility to speak for themselves. Books are like museums.\r\nTranslation of everything that is common. The modeling of weather and finance, the simulation of physical dynamics and biological emergence, the transcoding of material and intangible memory. Computational networks originating from the ground, yet acting as clouds. \r\nHow things speak to each other? Sites of identification and mediation, of recognition and difference. Instruments of linkage and partition. Faces and interfaces. Masks bridging thresholds, pointing towards alternate states. Performing the transformations of identity and the hybridisation of time. The orality of myth encoded in skins and surfaces. The return of any gaze in perpetual loop. ',NULL),(462,0,'2017-04-07 10:08:16','2017-10-12 10:54:39',NULL,'XARKIS DISCUSSION',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'xarkis-discussion',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\nPress Release\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nWe are pleased to invite you to take part in a discussion we are organising entitled *Activating sustainability for cultural & educational organizations*. This is an open discussion with Cypriot cultural and educational organisations, which will take place this Thursday, October 20 at 18.30 at the Point Centre for Contemporary Art in Nicosia.\r\n<br />\r\nThe discussion intends to highlight Cypriot organisations\' creative initiatives and ways that viable NGOs, institutions and centres of innovation can be structured, particularly in relation to the arts, culture and design. The discussion will bring together questions such as: How can useful proposals be maintained as well as a lasting, collaborative relationship, two way communication and support between local cultural production and the wider society? The presentation of aspects and challenges in terms of activism within the Cypriot cultural production, is also a key aim of this discussion.\r\n<br />\r\nIn this context, there will be presentations that will include a few words about the vision, mission, objectives and journey of each organisation, as well as an articulation of the main challenges being faced. After the presentations there will be an open discussion.\r\n<br />\r\n*This talk will be in English.\r\n<br />\r\nThe discussion will include the following NGO and Foundation representatives:\r\nMarios Epaminondas from Association for Historical Dialogue & Research (AHDR) and Home For Cooperation <br />\r\nClaudia Konyalian from Urban Gorillas <br />\r\nAchilleas Kentonis from ARTos Cultural and Research Foundation <br />\r\nChristina Skarpari from Xarkis\r\n',NULL),(463,0,'2017-04-07 10:13:17','2017-10-12 15:49:54',NULL,'XARKIS',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'xarkis',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\nInfo\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n[Xarkis](http://xarkis.org/en/) is an NGO, aiming to inspire Cypriots view themselves in a new, positive light. In essence, this is a rebranding project for a socially sustainable Cyprus. Its name comes from the ancient Greek word eksarhis, which means from the beginning. \r\n<br />\r\nXarkis envisages a Cypriot citizenry that is active, participatory and socially engaged. It recognizes, as others do as well, that a large portion of citizens today are passive, consumerist and individualistic. Xarkis wants to work with, collaborate and facilitate any team or individual with the same urge for social change. It organises the annual festival [Xarkis Festival]().\r\n',NULL),(464,0,'2017-04-07 11:18:41','2017-10-12 15:50:15',NULL,'PLANTING THE SENSORIUM',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'planting-the-sensorium',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\nA continuous series of Performances by Nicolina Stylianou <br />\r\n<br />\r\nSaturday 22 October 2016, 20:00 | Point Centre for Contemporary Art\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nPress Release\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nDoes the past experiences influence my psychological condition? Am I just a residue of the past? and if I am, what type of deep communications, the human existence may be experiencing?\r\n\r\nThe drive of being in a constant communication with my body, mind and spirit can create different thought compositions and many bodily experiences. Through performance art my body is asking questions that can only be answered when one feels into certain sensory experiences and perhaps interact with them.\r\n\r\nIn the mode of communicating with the viewers senses, environment and state of mind, the body keeps questioning and interact. At the center of the creative thought process, the core issue deals with the interaction and meeting with people. What appears to be known; counteracts with the ‘opposite’ in the face of others. This core is in a constant development and the threads may be synchronized with another. In a silent state of mind, these vibrations are identified through external or internal sequences that can be identified usually through a temporary sensation in the environment.\r\n\r\nWriting about thought compositions while a core sensation of the Performer keeps anoticeablevibration is like creating a moment to engage on another frequency; the body receives and shares as a tuning channel. What interests me is turning into these frequencies, emphasizing their affect on my own body within the action. My own sense experience hovers on the acute level of sensory perceptions. Like penetrating a broken wall to reach the manifestation of the meeting of two people.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nCredits: <br />\r\nConcept/Performance: Nicolina Stylianou <br />\r\nTechnical Support: Stelios Andreou <br />\r\nDesign/Constructional assiduity: Marios Messios <br />\r\n\r\n',NULL),(465,0,'2017-04-07 11:37:38','2017-10-12 14:26:30',NULL,'NICOLINA STYLIANOU',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'nicolina-stylianou',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\nBio\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n[Nicolina Stylianou]( www.nicolinastylianou.com) studied Art & Design at Kingston University, UK. \r\nSelected performances include *]performance s p a c e[*, London; [*GRADIENT: From Gray to Colour Scale*]( https://www.facebook.com/events/253860184810177/), Ioannina, Greece, both in 2015; *Transmission of the triangle*; *Growth*, both in 2014; *Abbey of Silence*, 2013. During 2014, she has also participated in Xarkis Festival in Arsos, Cyprus and has worked in different television series and theatrical plays in Cyprus as a scenographer. She is the founder and curator at [*Sensorium Space*](www.sensoriumspace.com).  \r\n\r\n',NULL),(466,0,'2017-04-20 09:53:17','2017-10-17 15:21:28',NULL,'TO BRING BACK THE WORLD TO THE WORLD, 2012',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'to-bring-back-the-world-to-the-world-2012',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\n35 mm film projection, 39’55’’ + 19 frames <br />\r\n(screenings at the Zena Palace on December 3) <br />\r\n<br />\r\nFor *To Bring Back the World to the World*, Panayiotou takes off-screen space and absence to an extreme by projecting a black monochrome picture that runs 38 minutes, 55 seconds, and 19 frames. The title is a reformulation of the slogan used by the Lumière brothers, inventors of the cinematograph, and is thus a direct reference to the way they conceived the medium. Panayiotou radically rejects all representation and narrative, the main engines of today’s movies. The dark void of *To Bring Back the World to the World* is itself derived from one of the mainstays of the mainstream cinema, namely the “black frames” that punctuate Walt Disney’s *Mary Poppins* (1964). The film is assembled by adding up all of the black frames, which refer to all the interstices of an image sequence, generally projected at 24 frames per second. It is the rapid succession of these frames that produces the illusion of an animated sequence. By using the interstices as such, the sequence is reduced to a black monochrome. Like off-screen action in the moves, the absence of pictures gives free rein to an unrestricted imagination.\r\n',NULL),(467,1,'2017-05-30 23:55:09','2017-05-30 23:55:09',NULL,'THE LISTENING GROUP',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'the-listening-group',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(468,1,'2017-06-04 21:31:38','2017-06-04 21:56:28',NULL,'POINTâ€“ELENEIO: MAGIC CARPET',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'point-eleneio-exhibition-magic-carpet',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(469,1,'2017-10-11 11:58:39','2017-10-13 11:40:17',1,'POLINA NIKOLAOU',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'polina-nikolaou',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\nBio\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n[Polina Nikolaou](http://polinanikolaou.com/) (b. 1986, Cyprus) holds a BA in History from University of Athens, an MA in Landscape and Culture from University of Nottingham, UK, and a PhD in Historical/Cultural Geography and Museology from University of Exeter, UK, entitled *The diaspora of Cypriot antiquities and the British Museum, 1860-1900*. \r\nShe is a museum and cultural heritage consultant with scholarly outputs (articles and conference presentations) on the history of (Cypriot) archaeology. \r\n\r\nHer work has two interrelated strands: academic research and public history. Her current research interests focus on the conceptual and historical aspects of the relationship between knowledge, space and antiquities. Her work on public history is founded on the notion of cultural heritage as a continuous and inclusive process of constructing and reconstructing material culture. \r\n',NULL),(470,1,'2017-10-11 14:39:54','2017-10-11 14:43:04',NULL,'ZÃ–E DOMINIQUE SUTHERLAND',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'zÃ¶e-dominique-sutherland',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br /> \r\nBio \r\n<br /> \r\n<br /> \r\nZöe Dominique Sutherland living in UK,  holds a BA in Continental Philosophy from Middlesex University, UK, an MA in Analytic Philosophy from King\'s College London, and a DPhil entitled *The Phenomenology of Conceptual Art* from Sussex University, UK. She is a Senior Lecturer of Philosophy at Brighton University, UK. \r\n \r\nSutherland\'s [research interests](https://brighton.academia.edu/ZoeDominiqueSutherland) include contemporary artistic practices, the politics of aesthetics, feminist theory and continental philosophy.',NULL),(471,1,'2017-10-12 11:58:53','2017-10-18 10:00:44',NULL,'EFTYCHIOS SAVVIDIS',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'eftychios-savvidis',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\nBio \r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nEftychios Savvidis (b. 1988, Cyprus) holds a BA & MArch in Architecture from the School of Architecture of the National Technical University of Athens, Greece and an MA in Architecture & Historic Urban Environments from the Bartlett School of Architecture of UCL. \r\n\r\nSavvidis has worked as an architect in Greece and Spain. His projects investigate the spatial implication of the intersectionality between past, present and future and often engage with the confrontation of the traditionally established concepts of monumentality, heritage and archaeology.\r\n',NULL),(472,1,'2017-10-12 12:01:03','2017-10-18 10:00:50',NULL,'CHARALAMPOS IOANNOU',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'charalampos-ioannou',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\nBio \r\n<br />\r\nCharalampos Ioannou (b. 1988, Cyprus) is a qualified architect and holds a M.Arch in Architecture from National Technical University of Athens School of Architecture.\r\n\r\nIoannou works as a visual designer at the [Science and Technology in Archaeology Research Center]( https://www.cyi.ac.cy/index.php/starc/about-the-center/center-overview.html) of the Cyprus Institute. He is involved in research projects which deal with the history and complexity of the city and make an effort to analyse and visualize them through new technologies such as Virtual Reality.\r\n\r\n',NULL),(473,1,'2017-10-12 12:15:15','2017-10-18 10:43:06',NULL,'PETROS MORIS',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'petros-moris',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\nBio\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n[Petros Moris](http://petrosmoris.com/) (b. 1986, Greece) studied at the Athens School of Fine Arts, Greece, and received an MFA in Curating from Goldsmiths University, UK. He is currently a PhD researcher in the Department of Architecture at the University of Thessaly, Greece.\r\n\r\nMoris has presented his work in solo projects at Duve, Berlin, Germany; Union Pacific, London, UK, both in 2014; Project Native Informant, London; SPACE, London, UK, both in 2013, and was nominated for the [Deste Prize 2015]( http://deste.gr/deste-prize/deste-prize-2015/). As a member of the art collective KERNEL and the curatorial projects SIM and Radical Reading, he has curated shows and panels at the Athens Biennial 2011; the Chisenhale Gallery, UK; the Whitechapel Gallery, UK, and at Circuits and Currents, Greece.',NULL),(474,1,'2017-10-12 12:45:12','2017-10-18 10:57:19',NULL,'MARIO GARCIA TORRES',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'mario-garcia-torres',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\nBio\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nMario García Torres (b. 1975, Mexico) holds a BA in Fine Arts from University of Monterrey, Mexico and an MA in Fine Arts from California Institute of the Arts, USA. \r\n\r\nSolo exhibitions of his work have been, among others, held at Stedelijk Museum, Amsterdam, Netherlands; Kunsthalle Zürich, Zurich, Switzerland; Wattis Institute for Contemporary Arts, San Fransisco, USA; Museo Nacional Centro de Arte Reina Sofia, Madrid, Spain; Museo Madre, Naples, Italy; Hammer Museum, Los Angeles, USA, and Modern Art Museum of Forth Worth, Texas, USA.',NULL),(475,1,'2017-10-12 12:47:34','2017-10-18 11:03:01',NULL,'JOAO MARIA GUSMAO & PEDRO PAIVA',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'joao-maria-gusmao-pedro-paiva',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br /> \r\nBio \r\n<br /> \r\n<br /> \r\nJoão Maria Gusmão (b. 1979, Lisbon, Portugal) and Pedro Paiva (b. 1977, Portugal) have been collaborating since 2001. As an artistic duo they produce “poetic philosophical fictions” using the mediums of film, sculpture, photograph, installation and anthologies of texts. They have also published a philosophical journal, entitled *Efluvio Magnetico*.  \r\n\r\nSolo exhibitions of their work have been, among others, held at Fundação Eva Klabin, Rio de Janeiro, Brazil; Haus der Künst, Munich, Germany; Aargauer Kunsthaus, Aaru, Germany; KW Institute for Contemporary Art, Berlin, Germany; REDCAT, Los Angeles, USA; Camden Arts Centre, London, UK, and Le Plateau, Paris, France. They participated at the Gwangju Biennale, 2010; Manifesta, 2008 and the Sao Paulo Biennale, 2006.   Together they represented Portugal at the 53rd Venice Biennale in 2009 and also took part in the 55th Venice Biennale in 2013.  ',NULL),(476,1,'2017-10-12 12:50:56','2017-10-18 10:50:27',NULL,'DANIEL STEEGMANN MANGRANE',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'daniel-steegmann-mangrane',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br /> \r\nBio \r\n<br />  \r\n[Daniel Steegmann Mangrané](http://www.danielsteegmann.info/) (b. 1977, Spain) studied at the Escola de disseny i art and the Gris ART School of Photography, both in Barcelona. \r\n \r\nSolo exhibitions of his work have been held at Esther Schipper, Berlin, Germany; New Museum, New York, USA; CRAC Centre Rhénan d\'Art Contemporain, Alsace, Altkirch, France; Casa França Brasil, Rio de Janeiro, Brazil, and Uma Certa Falta de Coerência, Porto, Portugal, amongst others. He is one of the organisers of the experimental school Universidade de Verão at Capacete, Rio de Janeiro. Mangrané has been nominated for the [PIPA Prize for Latin American artists](http://www.pipaprize.com/pag/daniel-steegmann-mangrane/) in 2012, 2013 and 2014 and has received numerous prizes and fellowships. ',NULL),(477,1,'2017-10-12 13:29:03','2017-10-18 10:11:11',NULL,'NIKOLAS BAKIRTZIS',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'nikolas-bakirtzis',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\nBio\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nNikolas Bakirtzis holds a BA in Archaeology and an MA in Social Anthropology from the Aristotle University, Thessaloniki, Greece and received his PhD in Art and Architectural History from Princeton University. \r\n\r\nHe is Associate Professor and Director of the Doctoral Program in [Science and Technology in Cultural Heritage]( https://www.cyi.ac.cy/index.php/starc/about-the-center/center-overview.html) at the Cyprus Institute. \r\nBakirtzis has been awarded a Dumbarton Oaks Junior Fellowship, a Whiting Fellowship in the Humanities and has been a Resident Fellow at the Research Center for Anatolian Civilizations of Koc University, Istanbul (2005-2006), and Mellon Postdoctoral Fellow and Lecturer in Columbia University’s Department of Art History and Archaeology (2006-2008). He was awarded a Marie Curie International Reintegration Grant by the European Commission. In 2013 he was Visiting Research Fellow at the Seeger Center for Hellenic Studies at Princeton University, and in the 2015 summer term he joined Columbia University’s Global Program in Istanbul as Visiting Faculty. In Spring 2016 he was [Getty Guest Scholar]( http://www.getty.edu/research/scholars/years/2015-2016.html) at the Getty Research Institute in Los Angeles.\r\n',NULL),(478,1,'2017-10-12 13:32:53','2017-10-12 13:32:53',NULL,'CATALOGUE',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'catalogue',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(479,1,'2017-10-12 13:36:46','2017-10-16 10:23:59',NULL,'ZOE DOMINIQUE SUTHERLAND',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'zoe-dominique-sutherland',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br /> \r\nBio \r\n<br /> \r\n<br /> \r\nDr [Zöe Dominique Sutherland](https://brighton.academia.edu/ZoeDominiqueSutherland) holds a BA in Continental Philosophy from Middlesex University, UK, an MA in Analytic Philosophy from King\'s College London, and a DPhil entitled *The Phenomenology of Conceptual Art* from Sussex University, UK. She is a Senior Lecturer of Philosophy at Brighton University, UK. \r\n \r\nSutherland\'s research interests include contemporary artistic practices, the politics of aesthetics, feminist theory and continental philosophy.',NULL),(480,1,'2017-10-12 16:08:16','2017-10-12 16:22:37',3,'ABY WARBURG',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'warburgian',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br/>\r\n\r\n[...] Aby Warburg’s main achievements are the widening of the field of art history to include all types of artifacts and the transformation of the preexisting study of styles and schools into a transculturally oriented historical discipline. He called this discipline Kulturwissenschaft (science of culture), himself a Bildhistoriker (image historian), and his method iconology: literally a combination of the study of word and image that relied on merging a historical with a meta-historical approach to various forms of visual expression. Warburg’s pioneering meta-historical turn of the study of art owed much to contemporaneous psychology, anthropology, and the analysis of religious beliefs. At the same time, he promoted a historical turn that relied on close attention to the political and social ramifications of culture. Warburg thus combined the evolutionist theory of his days with a positivistic study of historical documents. After focusing first on the Italian Renaissance, he turned his attention to the German Reformation and to the subsequent scientific revolution. Crucial times of crisis, he believed, had activated an evolution of thinking toward the Enlightenment, although any human being maintained the potential for regression to irrational behavior. Enlightenment as a remaking of Classical Antiquity—both intellectual and material—was, according to Warburg, achievable only through a necessary balance between individual experience and the perception of generally comprehensible abstracted “symbolic” forms. Such forms, he believed, were coined in archaic times and peaked in Classical Antiquity. Subsequently all his studies were dedicated at a phenomenon that he called the Nachleben der Antike (Afterlife of Antiquity).\r\n\r\n<br/>\r\nOxford Bibliographys',NULL),(481,1,'2017-10-12 18:02:41','2017-10-12 18:06:26',NULL,'INDIAN SNAKE CHARMER',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'indian-snake-chramer',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(482,1,'2017-10-16 14:29:02','2017-10-16 14:29:02',NULL,'APARTAMENTO',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'apartamento',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(483,1,'2017-10-17 10:37:58','2017-10-17 10:37:58',NULL,'PHENOMENOLOGY AND THE ARTS SEMINARS',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'phenomenology-and-the-arts-seminars',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\nDates of seminars\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nFirst Seminar: 13 February 2016 <br />\r\n[Second Seminar](https://vimeo.com/234443347): 27 February 2016 <br />\r\nThird Seminar: 12 March 2016 <br />\r\nFourth Seminar: 19 March 2016 <br />\r\nFifth Seminar: 26 March 2016 <br />\r\nGuest speaker: Zöe Dominique Sutherland: 16 April 2016 <br />\r\nGuest speaker: Suzan Kozel: 27 May 2016 <br />\r\n\r\n',NULL),(484,1,'2017-10-17 10:46:28','2017-10-17 10:46:28',NULL,'ANDREAS VRAHIMIS',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'andreas-vrahimis',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<br />\r\nBio\r\n\r\n[Andreas Vrahimis](https://www.academia.edu/search/advanced/?q=Andreas%20Vrahimis) (b. 1983, Cyprus) holds a PhD in Philosophy from Birkbeck, University of London, an MA from Goldsmiths College, University of London, and a BA (Hons) from the University of Nottingham. \r\n\r\nHe has taught at the University of Cyprus, the Cyprus University of Technology and European University Cyprus, and has held an Honorary Research Fellowship at Birkbeck, University of London. He is the author of [*Encounters between Analytic and Continental Philosophy*](http://www.palgrave.com/la/book/9781137290199) (Palgrave, 2013), and his work has been published in *Mind*, the *British Journal for the History of Philosophy* and the *International Journal for Philosophical Studies*, among others.\r\n',NULL);
